<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PanamaCocaine 1stLd-Writethru a0867 10-20 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama Cocaine, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0867,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Convicted In Cocaine Military Mailing Scheme</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Oscar and ..., to CORRECT Mrs. Thom's
hometown to New York City, sted Doerun, Ga.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court jury Wednesday convicted
four people of conspiracy to import cocaine in a scheme involving
the use of military mail to ship the drug from Panama to the United
States.
   The jury, which deliberated about five hours Wednesday, convicted
   Oscar and Regina Smith and Julia Thom, all of New York City, and
Gary King of Doerun, Ga., were convicted after about five hours of
jury deliberations. All four face up to life in prison and $4
million in fines.
   U.S. District Judge J. Robert Elliott set no sentencing date.
   Prosecutors said the four were involved in a drug ring that
shipped 352 pounds of cocaine to the United States between early
1987 and May of this year.
   ``Obviously, we're pleased,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Deborah Fowler after the verdict was read. ``We believe the jury
spoke.''
   The alleged conspiracy was discovered when Jackie Lee Bigelow of
Moultrie was arrested in Colquitt County for a traffic violation
and police discovered 17 pounds of cocaine in the trunk of his
girlfriend's car.
   Bigelow, a former soldier, pleaded guilty and testified for the
prosecution. Authorities claim 42 pounds of cocaine were mailed to
some of Bigelow's friends from military post offices in Panama.
   Frank Martin, who represented Oscar Smith, said the sheer volume
of the drug, which was shown to jurors, probably helped sway their
decision.
   ``It was just too much cocaine to overcome,'' Martin said. ``I
think it was such a shocking amount that the jury couldn't focus on
other issues.''
   Prosecutors told the jury that duffel bags stuffed with cocaine
also were flown to air bases in Georgia, Texas and Maryland from
Howard Air Force Base in Panama.
   The couriers were either current or former soldiers who used
false military ID cards, wore their old uniforms and carried forged
leave papers to board military flights, prosecutors said.
   The defendants were charged with a variety of criminal counts,
including conspiracy to possess cocaine with intent to distribute.
   Smith, the alleged mastermind, was convicted on 19 of 20 counts,
including conspiracy to import cocaine, use of the mail to
facilitate a drug felony and possession with intent to distribute.
   Mrs. Smith, his wife, was convicted of four counts, including
use of a telephone to facilitate a drug felony.
   King was convicted of three counts, including possession with
intent to distribute and interstate transportation in aid of
racketeering.
   Mrs. Thom, who was arrested with Mrs. Smith at a Moultrie motel
last May, was convicted on one count of conspiracy to possess
cocaine with intent to distribute.
   Mrs. Smith told officers who arrested her that she made the trip
to Moultrie because she was having an affair with Bigelow. Mrs.
Thom said she thought she was traveling to Georgia to pick up Mrs.
Smith's niece for a return trip to New York.
   Bigelow and John Turner, a military reservist from Nashville,
Tenn., have pleaded guilty to one count each, but three major
figures in the case remain free because the government has not been
able to bring them out of Panama.
   Ms. Fowler identified them last week as Faustino Lee, an alleged
paymaster at the New York end of the cocaine connection, and Alex
Smith and Ricardo Brown, described as key figures in the ring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
