<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DrugBill 1stLd-Writethru a0830 10-20 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0830,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Fashioning Compromise Drug Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with agreement on some provisions.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A compromise anti-drug bill began to take
shape Wednesday night as more than 20 House-Senate negotiators
agreed to major law enforcement provisions.
   The lawmakers, however, were unable to agree on how to carry out
provisions to deny many federal benefits to those convicted of drug
offenses.
   While there was no doubt that denial of benefits would remain in
the bill, disagreement remained over whether judges should have
discretion in removing the benefits _ or should be required to
withdraw the assistance upon conviction.
   The drug bill, expected to authorize about $2.5 billion in new
spending, is the major legislation keeping Congress in session. The
top House and Senate leadership was expected to resolve the
remaining issues Thursday and, hopefully, schedule final passage on
Friday.
   Each house has overwhelmingly approved different versions of the
popular election-year legislation, which also will include the
death penalty for those who kill during drug crimes.
   One of the most controversial House-approved measures was
dropped. It would have permitted introduction in federal court of
evidence seized illegally, but in ``good faith'' _ even when a
search was made without a warrant. Current law permits the ``good
faith'' exception only when searches are conducted with warrants.
   The negotiators accepted Senate language on child pornography.
The provisions would set prison terms of 20 years-to-life for
anyone convicted of facilitating use of a child for producing
sexually explicit materials.
   The buying and selling of children for the purpose of producing
child pornography would be made a federal crime.
   The negotiators failed to agree on Senate provisions to
strengthen adult anti-obscenity laws, and threw that issue to House
and Senate leaders.
   The bill would require the Justice Department to devise a system
that would allow gun dealers to check whether gun purchasers are
convicted felons _ a provision originally inserted by the House to
replace an optional seven-day waiting period on handgun sales.
   Lawmakers agreed that states would initially have to contribute
25 percent of the cost to receive federal grants for anti-drug
crime programs. After the first year of the four-year program, the
state match would go to 50 percent.
   Senate language that 10 percent of federal anti-crime grants go
for street-level enforcement was dropped, and the decision would be
left to the states.
   The final bill also will include civil fines for those found in
possession of illegal drugs, including marijuana and cocaine.
</TEXT>
