<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CaliforniaAIDS     10-20 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-California AIDS,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Tax Rebel Seeks Sweeping Changes In AIDS Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Gann, who a decade ago helped
lead this state's revolt against high taxes, is crusading against a
far deadlier foe this November: AIDS, the disease from which he
himself is suffering.
   California law currently prohibits most mandatory AIDS virus
testing and requires that voluntary test results be kept
confidential.
   But Gann, who contracted AIDS in 1982 from a blood transfusion,
is a chief sponsor of Proposition 102, which would eliminate the
statewide anonymous AIDS testing program, allow insurers and
employers to screen prospective clients and workers, and require
health officials to do everything ``reasonably necessary'' to halt
the epidemic, including tracing the contacts of anyone exposed to
the AIDS virus.
   The measure would also make it a felony for anyone who knows
they have acquired immune deficiency syndrome to donate blood or
engage in prostitution.
   State health authorities and other critics insist current
policies are effective. And they warn that AIDS victims and people
who test positive for the AIDS virus could be subjected to housing
and employment discrimination, job loss and other abuses if voters
approve Proposition 102.
   But Gann dismissed those objections at a recent legislative
hearing: ``They (opponents) want to make AIDS a civil rights issue,
but who in God's name has the right to go out and give you a virus
that's going to kill you _ not maybe kill you, but kill you?''
   As part of his campaign, Gann this week called for a boycott of
Wells Fargo Bank because the bank contributed $5,000 to opponents
of the initiative.
   ``They're (the bank) afraid they'll be boycotted by the gay
community,'' Gann told reporters Tuesday, though he could not
provide proof that any boycott had been threatened.
   Wells Fargo spokeswoman Kim Kellogg said the boycott would
probably not be effective. She added that the bank and other
corporations are opposing the initiative because they don't like
it, not out of fear of a boycott.
   A second, more moderate AIDS initiative on Nov. 8 ballots would
allow some mandatory AIDS testing and limited release of test
results.
   Proposition 102's other chief sponsor is U.S. Rep. William
Dannemeyer, a conservative Republican.
   Critics including the California Medical Association, the
California Nurses Association, health officers and numerous AIDS
researchers argue that Proposition 102 would drain support for
programs that have already proven effective in combating the
epidemic, including research, education and voluntary testing.
   Public opinion polls reveal that voter support for Proposition
102 dropped from more than 70 percent early in the campaign to 36
percent by early October as critics have gotten their message out.
   Opponents compare Proposition 102 to two previous ballot
measures sponsored by political extremist Lyndon LaRouche. Those
initiatives, which also enjoyed strong initial support, were
overwhelmingly defeated by voters in 1986 and earlier this year.
But opponents concede their battle is more difficult this time
without LaRouche's name attached to the proposal.
   Health officials argue they can, with consent, trace partners
and other contacts of AIDS victims and people who test positive for
the virus.
   The second AIDS-related measure, Proposition 96, was designed by
Los Angeles County Sheriff Sherman Block to help protect rape
victims and law enforcement officials who fear they may have been
exposed to AIDS or other communicable diseases.
   If approved, rape victims and public safety officers could
request mandatory AIDS testing of individuals charged with certain
crimes or involved in an assault on police, firefighters or
emergency medical personnel.
   Supporters call the measure a ``victim's rights'' initiative.
   But critics including the president of the Health Officers'
Association of California fear inmates who have been exposed to
AIDS may be mistreated if test results are reported.
   They also point out that AIDS tests are not a foolproof means of
detecting exposure to the virus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Westlake     10-20 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Westlake,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Three Decades, Seattle's Westlake Center Opens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 30 years of committees, proposals and no
small amount of bickering, a downtown center opens this week giving
Seattle a combination town square, office tower, shopping arcade,
bus station and monorail terminal.
   ``That's a minor miracle,'' says Stephen Koehler, president of
Koehler McFayden & Co. of Seattle, one of the project's
co-developers.
   ``There's so many people and so many ideas of what was going to
go into the small space called Westlake, that it's really
impossible to make all the people happy about this. But I think the
overwhelming majority will like what's here.''
   What's here is a 24-story office building, a five-story shopping
and restaurant pavilion and a one-acre city plaza on a roughly
triangular wedge in the middle of the city's retail district. It's
a compromise of three decades of discussions, lawsuits, civic
commissions and studies over what to do with one of the few open
spaces left in Seattle's core.
   ``It's been such a controversial project for so long, I'm just
kind of glad it's done,'' says Mayor Charles Royer.
   Westlake Center was formally opening today amid speeches, bands,
doves and 50,000 balloons.
   Koehler McFayden and The Rouse Co., the Columbia, Md., developer
of such projects as New York's South Street Seaport and Baltimore's
Harborplace, built the $110 million office and shopping complex. It
adjoins the $18.9 million Westlake Park, paved in multi-colored
granite to resemble a Salish Indian basketweave pattern.
   The center's lower level opens to a station of a bus tunnel to
be completed next year. The third floor is the terminus for the
one-mile monorail ride to Seattle Center, site of the 1962 world's
fair.
   Westlake, at the junction of Westlake Avenue, Pine Street and
Fifth Avenue, has long been a place to find flower vendors, hear
street musicians and political speeches, and to duck out of the
rain beneath the old monorail terminal.
   It's also a place to shop. Bordering are large department
stores. A few blocks away is the Pike Place Market, a collection of
fresh fish and vegetable stalls, bakeries, espresso cafes and
open-air entrepreneurs.
   Since the 1950s, when the city closed a two-block stretch of
Westlake Avenue, the site has been the focus for big plans.
Proposals have included a pedestrian mall, a hotel-shopping
complex, a home for the Seattle Art Museum and a central city park.
   Downtown merchants wanted to attract shoppers. Open-space
advocates, including the late Victor Steinbrueck, an architect who
battled to save the Pike Market, wanted a central plaza, a ``living
room'' for the city.
   Steinbrueck, head of the Committee for Alternatives at Westlake,
led a successful legal fight to block a plan by Royer to locate the
art museum at Westlake. That led to the city agreeing to the joint
venture by Rouse and Koehler McFayden in 1983.
   Construction began in January 1987. The result pleases the
developers, satisfies the city and is accepted with mixed feelings
by Steinbrueck's son, Peter.
   ``Seattle lost a great opportunity for a grand square,'' says
Steinbrueck, himself an architect. But, ``I think the park and
shopping pavilion will be a major enhancement to the retail core.''
   Steinbrueck thinks the park is good architecturally. He's less
kind about the center, which he says blocks Westlake Avenue from
the plaza and doesn't fit with nearby buildings. And the ``awful,
tacky blue glass'' of the tower's windows creates an eyesore, he
said.
   Royer says the city has ``a clear winner'' in the retail center,
but thinks it might be a while before the park becomes popular.
   ``It's sort of like a new shoe, it will take a little time for
it to become comfortable as a gathering place,'' said Royer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
