<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Fashion     10-20 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Fashion,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summer Ready-To-Wear Reveals All But Favors Less Leg</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Full pants and long skirts are coming back in a big
way. As ready-to-wear shows for next summer started Wednesday, they
revealed leggy looks in shorts and short skirts, but paid more
attention to longer hemlines.
   For the first time American designer Patrick Kelly gave a tent
show in a courtyard of the Louvre, joining the other big names of
ready-to-wear.
   His clothes were just as jazzy and fun as in past, less orthodox
settings, with plenty of clinging jersey dresses, decorated in dice
this time along with the usual Kelly signature _ buttons.
   The dice also gave pizazz to little, fitted pinstriped suits in
cotton that looked like denim. Flower-and-polka-dot prints on linen
also added fun, topped by fitted jackets with decollete shawl
collars.
   There were a lot of wide, wearable trousers. But Kelly also
stuck to shortie bloomers and full shorts.
   Among the lovely, more wearable clothes were simple, white linen
shift tops decorated with seashells worn with wide shorts or full,
long skirts.
   He based most of his collection on jokes about the Mona Lisa,
showing ``Jungle Lisa'' in safari outfits, skirts, pants and bras
or bustier tops in panther spots. He put Mona Lisa cartoons on
T-shirts, including one of himself framed like the famous portrait.
   Kelly's little, clinging dresses topped with flowers and
flowerbasket hats were as winning as his white jerseys with
multicolored handkerchief trim or bright, multicolored trains.
   And Kelly laid on a Milky Way galaxy of stars and crescent moons
in his stretch jersy numbers for evening.
   In contrast, Marc Bohan's show for Dior was full of clothes that
were chic, wearable and young, though not for the avant-garde.
   He showed plenty of suits, with skirts either above the knee or
nearly ankle-length. Linens and chiffon were mixed up in soft tones
based on blue and beige with dusters topping very full pants or
leaner skirts. Some fun carnation print outfits were topped with
lurex cardigans.
   Suits in acid shades of green, electric pink or turquoise teamed
with taupe sported the type of fitted jacket Bohan used for his
winter couture collection _a tulip front and dipped,
martingale-belted back.
   Notable for daytime were the navy and white chemise dresses and
zigzag prints on little shifts. Unforgettable prints were the giant
daisies on full pants and tie-around blouses for resort wear.
   Lola Lempicka, the suit queen, softened up her line considerably
from strict tailoring of recent seasons. She dropped hemlines in
outfits that had a kind of retro charm borrowed from the colonial
look in India.
   The color scheme was subdued with lots of deep or milk
chocolate, cafe-au-lait, taupe and rosy brown.
   Her hourglass jacket was very long this time, often over a
fluid, pleated voile skirt. Some jackets had a triple row of
buttons down the front and were adorned with lace collars. Others
had guipure embroidery details. Lace insets gave a nostalgic touch
to sleeves.
   Nautical themes like anchors embroidered on trouser suits or
cockades on berets added a cruise-wear touch in navy, white and
rust instead of red, all in the Lempicka nostalgic palette.
   The scooped-neck, fitted bodices over flowered or polka-dotted
skirts had youthful appeal. But black suede sheathes with spangled
tops fitted on the bust like bras lacked the touch of class seen in
most of her collection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
