<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NewCabinet     10-20 1004</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Cabinet,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Adminstration Would Strongly Resemble Reagan's, Insiders Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential election is more than two
weeks away but insiders already are predicting that a George Bush
administration would be run by a cast of familiar figures from
Ronald Reagan's presidency.
   With Michael Dukakis far down in the polls and struggling to
recover, his staff says transition planning is on hold. Even so,
Democrats who have been out of power for eight years dream about
the makeup of a Dukakis administration.
   Among Republicans, there is a general expectation that former
Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III, who is Bush's campaign
chairman, would become secretary of State. Former Sen. John Tower
of Texas, an arms negotiator for Reagan and an adviser to Bush on
national security matters, has been lobbying for secretary of
Defense and probably has a claim on it, Republicans say.
   GOP sources say Dick Thornburgh, who replaced Edwin Meese III as
attorney general this year, probably would remain as head of the
Justice Department while Nicholas Brady, a onetime Bush campaign
adviser who replaced Baker at Treasury, would hold onto his job.
   Other likely holdovers in a Bush administration, according to
various sources, are Labor Secretary Ann Dore McLaughlin and
Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos. Bush has promised to put a
Hispanic in his Cabinet, and Cavazos fits the bill.
   Reagan's national security adviser, Colin Powell, is rumored
both as a candidate to stay in his current job or to head the CIA.
Otherwise, William Webster, currently the CIA chief, may be asked
to remain, according to sources.
   Craig Fuller, who has been Bush's chief of staff for the past
four years, would have to be considered for the same job in the
White House. New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu also is mentioned for
that post or for a spot in the Cabinet.
   However, political consultant Vic Kamber _ who owns a public
relations firm whose major clients are labor unions _ notes that
Bush's selection of Dan Quayle as his running mate was a ``total
shocker.'' With that in mind, Kamber says, ``We may be in for some
surprises when he (Bush) picks his Cabinet.''
   On the Democratic side, Paul Brountas, a lawyer who is Dukakis'
campaign chairman and a close friend and trusted adviser,
presumably could have any job he wants, including attorney general.
Another longtime adviser, John Sasso, likely would end up as White
House chief of staff.
   Rep. Lee Hamilton of Indiana, the second-ranking Democrat on the
House Foreign Affairs Committee and the chairman of the House
Iran-Contra committee, has been mentioned as a possible secretary
of State under Dukakis.
   For Treasury, the names of Rep. William Gray, D-Penn., chairman
of the House Budget Committee, and investment banker Roger Altman
are frequently mentioned for Dukakis.
   On defense matters, Dukakis turns to the chairmen of the House
and Senate armed service committees, Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia and
Rep. Les Aspin of Wisconsin, and they would be regarded as the
leading candidates to head the Pentagon.
   For the record, Bush and Dukakis _ as well as their aides _ do
not talk about whom they would put in their Cabinet. By revealing
their choices before the election, they would alienate people who
weren't picked, and the name of the game now is to offend as few
people as possible.
   ``When they tell me I'm the president of the United States, or
president-elect of the United States, I'll begin picking a
cabinet,'' Dukakis said this week.
   Bush said he would be ready to name a Cabinet quickly, but
dismissed suggestions he already has decided whom he would pick.
   ``I can't let myself think about that. ... I'm not going to do
something that dumb and shift gears,'' Bush told a news conference
Sunday.
   Despite the disclaimers, there has been no shortage of talk
about post-election plums, particularly in the Bush campaign and in
Republican circles.
   It's believed that Clayton Yeutter, the U.S. trade
representative under Reagan, would be happy to be picked by Bush as
secretary of Agriculture. Another name in circulation for that post
is former Iowa Rep. Cooper Evans.
   Jim Burnett, former chairman of the National Transportation
Safety Board and currently a member of the panel, has let it be
known he'd like to be secretary of Transportation.
   For the Energy Department, a name frequently mentioned for a
Bush administration is William Martin, a former deputy secretary of
the department who serves as an adviser to Bush. C. Boyden Gray,
counselor to Bush, is believed to be more interested in a White
House post but would go to Energy if asked, sources say.
   Bush also may ask Lee Thomas to remain as chief of the
Environmental Protection Agency, according to sources both at the
agency and within the environmental community. A darkhorse
candidate for the same job is Michael Deland, EPA's regional
administrator in Boston who was the point man in federal efforts to
clean up Boston Harbor.
   For Dukakis, the EPA chief might be Thomas Jorling, head of the
environmental conservation department in New York.
   It's expected that the chairman of the Council of Economic
Advisers under Bush would be Stanford University economist Michael
J. Boskin. Under Dukakis, it probably would be Harvard economist
Lawrence H. Summers.
   Richard Darman, a top White House adviser under Reagan who moved
to Treasury as deputy secretary with Baker, likely would be
director of the Office of Management and Budget under Bush.
   David Keene, a GOP political consultant with connections to
Bush, says Zbigniew Brezinski, a Democrat who was President
Carter's national security adviser and now is a supporter of Bush,
would be a good candidate to be U.N. ambassador.
   For the Interior Department, two names mentioned for a Bush
administration are Henry Diamond, a lawyer in environmental
practice, and Nathaniel Reed, former assistant secretary of
Interior for fish and wildlife and parks.
   Under Dukakis, Interior probably would be filled by former
Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
