<DOCNO> AP881020-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0241EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DukakisAds Bjt   10-20 0870</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis Ads, Bjt,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Everyone's a Media Adviser With Suggestions for
Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scratch a Democrat these days and you'll more
than likely find a budding media consultant with an idea for
television ads to buoy Michael Dukakis' flagging presidential
campaign.
   Some of these proposals lack a practical touch, such as the man
who called to say he had a great idea _ Republican George Bush
driving a truck for Busch Light beer. He wasn't sure how the
Dukakis campaign could get the vice president into the truck with
his rival's cameras rolling.
   But while their advice may be questionable, voters have sensed a
vacuum, one that stems to a large degree from Dukakis' failure to
hone in on a single, strong theme for his overall campaign.
   Since the convention in July, the Democrats have released a
string of seemingly random ads, some negative and some positive,
touching on a wide variety of themes, with little apparent tie-in
to Dukakis' daily campaign speeches and activities.
   By contrast, the Bush campaign and its media, shaped by
political veteran Roger Ailes, have from the start held to a
consistent and unified goal: to paint Bush as a family man with
mainstream values and leadership goals, and Dukakis as an
inexperienced, left-wing robot who is soft on crime, weak on
defense and holds values alien to most Americans.
   Accurate or not, the tactic has worked.
   Dave D'Alessandro, Dukakis' recently hired ad chief, says the
Massachusetts governor's advertising strategy is on target _ as of
last Friday. That was the day two new spots featuring Dukakis
speaking straight into the camera began running on national
television. The campaign also is running a national ad ridiculing
Bush's plan to put his running mate, Dan Quayle, in charge of the
war on drugs.
   But the question pondered by many observers, from academics and
political pros to columnists and average citizens, is why did the
Dukakis campaign take so long to develop its own strategy? Where
was Dukakis in midsummer, when Bush began hammering at his records
on crime and the environment, blasting him as a liberal and raising
issues that put him on the wrong side of patriotism?
   D'Alessandro says he won't answer those questions, since he
didn't come on board until last month. But there is now, he
maintains, a strategy. ``We will show Michael Dukakis as a human
being and who he is,'' he said. ``There's one overarching theme.
Michael Dukakis is on the side of the majority of the people. ...
His theme is that we must regain our stature and our ability to
perform as a country.''
   How the new strategy will be played out on television in the
final weeks of the presidential campaign, both in news coverage and
advertising, is a mystery. But some experts aren't shy about
suggesting what should be done.
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, a University of Texas political
scientist and author of three books on campaign media, said the
Dukakis campaign has failed so far to do ``the one thing that
advertising can do well, which is show the private person.''
   She said the campaign should produce an ad similar to one that
shows Bush with his grandchildren at a picnic, in a kitchen and
other domestic settings. The Democrat sorely needs ``something that
shows that when he bends his knees, his pants crease,'' she said,
and recommended some sample footage: a primary-season clip of
Dukakis sitting in a little chair at a nursery school, singing
``Itsy-Bitsy Spider'' with the children.
   That should be combined with four or five hard-hitting attacks
on Bush, Jamieson said, plus some extended into-the-camera
statements on how things would be different under a Dukakis
administration and lots of Hispanic advertising with Dukakis
speaking in Spanish ``about everything they care about.''
   David Axelrod, a Chicago media consultant who did the ads for
Illinois Sen. Paul Simon's presidential campaign, said he would
abandon the effort to humanize Dukakis. ``He's not going to
out-schmaltz Bush and he shouldn't try. And there's no time for
that,'' he said. ``I'd really go hard negative on Bush and try to
shake some people loose.''
   Axelrod said Dukakis ``has lost the battle to define himself and
that was one of the critical mistakes that's been made. He was not
well-known and he allowed the Bush people to paint in the blank
canvas before he did. I don't think there's time now to erase their
picture totally. He has to concentrate instead on chipping away at
Bush's vulnerabilities.''
   D'Alessandro reacts philosophically to the outpouring of advice
_ which even included a call from his own father, who is in the
hospital with a heart ailment and is normally indifferent to
politics.
   ``We have seen all those ideas. We have actually done some,'' he
said, citing as an example a slew of Hispanic ads due to start this
week. But he said 99 percent of the decisions already have been
made, so no more advice is needed. ``We have a strategy. We know
what the issues are. We know what needs to be done.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDITOR'S NOTE - Jill Lawrence covers the presidential media</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   campaigns for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
