<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan-Bush     10-20 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Bush,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Reagan Changes Strategy in Midstream</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, campaigning for Republican
White House hopeful George Bush, had second thoughts about
declaring the opening of a second front for GOP Senate candidates.
   Reagan on Wednesday deleted from the prepared text of a campaign
speech his reference to a broadened political strategy aimed at
giving more focus to Republicans seeking to recapture the Senate.
   On a day in which Bush campaign manager James A. Baker III
accompanied Reagan to tout the ``unprecedented degree of
cooperation'' between the Bush campaign and the White House, Reagan
found himself explaining why he didn't use the ``second-front''
reference in his speech to a campaign rally in Bowling Green, Ohio.
   Asked as he arrived at Cincinnati airport why he had dropped the
phrase, Reagan replied, ``Bcause I didn't think it fit.'' The
president often departs from a prepared speech text to add a joke
or some other thought, but he seldom deletes something that has
been included in a speech and distributed to reporters.
   The deleted portion of the speech said, ``Today, we're opening a
second front.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that Reagan
``removed the sentences because he didn't want to inadvertently
give any suggestion that the focus was changing from the election
of George Bush. The president will campaign as if the vice
president were 10 points behind.''
   There has been speculation that the Bush campaign and the
president would make proportionately more appearances through the
remainder of the campaign in states where the GOP might have a
chance of capturing a Senate seat.
   Baker, however, has been urging Bush campaign officials and
workers to avoid seeming overconfident or complacent in view of the
vice president's advantage over Democrat Michael Dukakis in public
opinion polls.
   Baker told reporters he had decided to accompany Reagan on
visits to Columbus, Bowling Green and Cincinnati because Reagan was
appearing for the first time at events financed by the Bush
campaign.
   He called Wednesday the first day the president ``is traveling
on the campaign's nickel.'' Reagan's campaign appearances so far
have been financed either by state Republican parties or the
national party.
   In a conversation with reporters aboard the president's plane,
Baker was asked whether Bush would change his campaign strategy now
that he appears to be leading.
   ``We're not changing our mix of states,'' he replied. ``We've
been campaigning in states where there are Senate races all along.''
   The Democratic Party recaptured the Senate from the Republicans
in 1986, even though Reagan campaigned vigorously for several GOP
candidates who subsequently lost. The Democrats now hold a 54-46
majority in the Senate.
   White House chief of staff Ken Duberstein said that Reagan and
Baker, at some point during the campaign day, discussed what the
president would do to provide further help for Bush.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
