<DOCNO> AP881020-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialPolls     10-20 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Polls,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Up by Nine in Harris Poll, Seven in ABC-Post's</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican nominee George Bush has a sizable but
not an overwhelming lead in the presidential race, and his
advantage relies heavily on disproportionate support from men, new
polls indicate.
   ABC News-Washington Post and Harris polls released Wednesday put
the Bush lead at seven and nine points respectively, both
considerably less than the 17-point Bush lead in an NBC News-Wall
Street Journal poll out Monday.
   The ABC-Post poll, done Oct. 12 through Tuesday, found virtually
no movement since before last week's presidential debate. It put
the race at 52 percent to 45 percent Bush, little different from
its 51-45 result Oct. 5-11.
   John Brennan, an ABC pollster, noted that debates historically
produce little or no sizable change in voter sympathies. The Harris
poll, however, did find movement _ from 50 percent to 48 percent
Bush on Oct. 6-10 to 53-44 now.
   As in other recent surveys, the Harris poll found a continuing
gender gap for Bush, despite his lead. He led among men by 57-40,
but the race among women was about even: Forty-eight percent for
Bush, 49 percent for Dukakis.
   That poll indicated that Bush had gained through his attacks on
Dukakis' stand on crime. Sixty-three percent rated Dukakis as ``too
soft on law enforcement,'' up from 52 percent in late August.
   Also, 49 percent agreed that Dukakis ``seems too liberal in his
views to get my vote,'' a number that has remained more or less
stable in the poll since August. Sixty-nine percent said Dukakis
lacked enough foreign policy experience, down from 75 percent in
August but still high.
   The NBC-Journal poll that had found a 17-point Bush lead was
done Friday through Sunday, and NBC pollster Laurily Epstein said
it could have missed some movement back to Dukakis on Monday after
a big swing to Bush following Thursday's debate.
   Epstein, commenting on the Harris poll before the ABC-Post poll
was released, noted that the Harris and NBC-Journal polls found
nearly the same level for support for the Republicans _ 53 percent
and 55 percent, respectively.
   ``The difference is really on the Democratic side, not the
Republican side,'' she said. ``It may be that we caught the highest
spinoff from the debate,'' which polls and other news accounts said
Bush had won.
   The Harris poll, of 1,356 likely voters, had a margin of error
of plus or minus three points, as did the NBC-Journal poll released
Monday. The ABC-Post poll, of 1,195 likely voters, had an error
margin of about three points.
</TEXT>
