<DOCNO> AP881020-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Education-Holocaust Bjt   10-20 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Education-Holocaust, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Program Spiked After Reviewer Complained About Lack of Nazi
Views</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Reagan administration official who refused
to fund a school study program on the Holocaust acknowledges that
her decision was based in part on reviews including one complaining
that the views of Nazis and the Ku Klux Klan weren't included.
   Supporters of the Holocaust program entitled ``Facing History
and Ourselves'' contend that the review boards set up to assess the
merits of the program for the Education Department were
ideologically slanted and predisposed to recommend it not be funded.
   But Shirley Curry, a political appointee in the department, said
criticism that ``somehow the department in general and I in
particular have operated in some anti-Semitic mode ... is
absolutely absurd.''
   She told a House Government Operations subcommittee Wednesday
that the program was denied $70,000 in federal funds three times.
Those decisions were made either because the program scored low in
critiques prepared by panels of outside reviewers or because, as
was the case this year when the program received a relatively high
score, a money squeeze prevented funding of an entire category of
programs.
   ``We looked at categories that we needed and that is what we
funded,'' she said.
   She said she supports secondary school programs examining the
Holocaust, the Nazis' systematic killing of some 6 million Jews
during World War II. She said the ``Facing History'' curriculum
would have received a grant if money had been available ``to fund
everything.''
   The program was first denied a federal grant in 1986 after a
member of an outside review panel faulted it for not including the
opinions of the Nazi Party and the Ku Klux Klan. In 1987, a
reviewer called it ``leftist,'' anti-war, anti-hunting'' and
``offensive to (Christian) fundamentalits.'' Another reviewer said
it was likely to produce a ``guilt trip.''
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., told the witness: ``The fact is that
you selected these reviewers and you gave full weight to their
scores. These two offensive, wacko opinions were given full weight.
   ``Did you discount them for being crazy?'' he asked.
   Curry: ``The scores were recorded.''
   Frank: ``Were these scores given the same weight as others?''
   Curry: ``Yes.''
   Frank: ``You read them. You gave them full weight. Shame on the
department.''
   Responding to further questions, Curry said that at the time the
Holocaust program was being considered, she was a member of the
Eagle Forum, whose president is conservative activist Phyllis
Schlafly.
   Mrs. Schlafly, in a 1987 letter to an Education Department
official, urged that the grant application for the program be
rejected. She said it employed ``psychological manipulation,
induced behavioral change and privacy-invading treatment.''
   Asked if Mrs. Schlafly's position had any impact on the decision
not to fund the program, Curry replied, ``Not in my book.''
   Curry said she was reassigned last Friday from her position as
director of the department's National Diffusion Recognition
Division to become a special assistant to the assistant to the
deputy secretary for management.
   She said she plans to leave her $57,000 a year position by the
end of the year and hesitated when asked what her new duties would
be.
   Rep. Frank told the witness: ``It seems to me that they moved
you to a political position for a month or two to avoid political
embarrassment and gave you a month or two vacation at a $57,000 a
year salary.''
   Margot Stern Strom of Brookline, Mass., who was instrumental in
developing the Holocaust teaching project for Facing History and
Ourselves National Foundation Inc., said the initial review
comments on the program were ``beyond my imagination.''
   She said she and her colleagues concluded that the outside
review system amounted to ``an ideological screen to permit the
department to deny funding to `Facing History.'''
   ``My own reading of the comments showed an extraordinarily
narrow bias on the part of the reviewers,'' she said.
</TEXT>
