<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LateCongress     10-20 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Late Congress,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Nearing Quiet Close to Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 100th Congress, rather than recessing with
a bang, may go out with a whisper.
   Most sessions of Congress end with raucous, all-night
bill-passing sessions. But the 100th Congress is nearing an end to
its productive two-year session so quietly that many lawmakers may
not be around to see the gavel fall.
   It's an election year, and many senators and House members have
already slipped out of town to campaign for re-election back home.
Congress already has fallen nearly three weeks behind its original
adjournment target.
   Some members aren't anxious to come back at all.
   Senate leaders hinted Wednesday as to just how _ and just when _
the Congress might adjourn for the year.
   ``We won't have another vote this year,'' Senate Republican
leader Bob Dole of Kansas told startled reporters at a morning
meeting. He meant he didn't think the Senate would have any formal
roll call votes, but would pass remaining legislation by the
unanimous consent of those present.
   The Senate has been passing legislation all week without roll
call votes, a process that requires the presence of three senators:
the presiding officer, a single Democrat and a lone Republican.
   Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said later that Dole
had made ``a pretty accurate prediction.''
   Byrd explained in a telephone interview that although
legislation remains to be passed, including a major anti-drug bill,
``it's not the kind of thing senators have to come back for to take
roll call votes.''
   Two major pieces of legislation remain, the catchall anti-drug
bill already passed by the House and Senate in differing versions,
and a tax bill. If House-Senate negotiators can iron out
differences, the Senate could pass them both by Friday and quit for
the year.
   ``We ought to be able to finish the whole kit and caboodle by
the close of business Friday,'' Byrd said.
   Are any members complaining about still being here?
   ``My wife has complained,'' Byrd responded.
   In the House, members returned for roll call votes Wednesday,
but only after enjoying a five-day break while waiting for the
Senate to act on bills it already had passed.
   House Democratic Whip Tony Coelho of California had his own
theory on why the election-year Congress was taking so long to
finish its business.
   ``Incumbent senators are enjoying having the excuse not to be
debating their opponents,'' Coelho said. ``How can the public
complain if you're here working on a drug bill?''
   Dole and Byrd are showing physical signs of wanting to call it
quits, or, in congressional parlance, adjourning ``sine die.'' In
English, that means without setting a date.
   Dole wore a campaign-style button on his label the other day
that proclaimed ``Free The 100th.''
   Byrd showed up the next day with his own button, warning: ``Sine
or Die.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Nancy-Wardrobe     10-20 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nancy-Wardrobe,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nancy Dodges Press on Wardrobe Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Nancy Reagan plans to continue her
years-long practice of borrowing high-priced designer fashions,
she's not saying.
   But her spokeswoman isn't ruling out the possibility that more
free fashions might be seen at White House functions.
   And President Reagan is jumping into the flap to defend his
wife, praising the first lady as a hard-working but unpaid
``government employee.''
   This evening, the president was scheduled to attend an elaborate
tribute to Mrs. Reagan, sponsored by Kiwanis International and
other organizations that have participated in her anti-drug abuse
campaign efforts.
   The celebration comes after a day in which Mrs. Reagan shunned
reporters who were attempting to speak with her about the designer
gowns lent her by leading fashion houses.
   On Wednesday, as she left the National Center for Therapeutic
Riding, a center devoted to helping the handicapped, Mrs. Reagan
only smiled slightly and continued walking as reporters attempted
to query her.
   The first lady's spokeswoman, Elaine Crispen, has acknowledged
that Mrs. Reagan ``broke her little promise'' made in 1982 to stop
accepting the items lent her by leading couturiers.
   Reagan denounced the reports, which first appeared in Time
Magazine over the weekend.
   ``I don't have anything to say about that ridiculous story,''
Reagan told reporters as he left the White House for a day of
campaigning in Ohio.
   And at a speech later in the day, Reagan came to his wife's
defense.
   He praised the first lady's anti-drug abuse campaign, and added:
``The government's got quite an employee there, with no salary.''
   White House counsel Fred Fielding informed the Office of
Government Ethics in 1982 that even though the Ethics in Government
Act of 1978 did not require Mrs. Reagan to report the borrowed
material, she would include the information on financial disclosure
forms.
   At that time, she also pledged to quit using borrowed items.
   However, Time quoted several designers over the weekend as
saying they have continued to lend Mrs. Reagan expensive clothes
since 1982. And neither the first lady nor the president has since
reported the items as gifts or loans on their financial disclosure
and tax forms.
   One Los Angeles designer, David Hayes, was quoted by Time as
saying he'd made some 60 to 80 made-to-order outfits available to
the first lady over the years. She returned more than half and kept
the others, he said.
   A spokeswoman for Hayes, who refused to identify herself, said
he was ``in conference'' on Wednesday and unable to take a phone
call.
   Mrs. Reagan's spokeswoman disputed Hayes' account, contending
his numbers were ``extraordinarily high.''
   ``I haven't seen her wear a David Hayes in five years,'' Mrs.
Crispen said.
   Mrs. Crispen also took issue with Hayes' assertion that she
hasn't returned some of the dresses made especially for her. ``All
the items that were borrowed have been returned,'' Mrs. Crispen.
   The spokeswoman said she did not know what led the first lady to
break the promise she made in 1982 to report the borrowed gowns.
   ``I just don't know. She made her own rule ... She broke her own
rule. Perhaps because she was told it wasn't against the law. I
just don't know what her personal thinking was,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   The spokeswoman said she couldn't rule out a continuance of the
practice, however.
   ``I won't rule out that possibility _ that sometime, something
in the future might be borrowed,'' she added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
