<HEAD>Convicted Tax Evader To Be Freed From Jail To Feed Cats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARGO, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman sentenced to 30 days in jail for tax
evasion will be freed for two hours each day so she can go home to
her cats and visit a park to feed squirrels and birds.
   Daisy Salsman, 50, began serving her sentence Tuesday at the
Cass County Jail here. She was convicted in May of tax evasion,
conspiracy and failure to file income tax returns.
   U.S. District Judge Patrick Conmy granted her request to be
released from jail so she could feed her four cats and the
squirrels and birds at a park near her home.
   Mrs. Salsman said in a letter to Conmy last week that she had
tried to find someone to care for her animals but had been
unsuccessful.
   ``While this sounds like a ridiculous request, the court finds
that it does have merit,'' Conmy wrote in an order signed Friday.
