<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cats Bjt   10-20 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cats, Bjt,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cat Cases Tied To Fur Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspicious vans stacked with cages, 800 paws found
on a rubbish dump and thousands of missing felines point to
catnapping on a massive scale in England and Wales, a pet charity
says.
   The National Petwatch group in a report Wednesday warned owners
to keep cats indoors at night, saying increasing numbers of hunters
are seeking cat pelts for toys, fur coats and even food.
   ``In many parts of the country, cat theft has become an
organized crime on a massive scale,'' said Joan Warne, national
coordinator of the charity which monitors the loss and theft of
family pets.
   In ``Cat Stealing: A Special Report,'' the group said ``it would
be comforting to take refuge in the old adage `cats will wander,'
but we must face the real facts of the problem.''
   The group did not cite statistics on exactly how many cats have
been stolen. Police do not keep records on stolen cats and are not
required to record such cases, as they must with dogs, it said.
   But by monitoring advertisements for missing cats for five years
and other sources the group said it has uncovered ``alarming''
evidence, which it believes is ``only the tip of the iceberg.''
   Saying London and urban areas are among the worst-hit, the
report quoted excerpts from the Peckham Mercury newspaper in
southeast London as saying more than 100 cats were feared stolen in
the area.
   ``Many of the pets have vanished from roads where residents
report repeated sightings of a white van stacked with cages,'' the
paper said.
   A south London newspaper was quoted as describing a woman
chasing a man with a bag, and when he dropped it, out jumped three
cats including her own.
   National Petwatch reported that not only have 800 paws been
sighted on a rubbish dump in Manchester but skinned cat bodies have
been found, although it did not say where.
   Earlier this year, the group undertook a computer analysis of
2,027 advertisements for missing cats over a two-month period and
said the results pointed clearly to organized catnapping.
   It said 162 cats disappeared in the two months in rural
Hampshire, more than four times the national average.
   In some areas, more than 40 percent of the missing cats were
tabby, with dark stripes, or tortoise-shell with distinctive
markings, both fur colors popular for coats.
   Cat fur is cheap to obtain and has become more sought after in
the fur trade following restrictions on seal and other endangered
animals' fur, the report said.
   ``Lots of 10,000 domestic cat pelts regularly come under the
hammer at German fur auctions,'' the group said, adding that
Scandinavia, Australia and Britain are known in trade circles as
good suppliers.
   An unidentified spokeswoman for the Fur Trade Association,
interviewed on Independent Television, denied that cat pelts used
in the fur trade were stolen.
   ``There is really no reason to go out and steal pets because
frankly you wouldn't make any money anyway,'' she said, adding that
pelts cost only about $1.75 each and are obtained legally from
veterinarians. ``And there is no demand, either.''
   But the report argued that ``foreign dealers require so many
that they are willing to buy them in tens of thousands on a `no
questions asked' basis.''
   The report added that cat pelts are sold in Germany pharmacies
as a cure for arthritis, that some cats are stolen as training bait
for fighting hares and dogs, and that others are apparently killed
for food.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EarlyFuneral Bjt   10-20 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Early Funeral, Bjt,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Terminally Ill Woman Plans To Attend Her Own Funeral</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LIGHTFOOT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carrie Munson beat heroin addiction to succeed
as a radio broadcaster and social worker. Now that the 62-year-old
has terminal cancer, she plans to beat death, too, by attending her
own funeral next week.
   The music, she says, will be ``I Did It My Way.'' And she plans
to enjoy it.
   ``As long as I can remember, I have always wanted to know when I
was going to die so I could put things in order,'' the Milwaukee
woman said Wednesday. ``I want to watch the peoples' expressions. I
want to see the way they react.''
   Munson, who has pancreatic cancer and has been told she does not
have long to live, sent invitations to her ``friends, associates
and enemies'' and three sons for the Oct. 29 service. Her sons plan
to attend.
   Munson is writing an autobiography called ``Bury Me in My Cap
and Gown,'' and said the funeral would be an appropriate way to end
her life's story.
   ``I'll get it all embedded in my mind and when I get home I'll
just write up that final chapter,'' she said.
   The Rev. R. L. Lathan, pastor of the New Hope Baptist Church,
has agreed to conduct the service.
   ``This is the first time I've had this kind of request,'' Lathan
said. ``It's very, very strange and unusual. She wanted to be at
her own funeral and she wanted to be alive.''
   For Munson, who says she spent more than 20 years as a drug
addict until she returned to school in her 40s, death is not
something to fear.
   ``I have a message for all these young drug addicts out there,
and I have a message for the cancer patients,'' she said. ``The
message is why be afraid? We've all got to die.''
   Although Munson said her cancer is painful, she refuses to let
it disturb her ``because I'm not the type to give in.''
   Munson, born in Mississippi, had only a fourth-grade education
until she returned to school decades later. She said she is strong
because she has been on her own all her life.
   ``My mother died when I was 3 and I was the youngest of six,''
she said. ``If I knew one thing, it was that I was not going to be
a sharecropper.''
   She saved enough money from picking cotton to buy a bus ticket
to St. Louis and arrived ``with nothing but what was on my back and
some high-heeled shoes that had the heels cut off.''
   Once in St. Louis, Munson scraped together enough money to get
to Chicago, where she said she was turned on to heroin by an
acquaintance.
   That, she said, began an involvement with drugs that led to
prison terms for crimes committed to get the drugs, including
theft, prostitution and forgery.
   ``It took me 24 or 25 years to get off that darn stuff,'' she
said, ``I said to myself, `Either crawl out of the gutter and die
or get off your butt and do something.'''
   Munson said she decided to apply to the University of
Wisconsin-Milwaukee, and although she was not qualified, ``I had so
much enthusiasm they let me in.''
   Since graduating with a degree in mass communications and
journalism in 1975, Munson has worked as the host of a jazz show at
a radio station and most recently as a social worker with Wisconsin
Correctional Services, where she has helped clients find jobs.
   Munson said she would wear her college cap and gown at the
funeral service, ``which I am very proud of.''
   ``And when I die,'' she said, ``somebody better put it on me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     10-20 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Tells Arab Voters Likud Will Fight PLO Supporters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: STANDS for PM-Israel-Politics listed on digest.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Car Bomb, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMRA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told dozens
of Israeli Arab villagers that his hardline Likud bloc offers Arabs
``real rights'' but will fight against those who support the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   In a campaign speech in this northern village Wednesday, Shamir
also urged about 250 Arab listeners to ``ask your brothers to stop
terrorism and start negotiations.''
   The right-wing leader referred to the 10-month-old Palestinian
rebellion against Israeli rule in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, during which 301 Arabs and six Israelis have died.
   The uprising in the occupied territories are a key campaign
issue in the Nov. 1 general elections.
   Polls show that Likud's principal rival, the left-leaning Labor
Party, may lose half of its Israeli Arab support because many Arabs
hold Labor's No. 2 man, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, responsible
for the harsh crackdown on the Palestinian uprising.
   Likud and Labor, headed by Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, are
now running neck-to-neck, and both compete for crucial Arab support.
   On Monday, Peres took his campaign to the Israeli Arab town of
Shfaram but encountered a frosty reception as he told the Arabs
they should decide the battle between the two major parties and not
waste their votes on smaller parties.
   Shamir, however, dismissed the importance of the Arab vote. ``I
don't think the Arab vote will be the deciding vote,'' he told
reporters.
   But speaking in Tamra, Shamir told Arab villagers:
   ``What we offer is real rights. The Likud will be here for both
Jews and Arabs as well.''
   Last year, Israeli Arabs staged several general strikes to
demand better schools and municipal services and protest
bureaucracy in solving housing problems.
   Israeli leaders, among them Shamir, have expressed concern that
Palestinian uprising may spread to the Arab sector in Israel.
   ``We are searching for peace,'' Shamir said. ``We're going to
live together as two peoples. Ask your brothers to stop terrorism
and start negotiations ... But to those Arabs who want to support
the PLO, we will say go your way. As much as we want peace, we know
how to fight those who threaten us.''
   Ismael Salaama, an Arab from the village of Turam, stood in the
crowd featuring a Likud campaign hat and carrying a party campaign
pamphlet.
   ``I'm listening to Likud and Labor, then I will decide,'' he
said. ``When I go to a Labor rally and there are hats, I wear those
hats, too.''
   About 330,000 of Israel's 800,000 Arabs are eligible to vote
this year, and could control 14 seats in the 120-member Knesset, or
parliament. In the 1984 general elections, one in four Arabs voted
Labor. This year, analysts say Labor may lose 1.5 seats in the Arab
sector.
   According to recent Labor polls cited in the Jerusalem Post, the
Communist Party may gain one seat in the Arab sector this year,
bringing its total to five.
   The Communists are fiercely competing for the Arab vote against
the pro-PLO Progressive List for Peace. The group is expected to
maintain its strength with two seats.
   Six other parties, including Likud, would share the remaining
seats in the Arab sector, an udentified Labor official told the
newspaper.
</TEXT>
