<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SuicideHelper     10-20 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suicide Helper,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friend Who Allegedly Offered Suicide Help Faces Murder Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-year-old man who a witness said
helped a friend commit suicide by pulling the trigger of a shotgun
placed in the victim's mouth has been charged with murder.
   Dennis C. Harwood Jr. was arraigned Tuesday in District Court in
the Oct. 6 death of Jack Main Jr. Prosecutors have not specified
the degree of murder.
   Main, 24, died in the apartment he shared with Harwood and Dean
Myers, 19. While police have not provided details of the shooting,
Myers said that after drinking heavily, Main put the barrel of a
20-gauge shotgun in his mouth.
   Harwood offered to pull the trigger, Myers told The Grand Rapids
Press on Tuesday.
   ``I think Denny thinks he was doing the right thing at the
time,'' Myers said. ``But now I think he realizes he was wrong.''
   However, one of the suspect's sisters said Harwood told his
family he was trying to pull the gun away from Main when it
discharged.
   ``He tried to stop him,'' Patty Musser said. ``He's not a
murderer.''
   Myers described sitting on a bed between the two men with the
barrel of the shotgun in Main's mouth and Harwood's finger on the
trigger, the gun suspended like a bridge above his lap.
   Harwood said, ``Let me do it,'' and Main answered, ``Go ahead,''
according to Myers. ``That was the last thing that was said.
   ``None of us said a word for about 30 seconds. It was all quiet
until the gun went off,'' he said.
   Main died instantly.
   ``On the day, we were quite sure it was not a suicide,'' Police
Chief Gene Koetje said. ``But yet we were not sure about the degree
of involvement. We weren't sure we were going to have an actual
murder.''
   Police on Monday arrested Harwood, who had known Main since they
were classmates in elementary school. He was held in the Barry
County Jail on a $100,000 bond. Police said Myers is not considered
a suspect in the case.
   Koetje said police knew Main had been threatening suicide. ``It
was just depression. Things just weren't going well. He'd been
having some personal problems,'' the chief said.
   Main's wife had recently left him, taking their year-old
daughter with her, according to relatives. Myers said Main had
argued with a girlfriend just before the shooting.
</TEXT>
