<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Suriname-Brazil     10-20 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suriname-Brazil,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suriname Strongman Mistakenly Detained By Brazilian Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the Suriname Army was
arrested and later released after Brazilian police confused him and
seven heavily armed companions with criminals, authorities said
today.
   In Paramaribo, Suriname Vice President Henck Arron denounced
Wednesday's arrest of Cmdr. Desi Bouterse over state television.
   Arron termed the detention of the Suriname strongman in this
industrial city as a ``sad incident,'' especially in light of
Brazil's recent grant of a $3 million credit line to Suriname for
food and raw materials.
   Arron said Bouterse, 43, was vacationing in Brazil and tried to
identify himself to officers at a shopping center but instead was
handcuffed and taken to the police headquarters.
   Globo, Brazil's largest television network, quoted Sao Paulo
police as saying officers did not understand what any of the
heavily armed group said.
   Brazilians speak Portuguese, while Dutch is spoken in Suriname.
   Suriname, a former Dutch colony in northeastern South America,
borders Brazil, Guyana and French Guiana.
   Globo said the group was released after phone calls to Brazil's
Foreign Ministry and diplomats at Suriname's Embassy in Brasilia,
the capital. No charges were filed, Globo said.
   In Suriname, Arron said Suriname Foreign Minister Edwin Sedoc
lodged a formal complaint with Brazilian Charge d'Affaires Henry
Jenne, who was summoned to the Foreign Ministry and asked for an
explanation.
   Radio broadcasts quoted Luiz Antonio Fleury, head of Sao Paulo's
state security, as apologizing to Bouterse over the incident.
   Bouterse and a band of army sergeants overthrew Arron's civilian
government in 1980 when Arron was prime minister.
   Bouterse named himself army commander and headed a military
government until national elections were held last February, in
which Ramsewak Shankar was elected president and Arron vice
president.
   Although Bouterse officially transferred power to the civilian
government, he retains control of the country's military, whose
blessing is required on all major government decisions.
   Last May, Bouterse was vacationing in Brazil when his companion,
Lt. Guno Mahaden, who as a sergeant had participated in the 1980
coup, drowned while swimming at a beach in Rio de Janeiro.
</TEXT>
