<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RollsFlap     10-20 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rolls Flap,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rolls-Royce Gets Bum's Rush on Rodeo Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rodeo Drive isn't what it used to
be, lamented an art gallery proprietor who stood helplessly as a
judge declared his $200,000 Rolls-Royce a public nuisance for
hogging a parking spot on the glitzy street.
   ``I just wanted to put glitter and glamor back on the street,''
David Spellerberg Wednesday after Superior Court Judge Edward
Kakita issued a preliminary injuction barring him from parking the
1954 Rolls on Rodeo Drive for more than an hour at a time in front
of his business.
   Spellerberg had infuriated city officials by flaunting parking
regulations, in effect using the vintage auto as a promotion for
his business.
   According to the order, Spellerberg must move the car at least
500 feet after it is parked an hour in the spot. The order also
prohibits him from blocking the sidewalk or using the sidewalk for
any commercial advertisements or promotions.
   Five attorneys representing the city persuaded Kakita to issue
the injunction.
   ``Rodeo Drive just isn't what it used to be,'' Spellerberg said
after the 15 minute hearing. ``This is the first time a Rolls-Royce
has been declared a public nuisance. Only in Beverly Hills would
this happen.''
   Spellerberg's chauffeur has parked the dark blue car in the
one-hour spot in front of his National Heritage Gallery of Fine Art
for the past seven months.His driver would pump the meter with $15
in quarters each day.
   ``We're paying $20,000 a month in rent and I can't even park my
own car in front of my own gallery,'' Spellerberg said.
   Spellerberg said he bought the Rolls after noticing tourists
walking down Rodeo Drive, known for its posh shops and celebrity
clientele, were frequently heard asking, ``Is that all there is?''
   Since parking the Rolls in front of the gallery, he said, an
estimated 20,000 tourists have posed for snapshots in front of the
luxury car. He blames the heavy-handed treatment by the city on
jealous business owners nearby.
   Spellerberg said he isn't giving up his fight, but he won't
disclose his next move.
   ``The city hasn't had any sense of humor in this,'' Spellerberg
said. ``They had five attorneys in there this morning. I want to
know what the taxpayers have to say about that.''
</TEXT>
