<DOCNO> AP881020-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma     10-20 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0519</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Ruler Warns Against Attempts To Discredit Army
^By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's military ruler has warned the
country's newly formed political parties against attempts to
discredit or sow dissension within the army.
   Since taking power in a Sept. 18 coup, Saw Maung has crushed
pro-democracy street demonstrations but allowed formation of
opposition political parties to contest a general election he has
promised to hold soon. No date has been set for the balloting.
   ``Taking advantage of permission for party organizations, some
parties are indulging in efforts to create misunderstanding between
the army and the public, and also create dissension within the
army,'' Saw Maung said Wednesday in a broadcast over state-run
Radio Rangoon.
   ``The army is not participating in the elections but it is
concerned only with the holding of a free and fair general
election,'' he said.
   ``Political parties are ... warned not to incite, preach, write,
or spread rumors aimed at creating dissension among the military.
Violations of these warnings will be dealt with effectively,'' he
said.
   The parties have not publicly made the statements suggested by
Saw Maung. But some opposition figures have said they do not trust
the administration to conduct fair elections, partly because they
say the National Unity Party enjoys the backing of the government
and the army.
   The party, earlier called the Burma Socialist Program Party, had
ruled the country with an iron fist for 26 years as the sole legal
party before its recent disbandment.
   The radio said two more parties registered Wednesday, bringing
the total number of parties to 24.
   The All Burma National Youth League registered along with the
Mon National Democratic Front, the fourth ethnic minority-based
party. In the remote countryside, guerrillas of a number of ethnic
minorities have been fighting the government for four decades.
   Radio Rangoon said U.S. Ambassador Burton Levin called on the
elections commission Wednesday and met with its chairman, Ba Htay,
to discuss the promised general election. No details were given in
the broadcast.
   Also, Radio Rangoon said Saw Maung's administration enacted a
law Wednesday changing the country's name from the Socialist
Republic of the Union of Burma to Union of Burma.
   Union of Burma was used beginning with the constitution of 1947,
a year before Burmese independence. It was changed after Gen. Ne
Win mounted the 1962 coup and began a quarter century of repression
and rigid socialist economic policies. Ne Win resigned July 23, and
two other leaders followed before Saw Maung's coup, which many
diplomats believe was engineered by Ne Win.
   The country's name had already been changed on some recent
government press releases, apparently as part of an effort to
convince the public that the ruinous policies of the past were
being shelved.
   The broadcast also said the name ``president,'' or head of
state, is to be replaced by ``the chairman of the State Law and
Order Restoration Council'' _ a title now held by Saw Maung. Saw
Maung already is prime minister, defense and foreign minister.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
