<DOCNO> AP881020-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Irish Bjt   10-20 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, Bjt,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bans On TV, Radio Interviews With IRA, Others Begin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government ban went into effect today on British
television and radio interviews with the Irish Republican Army and
10 nationalist and Protestant groups involved in Northern Ireland's
sectarian conflict.
   News reports today indicated further restrictions are in the
offing to try to curb the recent rise in guerrilla activity.
   Sinn Fein, the outlawed IRA's legal political wing, compared the
ban announced Wednesday by the government with Soviet bloc
censorship. In addition to the IRA, the ban includes Sinn Fein and
four Protestant groups.
   IRA guerrillas seek to end British rule in predominantly
Protestant Northern Ireland and unite it with the Roman Catholic
Republic of Ireland under socialist rule. Most Protestants oppose
uniting with the Republic.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd, the Cabinet member responsible for
law and order and broadcasting among other matters, on Wednesday
told the House of Commons:
   ``The government has decided that the time has now come to deny
this easy platform to those who use it to propagate terrorism.''
   Junior Home Office minister of state Timothy Renton explained
Wednesday night that ``the whole aim of this (ban)... is to remove
that extra weapon _ the ability to go on television immediately
afterwards to speak in justification of an explosion or a bomb.''
   Appearances by Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams and other Irish
nationalist leaders on British television in recent years have
enraged many viewers.
   Adams is a member of the British House of Commons. But in
accordance with long-standing IRA practice, he has never taken his
seat since first being elected for west Belfast in 1983.
   The Republic of Ireland has banned TV and radio interviews with
the IRA, Sinn Fein and other groups since the mid-1970s.
   Sinn Fein seeks to convince mainland Britain that British
security forces in Northern Ireland cannot curb the sectarian and
political violence there, and that British forces should be
withdrawn.
   The chairman of the British Broadcasting Corp., Marmaduke
Hussey, and its director-general, Michael Checkland, said in a
joint statement Wednesday night that the ban sets a damaging
precedent.
   Roy Hattersley, deputy leader of the socialist opposition Labor
Party, said the ban was ``trivial, worthless and almost certainly
counterproductive.''
   The ban affects only British TV and radio networks. It does not
affect interviews by foreign TV and radio networks broadcasting to
audiences outside Britain or interviews by newspapers and other
print media, either British or foreign.
   The seven Irish nationalist groups covered by the ban are the
Provisional and Official wings of the IRA; Sinn Fein; the Irish
National Liberation Army, an outlawed splinter group from the IRA;
Cumann Na Mban, the IRA's women's movement; Na Fianna Eireann, the
IRA's youth section; and the Republican Socialist Group Saor Eire.
   The four Protestant groups covered by the ban are the legal
paramilitary Ulster Defense Association; the outlawed Ulster
Freedom Fighters, who are reportedly the UDA's military arm; the
outlawed Red Hand Commandos; and the outlawed Ulster Volunteer
Force.
   Hurd said the ban would not apply to election campaigns and the
broadcasting of Parliament.
   David Nicholas, editor and chief executive of commercial
television's Independent Television News, said he feared the ban
might lead to further reporting restrictions.
   The London newspaper The Guardian quoted unnamed government
sources as saying the ban is the start of a series of initiatives.
   The British domestic news agency Press Association said measures
being considered include removal of a suspect's legal right of
silence, so that refusal to cooperate with police can be brought to
the attention of the courts; exclusion from elections of candidates
who refuse to renounce violence; and changes to allow guerrillas to
be convicted of IRA membership on the evidence of a single police
officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     10-20 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Soldiers Killed In Guerrilla Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels attacked
army-defended coffee plantations and a prison in Usulutan province,
killing two soldiers and wounding eight others, officials said.
   The attacks early Wednesday outside Santa de Maria, 70 miles
east of San Salvador, marked the guerrilla army's eighth
anniversary.
   The fighting began hours after two car bomb explosions wounded
six civilians in an affluent San Salvador neighborhood. Rebels were
presumed responsible for the bombings.
   Rebel radio on Wednesday said air force planes and helicopters
attacked Torola, in eastern Morazan province, with bombs, rockets
and machine guns on Monday. It said a rocket hit the town church
with ``numerous'' people inside, leaving three ``gravely wounded.''
   An air force spokesman said no officer was available to comment
on the allegation.
   The main targets of the pre-dawn Santa de Maria attack included
three plantations surrounding the town, their processing plants,
the local prison and an electricity transmission plant.
   Prudencio Llach, owner of one of the plantations, is
father-in-law of Defense Minister Gen. Carlos Vides Casanova and
also father-in-law of rightist presidential candidate Alfredo
Cristiani.
   About 50 criminals were reported freed in the prison attack.
Military officials said the electric plant was slightly damaged,
while guerrillas claimed it was destroyed.
   Rebels formed a unified command, the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front known as FMLN, in October 1980. The anniversary is
celebrated thoughout October.
   The rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos said the attacks were
part of an operation called, ``With the people we advance toward
victory on the eighth anniversary of the FMLN.''
   Military officers estimate there are 6,000 to 7,000 full-time
guerrillas and perhaps twice as many men and women who serve
part-time in the rebel militia. There are 55,000 men in the armed
forces of the U.S.-backed government.
</TEXT>
