<DOCNO> AP881020-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APMEConvention     10-20 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-APME Convention,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Urges More Press Responsibility; Cites Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy told newspaper editors the
news media have been unfair to vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle, and said coverage of the campaign has turned it into an
exercise in style over substance.
   ``It (the coverage) has not been a fair characterization of
him,'' the Massachusetts Democrat said of the Republican Senator
from Indiana during a speech at the conclusion of the Associated
Press Managing Editors convention.
   ``Most of his colleagues would say he does a lot better in give
and take in the Senate. I've worked with him and he does a better
job on the (Senate) floor.''
   Kennedy said Wednesday he was impressed with Quayle when they
co-sponsored the Jobs Training Partnership Act. He also called
Quayle a ``forceful, vigorous'' defender of the conservative issues
he espouses.
   Though Kennedy began on a light note, telling the editors ``it's
not often I get to address a group whose standing in the polls is
lower than Congress,'' he quickly became serious.
   He decried the 1988 presidential campaign, saying that the press
and politics have become dangerously intertwined.
   ``Substance has been overwhelmed by image,'' he said. ``Both
sides are guilty of reducing important events to `spin' control.''
   Kennedy said Republican presidential nominee George Bush's trip
to Boston Harbor to demonstrate his interest in the environment and
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis' ride in an Army
tank were typical of the flashy but trivial methods the candidates
have used to show their stand on the issues.
   ``Campaigning has become a meat market,'' said Kennedy. ``What
coverage there is comes in the form of labels. Negative campaigning
is drowning out positive campaigning.''
   Kennedy urged editors to try and stem the ``widening gap''
between issues and candidates by focusing more on real events and
avoiding ``horse-race'' style journalism.
   Also at the convention, a panel of three journalists urged
editors to make more of a commitment to hiring minority reporters
and editors, who they said comprise only 7 percent of working
American journalists.
   Norma Sosa, of the Corpus Christi (Texas) Caller-Times, called
the outlook for minority journalists ``bleak'' and encouraged
editors to attend minority journalist job fairs, recruit at
colleges and spend more time in newsroom minority development.
   William Hawkins, editor of the Durham (N.C.) Morning Herald and
The Durham Sun, urged editors to improve their treatment of
minority journalists once they are hired since many tend to leave
journalism after a few years.
   Also Wednesday, editors witnessed a debate between the principal
involved in a historic U.S. Supreme Court decision this year
backing school administrators in censoring student publications.
   Robert Reynolds, principal of Hazelwood East High School in St.
Louis said he censored articles in the school paper as a way to
prevent inaccuracies, guard privacy and maintain control of
students.
   Reynolds said the support he has received from educators and
parents around the country since the case began five years ago
``seems to send a clear message that many people think we have lost
control of their schools.''
   ``I do not believe I have the right to trample on student
rights,'' said Reynolds. ``But what we have done is to require
educators to exercise their judgment. ... Our interest should be
bringing a clarification of the purpose of student expression.''
   Reynolds debated David Hawpe, editor of The Courier-Journal of
Louisville, Ky.
   Hawpe, who has been with The Courier-Journal for 18 years and
was introduced as the editor of his elementary, high school and
college newspapers, said any censorship of student newspapers
threatens the First Amendment.
   ``It's a serious assault on the conventional wisdom once
embraced by the courts,'' Hawpe said. ``It gave school officials
breathtaking powers over school journalists.''
   The convention also included a discussion of media ethics with
editors and Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn and Philadelphia Mayor W.
Wilson Goode.
   The moderator, Michael Josephson, had questioned all the
panelists when he asked Flynn a complicated question about a
situation involving a reporter deciding whether to go off the
record.
   ``I thought I was just here to give greetings from the city of
Boston,'' replied Flynn, who later joined in the debate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
