<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APME-StudentsCensored     10-20 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-APME-Students Censored,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Principal, Journalist Spar over Student Newspaper Censorship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A principal whose censorship of the high school
newspaper was upheld in a landmark U.S. Supreme Court ruling told
newspaper editors he vetoed sensitive articles to prevent
inaccuracies, guard privacy and maintain control of students.
   Robert Reynolds, principal of Hazelwood East High School in St.
Louis, made his remarks Wednesday during a debate with David Hawpe,
editor of The (Louisville, Ky.) Courier-Journal, at the Associated
Press Managing Editors convention.
   Reynolds said the support he has received from educators and
parents around the country since the case began five years ago
``seems to send a clear message that many people think we have lost
control of their schools.''
   ``I do not believe I have the right to trample on student
rights,'' said Reynolds. ``But what we have done is to require
educators to exercise their judgment. ... Our interest should be
bringing a clarification of the purpose of student expression.''
   The Supreme Court ruled in January that Reynolds did not violate
students' free speech rights by ordering two pages containing
articles on teen pregnancy and divorce deleted from an issue of a
student-produced newspaper five years ago.
   Hawpe, who has been with The Courier-Journal 18 years and was
introduced as the editor of his elementary, high school and college
newspapers, said any censorship of student newspapers threatens the
First Amendment.
   ``It's a serious assault on the conventional wisdom once
embraced by the courts,'' Hawpe said. ``It gave school officials
breathtaking powers over school journalists.''
   Hawpe compared the ruling to state censorship.
   ``We ought to be teaching children about the diversity of
ideas,'' he said. ``But we aren't teaching them. We should teach
them that the Constitution is a living document, not a piece of
parchment.''
   Reynolds said he decided to delete the material because of
inaccuracies in the articles and his belief that they violated the
privacy of those mentioned in the stories.
   ``When it's Friday the 13th and Ferris Bueller's the editor of
your school newspaper, your luck runs out,'' said Reynolds. ``It
becomes more than just a case of students' rights alone. ...
Excellence in school journalism will survive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
