<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Seek Assurance From Reagan Over Safety of Weapons
Reactors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen lawmakers want assurances from
President Reagan that problem-plagued U.S. weapons plants are being
operated safely before reactors now shut down are restarted.
   ``Restoration of safe operations and reliable production are
essential to the defense and security of our nation,'' the 12
congressmen said in a letter to Reagan released Wednesday.
   The Energy Department shut the only active weapons reactor at
the Savannah River plant near Aiken, S.C., in August after the
plant operator, Du Pont Co., ignored an unexplained power surge
while restarting the reactor.
   ``Unless we solve the current problems at U.S. defense
production facilities like Savannah River, we will provide the
ultimate unilateral concession _ the unilateral disarming of our
nuclear deterrent,'' said Rep. Bill Clinger, R-Pa., one of the
lawmakers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Passes Video Privacy ``Bork Bill''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House, in a move prompted by a news story
last year during hearings on the nomination of Robert Bork to the
Supreme Court, has approved legislation designed to protect the
privacy of video store customers.
   The measure was approved by voice vote Wednesday and sent to
President Reagan.
   The Video Privacy Protection Act, which cleared the Senate last
week, was written after a weekly Washington, D.C., newspaper
published the video rental records of Bork, whose nomination was
the subject of a lengthy and bitter battle in the Senate.
   Bork and members of the Senate Judiciary Committee, which was
conducting the nomination hearing, expressed outrage at what they
said was a violation of Bork's privacy.
