<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito     10-20 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Discharges More Blood, Condition Deteriorates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito, bedridden for a month with an
intestinal hemorrhage, discharged more blood today, and the palace
said his kidney and other organ functions were deteriorating.
   The world's oldest living monarch coughed up blood Wednesday for
the first time in a month and discharged more from his bowels
shortly after. Palace spokesman Kenji Maeda reported fresh bleeding
from the bowels today and said the pace of the discharges was
quickening.
   Hirohito vomited a large quantity of blood Sept. 19 and has
received almost daily transfusions totaling more than 21 pints
since then.
   Maeda said the copious transfusions were producing a rapid
heartbeat and admitted without elaboration that they were harming
Hirohito's kidney functions.
   The emperor's daughter, Atsuko Ikeda, told reporters Wednesday
that the 87-year-old emperor barely responded during a five-minute
visit and coughed repeatedly.
   Meanwhile, Crown Princess Michiko, wife of Crown Prince Akihito,
scaled down celebrations for her 54th birthday today out of
deference to her ailing father-in-law.
   Michiko canceled a traditional birthday news conference and
planned a quiet gathering with members of the imperial family, a
palace official said. She and Akihito made their daily visit to
Hirohito's bedside this morning.
</TEXT>
