<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     10-20 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Proposes New Korea With Its Rival South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea has proposed creating a new
non-aligned Korean nation in which the communist north and its
enemy, the capitalist south, would peacefully co-exist.
   North Korea's deputy foreign minister, Kang Sok Ju, told the
43rd General Assembly that the new nation would ``realize national
reunification, leaving the two social systems in the north and the
south as they are.''
   ``There is no hidden attempt to insinuate `unification through
communization' and no intention to impose our ideas and system on
the other side,'' Kang said Wednesday.
   South Korea's U.N. mission said in a statement, ``We think the
North Korean delegation's speech this morning appears to be a
compilation of their past proposals.''
   Gen. Vernon Walters, the permanent U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, said, ``I don't think there were any new elements except
the tone; the tone was considerably more conciliatory.''
   The Korean peninsula was divided at the end of World War II,
when the Soviets ended Japanese occuption in the north and the
Allies landed in the south.
   The new Korea, which Kang called ``the Democratic Confederal
Republic of Koryo,'' would have a national assembly with an equal
number of representives from the north and south.
   Kang said the proposal was first suggested by North Korea's
President Kim il-Sung in 1980, and reiterated this September.
   Koryo was one of three nations on the Korean peninsula 600 years
ago, preceding the Lee dynasty that unified the three countries and
lasted 500 years before Japan annexed Korea.
   Kang said the new Koryo would abolish former military alliances
and treaties, have a unified military command, and dissolve the
demarcation line dividing north from south at the 38th Parallel.
   The new nation also would be the sole representative of the
entire peninsula in diplomatic relations with other nations, and
hold the sole Korean seat in the United Nations, he added.
   Both Koreas currently hold non-voting observer status in the
General Assembly, and speak to the assembly by special invitation.
   Koryo would be a neutral, non-aligned nation, and the peninsula
would become a nuclear-free zone and ban the presence of foreign
troops, Kang said.
   On Tuesday, South Korean President Roh Tae-woo called for a
summit meeting with Kim to adopt a non-aggression pact, but also
told the General Assembly that before reunification could occur,
mutual trust between the nations must be established.
   Roh is to meet President Reagan today in Washington. The South
Korean leader is expected to ask Washington to improve its
relations with North Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0058 </DOCNO>
