<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TV-WarandRemembrance     10-20 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-War and Remembrance,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Expects to Lose $20 Million on `War and Remembrance'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC expects to lose $20 million on the 32-hour
miniseries ``War and Remembrance'' due in part to author Herman
Wouk's restrictions on advertising, says Cap Cities-ABC Chairman
John S. Murphy.
   The restrictions on products that can advertised and the number
of commercial minutes per hour were written into Wouk's contract
for the 1983 miniseries based on his novel ``Winds of War,'' before
Cap Cities bought ABC three years ago.
   ``War and Remembrance,'' the sequel, cost $110 million to
produce.
   ABC is limited to six minutes of national advertising per hour
and is prohibited from promoting its own shows.
   ABC Television Network President John Sias, who joined Murphy on
Wednesday at a session with television critics, said Wouk won't
allow advertising of food or personal care products and of retail
stores.
   ``If I go on, I'm going to break down in tears,'' Sais said.
   ``If we don't do well with it, it's certainly something we'll
take a bath with financially, because we'll have makegoods, but
we've had those before and we'll survive,'' said Murphy, referring
to free advertising time the network has to give advertisers if the
show doesn't live up to ratings guarantees.
   He would not say what rating the network is promising
advertisers, but said the $20 million loss estimate was based on
the presumption of selling out commercial time and meeting the
guarantee.
   Sias said Murphy had tried to change Wouk's mind, but had only
received ``very eloquent turn-downs.''
   ``He's a very, very special man,'' Murphy said. ``We would be
delighted to make some sort of financial arrangement if that would
help, but it's strictly a matter of principle. He's a very unusual
man.''
</TEXT>
