<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Australia-SovietSpy     10-20 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-Soviet Spy,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spy Claim Is Bogus, Soviet Diplomat Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's No. 2 man in
Australia has denied a published report that he belongs to a KGB
spy ring, saying he is simply a career diplomat.
   ``I am not a member of the KGB. I am not being employed to
collect all sorts of intelligence about the Pacific,'' said Valery
Zemskov, minister-counsellor and second-in-charge of the Soviet
embassy.
   Zemskov called the allegation, made in the November issue of
Reader's Digest magazine of Australia, ``silly, ridiculous and
preposterous.'' He said the allegation could damage Soviet
relations with Australia if taken seriously.
   Reader's Digest senior editor John Barron said Zemskov belongs
to a highly secretive spy ring that is known to only a few people
outside the ruling Politburo.
   Barron has written books on the Soviet and American intelligence
services.
   Barron, writing in Reader's Digest, said Zemskov is a member of
the Special Reserve, which he said is a network of agents trained
to spy on foreigners as well as their own colleagues.
   ``We diplomats sometimes thrive on publicity,'' Zemskov told
reporters Wednesday. ``I am not a full colonel of the KGB. I'm not
acting for any other socialist countries. I am not a double agent
for the CIA or ASIO (Australian intelligence) or any other secret
service. I am employed as minister counsel in the embassy. Well, I
am really liking my job.''
   The opposition Liberal Party has called for Zemskov's explusion,
saying he may have gained damaging information from senior Foreign
Affairs officials that could affect Australia's foreign policy. The
party did not elaborate.
   Officials of Foreign Affairs and the Australian Intelligence and
Security Organization refused comment.
</TEXT>
