<DOCNO> AP881020-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StudentLockup     10-20 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Student Lockup,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mock Lockup Draws Praise from Students, Complaints from Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEATON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents said they were outraged by a
27-hour high school field trip during which youths were
strip-searched, hog-tied and forced to eat fish-head soup to
simulate life under a Third-World despot.
   ``This is not anything I would have signed a consent for,''
Connie Northrop said at a school board meeting Monday.
   Her son was among 34 Wheaton North High School juniors and
seniors who participated in the mock lockup.
   She said she unaware that when she gave her son written
permission to participate he would be hog-tied and left in a room
naked and alone for 2{ hours for refusing to eat fish-head soup.
   The optional field trip to Wheaton College during the Columbus
Day weekend was intended to give students a taste of
criminal-justice systems, including that of an imagined Third World
country.
   ``This is an outrage. The word `outrage' doesn't even begin to
touch how I feel,'' said another parent, Kay McKeen, whose child
did not participate.
   The Board of Education has asked school administrators to
re-evaluate the program, arranged by high school American
government teacher David Oliphant, and report back by Nov. 14.
   ``I believe conceptually it's a very good one (program), but we
certainly can improve on our communication on some of the
specifics'' of what students were to be subjected to, said school
board President James Carr.
   Among those specifics of the program were being strip-searched,
handcuffed, eating fish-head soup and hearing chants of ``You're
the scum of the earth,'' and ``You're dirty.''
   Oliphant declined to comment other than to say it had become a
``media circus.''
   Students who participated were almost unanimous in their praise.
   ``I'm shaking, I'm so angry at these parents,'' said senior
Kelly Kyler, 18. ``It's not that I ever wanted to go to prison. But
now I have a view of what these (incarcerated) people went through.
I learned about myself.
   ``I think it's very unfair Mr. Oliphant has got to go through
this.''
   Some parents agreed.
   ``I would like to say the teacher in question has been my
senior's most inspiring teacher so far,'' said Chris Sietz.
   ``The intent of the program was to have the young people learn
and gain an appreciation for our system of democracy and our system
of laws,'' Carr said. ``Also to give them somewhat of an
understanding of what it would be like to be in prison other than
perhaps in Du Page County. Example: a Third World situation.''
   The simulation was held on the fifth floor of the Billy Graham
Center in connection with the Christian school's Institute for
Prison Ministries.
   Students from the college have participated in simulated lockups
through the sociology department since 1983. Other high school
students have gone through it, and it has been the topic of feature
stories in the Chicago Tribune and the Chronicle of Higher
Education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
