<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-20 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar And Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices rose moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 127.15 yen, up 0.30 yen from the previous
day's close of 126.85 yen. Opening at 127.46 yen, the currency
moved slightly lower while ranging mainly between 127.05 yen and
127.53 yen.
   The U.S. currency started trading higher in the wake of the
stronger dollar on Wall Street overnight, following the rebound of
oil prices and news the United States did not want the dollar to
decline further, dealers said.
   Although speculative investors bought dollars in early trading,
the currency failed to recover much due to the wait-and-see mood
that dominated the market, they said.
   ``The market lacked fresh incentives to inspire trading today,''
said a dealer with a major commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymtiy.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average gained
96.88 points, or 0.35 percent, to close at 27,390.55. The index
gained 33.36 points shortly after the market opened and continued
rising. The Nikkei closed Wednesday at 27,293.67 points.
   Trading today was mainly affected by the Bank of Japan's
approval of lower interest rates for short term transactions, said
Manji Ueda of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage firm.
   ``Since all the economic factors including lower interest rates,
the money supply in the market and company achievements have been
good, it is only natural for the share prices to rise,'' Ueda said.
   But as long as uncertainty persists over ailing Emperor
Hirohito's health, which has already dampened market activity, the
index is unlikely to recover quickly.
   In active trading today with volume on the first section
estimated at 1 billion shares, steels and oil issues were among the
most traded issues.
</TEXT>
