<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-GrantTribute 1stLd-Writethru a0505 10-20 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Grant Tribute, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0505,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribute to Late Actor Cary Grant Benefits Princess Grace
Foundation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, ``He was always ...'' to clear garble.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY LYON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood blue bloods and real
royalty mingled in a gala tribute to the late actor Cary Grant to
benefit the Princess Grace Foundation.
   Grant starred with then-actress Grace Kelly in the 1955 thriller
``To Catch a Thief.''
   Wednesday night's black-tie affair at the Beverly Hilton's
International Ballroom drew the royal family of Monaco and many of
Hollywood's top names.
   The guest list included Quincy Jones, Sophia Loren, Henry
Mancini, Dean Martin, Sammy Davis Jr., Liza Minnelli, Warren
Beatty, Shirley Temple Black, Michael Caine, John Forsythe, Walter
Matthau, Dina Merrill, Robert Mitchum, Roger Moore, Gregory Peck,
Eva Marie Saint, Frank Sinatra, Jimmy Stewart and Robert Wagner.
   Grant's widow, Barbara, and his daughter, Jennifer, decided the
event would be the sole tribute to the actor, who died in 1986 at
age 82.
   ``Jennifer Grant and I wanted there to be just one special
tribute to Cary, and due to his close friendship with Princess
Grace and her family, we decided the proceeds from the evening
should benefit the foundation named in her honor, which favors
emerging young film, theater, and dance artists throughout America
with scholarships, apprenticeships, fellowships and special
grants,'' Mrs. Grant said in a statement.
   Princess Grace, who left acting behind when she married Prince
Rainier of Monaco, died in 1982 from injuries in a car accident.
   The prince, along with his son, Albert, and daughter Stephanie
were among those greeting the guests, all who shared anecdotes
about Grant, the embodiment of the class act in Hollywood.
   ``He was my first date when I came to America,'' gushed Eva
Gabor.
   ``He was always kind, gentle, funny,'' said actress Polly
Bergen. ``I think Cary was the ultimate gentleman, the ultimate
elegant man. He was the single, most elegant man I ever saw. Even
dressed casually lolling on a plane, he was always the dream of the
world; kind funny, tender, elegant.''
   ``Dynasty'' star Linda Evans said: ``He was just as charming off
screen as he was on.''
   ``I knew Cary Grant since I was a kid,'' said actor Robert Stack.
   ``He represented to me, growing up as a young actor, everything
that every actor wants to be and seldom does.''
</TEXT>
