<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Buddhists     10-20 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Buddhists,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buddhist Monks' Death Sentence Prompts Australian Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Buddhist monks have been
sentenced to death in Vietnam for alleged subversive activities and
Australia has filed a protest with the Vietnamese government,
Foreign Minister Gareth Evans said.
   Evans said he instructed the Australian ambassador in Hanoi to
protest the death sentences after finding out the monks had been
condemned to death following a trial in Ho Chi Minh City in late
September.
   The monks, Thich Tue Si, a philosopher, writer and teacher, and
Thich Tri Sieu, an eminent scholar, were arrested in 1984 with 19
Buddhist scholars. The monks were sentenced to death, while the
scholars were given undisclosed terms of imprisonment.
   The exact nature of the allegedly subversive activity was not
immediately known.
   The Foreign Ministry said the Vietnamese community in Australia
asked Sen. Margaret Reid to take up the issue after reading of the
sentences in a Vietnamese newspaper earlier this month. The
ministry said Ms. Reid then brought the matter to Evans' attention.
   Evans said Ambassador Graham Alliband was told to take the
matter up with the appropriate Vietnamese authorities, ``making it
clear, as we have with a number of other instances around the
world, the Australian Government's abhorrence of and complete
opposition to capital punishment.''
</TEXT>
