<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0631EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SKorea-Torture     10-20 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SKorea-Torture,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Leader Claims He Was Tortured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent dissident leader told
National Assembly members that he was tortured and forced to
confess that he was a communist, officials said today.
   Testifying under oath before the National Assembly's Home
Affairs Committee Wednesday, Kim Keun-tae recounted 23 days of
alleged police torture he had undergone in 1987, the officials said.
   ``I was forced to sign a false statement that I was helping
North Korea, and I am still suffering from the after-effect of
police torture,'' the officials quoted Kim as saying.
   Kim, then head of the Youth League for Democratization, was
found guilty of anti-state charges and sentenced to five years'
imprisonment in 1985. He was released in June under a special
amnesty.
   Kim drew international attention after he won the 1987 Robert
Kenndy Human Rights Award.
   After his release, Kim filed a lawsuit against several police
officers who allegedly tortured him during the investigation. On
Wednesday, he was summoned to testify before the National Assembly.
   According to the officials, Kim, 35, said he was arrested by
police in September 1987 without a warrant. He said he only fought
for democracy and had no connection with communist North Korea.
   For several weeks under police detention, Kim said he was denied
contact with his lawyer and family in violation with law and
subject to torture.
   ``I was tortured twice with water and eight times with electric
shocks,'' Kim said.
   Police wrapped his body in a blanket, tied him with ropes and
covered his face with a towel, over which water was dripped so that
he had to drink until he became almost unconscious, he said.
   The investigators then sent electric shocks through his body, he
said.
   ``The pain was so acute and unbearable I kept on shouting that
they would kill me,'' he was quoted as saying.
   A police officer, who also testified to the same Assembly
committee, denied that he and his colleagues had tortured Kim.
   Kim's case resurfaced as the National Assembly continued to
scrutinize state affairs under a parliamentary prerogative, revived
for the first time in 16 years under a new constitution adopted in
a national referendum late last year.
   The parliamentary investigation is focusing on corruption, human
rights violations and irregularities allegedly committed under the
government of former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   Chun, who stepped down in February at the end of a seven-year
term, has come under a parliamentary probe of his alleged
involvement in financial and other scandals.
   Chun's younger brother, Chun Kyung-hwan, was recently sentenced
to seven years' imprisonment for taking bribes and misusing
millions of dollars in government money while he headed a rural
development program.
   The three major opposition groups are jointly moving to subpoena
the ex-president to testify before the Assembly, but the government
camp objects to the move.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
