<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NaziAsylum     10-20 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nazi Asylum,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany Arrests Alleged War Criminal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUENSTER, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities say they have arrested
a former U.S. resident who faces a death penalty in the Soviet
Union for allegedly killing Latvian women and children during World
War II.
   Boleslav Maikovskis, 83, was being investigated ``in connection
with charges of murder and attempted murder,'' said Klaus Schacht,
a prosecutor with Dortmund's war crimes investigation office.
   The announcement that Maikovskis was arrested Wednesday came
just one day after officials said he had applied for political
asylum in West Germany after fleeing the United States last year.
   Maikovskis, a former head of a Latvian police force created by
the Nazis, is accused by the Soviets of burning down villages in
addition to fatally shooting women and children. In 1965, the
Soviets sentenced Maikovskis to death in absentia for his alleged
war crimes.
   Schacht said Maikovskis was being held in a prison hospital, but
did not specify where.
   ``He needs constant doctors' care,'' Schacht told The Associated
Press today. He said he would release further details at a news
conference later today.
   Maikovskis had been living in Mineola, N.Y. since 1951 and but
had been fighting deportation proceedings in recent years. On
Friday, the U.S. Justice Department acknowledged that he fled the
country and that it had lost track of him.
   Maikovskis was picked up at his residence in Muenster early
Wednesday after officials decided he might attempt to flee West
Germany, Schacht said.
   Investigators were basing their initial probe on evidence
presented at another war crimes trial in West Germany in 1976
during which Maikovskis ``was mentioned several times.''
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov said Tuesday
in Moscow that the Soviets are ``ready to give all the necessary
information'' to West Germany.
   Schacht said that his office would welcome any assistance from
Moscow. He declined to speculate on whether Maikovskis would be
deported to the Soviet Union.
   Schacht said prosecutors are checking 20 volumes of court
records relating to the war crimes case in which Maikovskis had
been mentioned.
   He said Maikovskis entered the country on a passport issued by
the Latvian government in exile, which is recognized by West
Germany.
   On Tuesday, the Nuremberg-based federal office for political
asylum requests said Maikovskis applied for asylum about a year
ago. A decision on the request is expected by late November.
   Maikovskis probably has been living in West Germany since
submitting the request in November 1987, said federal asylum office
spokesman Wolfgang Weickhardt. Decisions on asylum requests
normally take a year.
   The United States began deportation proceedings against
Maikovskis in 1976. His final appeal was denied by the U.S. Supreme
Court in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
