<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PlasticTax     10-20 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plastic Tax,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chamber Votes To Impose Tax On Plastic Bags</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Committee of the Chamber of
Deputies has voted overwhelmingly to impose a 13-cent tax on
plastic shopping bags to discourage their use.
   The decision to tax plastic shopping bags must be put to a vote
by the full Chamber and the Senate, but passage was expected
because all the major parties supported the Wednesday's measure.
   Most supermarkets already charge consumers for each plastic bag,
usually 7 cents. Some shoppers bring their own bags to supermarkets
so they don't have to pay extra to take home their purchases.
   Under the proposal, supermarkets would begin charging customers
around 21 cents per plastic bag. Other stores would charge 13 cents
a bag.
   The proposed law comes at a time when Italy is struggling with
garbage disposal problems.
   The vote was 22-5, unlikely political allies _ the
environmentalist Greens and the neo-fascist Italian Social Movement
_ voting for it, the Italian news agency AGI reported. The ``no''
votes were cast by Italy's largest party, the Christian Democrats,
which is pressing for a tax on all plastic.
   Assoplast, the producers association for the plastics industry,
said in a statement that the measure ``doesn't resolve in the least
the environmental problems connected with plastic bags, which only
pollute in the sense that they can be an eyesore, and make up only
7-8 percent of urban garbage.''
</TEXT>
