<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     10-20 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Preschool Molest,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McMartin Molest Case Defense Opens With Lawyer Testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense opened in the McMartin pre-school
molestation trial with a attorney calling himself as the first
witness to attack a jailhouse informant's credibility.
   Danny Davis, attorney for principal defendant Raymond Buckey,
took the stand Wednesday seeking to prove that his client never
confessed to the informant that he had sexually abused children.
   Buckey, 30, and his 61-year-old mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey,
are charged with 65 molestation and conspiracy counts in the case
of the school where children said they were molested and subjected
to bizarre satanic rites. The Manhattan Beach school was closed
five years ago.
   The prosecution alleges Buckey and his mother molested children,
but the defense has said it will show that if children were
sexually abused, it happened elsewhere and people other than the
defendants did it.
   During his unusual testimony, Davis insisted he had no memory of
the events he was testifying about. He referred instead to a memo
he dictated.
   The tactic was apparently used so that Davis could avoid
violating his attorney-client privilege with Buckey by abstaining
from references to conversations between the two men that
prosecutors might want to explore in questioning.
   ``I don't independently recall the conversation without
referring to the document,'' said Davis, referring to a memo
written after interviewing both Buckey and the informant, George
Freeman, at the county jail on March 28, 1984.
   Davis recalled that he went to the jail when he heard that
Buckey had been moved into a cell with another prisoner. He said he
was concerned for Buckey's physical safety.
   ``I was also concerned that Mr. Freeman might be an individual
who would concoct a story about my client,'' Davis said.
   Freeman, a convicted felon and jailhouse informant who testified
early in the 17-month trial, claimed that Buckey confessed to him
about molesting a child. The informant also contended that Davis
tried to intimidate him.
   In his jailhouse visit, Davis said Freeman ``did tell me some
things that he said my client had told him.''
   ``Did Freeman indicate that Mr. Buckey made any statements about
having relations with children?'' asked attorney Edward Rucker, who
was brought in to conduct the witness stand examination.
   ``No, he did not,'' said Davis.
   ``Did Mr. Freeman indicate that Ray Buckey denied wrongdoing?''
   ``Yes, he did,'' said Davis.
   Davis further said Freeman spoke of having been a Hell's Angel
and said he had ``lied as a snitch before.''
   He said Buckey admitted discussing the case with Freeman and
telling the informant that it was ``a setup.''
   But specifics of the conversations were not related because of
attorney-client privilege. The prosecution did not get a chance to
cross-examine.
   Later, Davis adamantly denied that he had ever threatened
Freeman.
   ``I didn't do that,'' he said under questioning by Mrs. Buckey's
lawyer, Dean Gits.
   Another issue argued Wednesday was whether jurors should be
taken to see the former school. Prosecutors objected because they
said the defense has removed shrubbery which blocked people from
looking inside.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
