<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     10-20 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Temporarily Suspends Operations Against Militants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today suspended
military operations against anti-government Sinhalese militants for
one week and said it would soon release 788 political prisoners.
   National Security Minister Lalith Athulathmudali said both moves
were aimed at restoring peace on this island nation, racked by five
years of ethnic violence.
   The minister said the changes would ``give a chance to those
involved in political murders to stop those acts and get on to more
democratic forms of protest.''
   ``This step has been taken by the government purely to save
innocent lives,'' Athulathmudali said.
   The People's Liberation Front, an extremist Sinhalese group
opposed to the government's peace overtures with the minority
Tamils, have been accused of killing at least 500 people the past
year.
   Most victims have been government supporters and people trying
to make peace with Tamil extremists fighting for a separate nation
in the northeastern province.
   The minister also said the government would expedite the release
of the 788 political prisoners against whom charges have yet to be
filed.
   The People's Liberation Front led by Rohana Wijeweera, a medical
dropout from Moscow's Patrice Lumumba University, is opposed to an
India-brokered peace accord because it claims the pact gives too
many concessions to Tamils who comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people.
   There was no immediate reaction on the government's offer.
   The accord, signed in 1987, calls for greater autonomy for
provincial councils in the northeastern district where Tamils are
in a majority. Under terms of the accord, the north and eastern
provinces were merged into a single adminstrative unit.
   The pact has, however, failed to stop bloodshed in Sri Lanka
after the most important of the Tamil rebels groups, the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, reneged after initially agreeing on its
terms, saying it did not meet their aspirations.
   India has an estimated 47,000 troops in Sri Lanka to disarm the
Tamil militants and enforce the accord. India got involved because
60 million politically powerful Tamils in southern Tamil Nadu state
are sympathetic to the rebel cause.
</TEXT>
