<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased in quiet European trading today,
pressured by lack of interest from market participants and
technical factors, foreign currency dealers said. Gold prices rose.
   Traders said the dollar dropped from the levels it reached in
earlier Asian trading as corporate market players filled their
daily requirements and withdrew from the market.
   They said the dollar is likely to continue trading in a narrow
range until economic developments or statements by American
policy-makers create enough momentum to move the currency one way
or the other.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 127.15 yen, up 0.30 yen. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 126.77 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8036 West German marks, down from 1.8115
   _1.5230 Swiss francs, down from 1.5275
   _6.1625 French francs, down from 6.1710
   _2.0377 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0380
   _1,343.90 Italian lire, down from 1,347.625
   _1.1995 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7610, more than 1 cent
higher than late Wednesday's $1.7515.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $412 a troy ounce, up
from $411.05 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $411.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $411.50, up from $410 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 1.56 to close at a bid $414.49.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.34 a troy
ounce, little changed from Wednesday's $6.35.
