<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Kenya-BBCArrests     10-20 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kenya-BBC Arrests,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest BBC Producers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested two British Broadcasting
Corp. producers and held them for 24 hours, a colleague said today.
The arrests came four days after President Daniel arap Moi accused
the BBC of supporting subversives in Kenya.
   The BBC employee, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
plainclothes officers Tuesday night took Ali Saleh, a Tanzanian,
and Ruth Thorlby, a Briton, from Midland Hotel in Nakuru, 100 miles
northwest of Nairobi, and kept them in cells for eight hours.
   John Tusa, BBC world service managing director, who was in
Nairobi, immediately protested the police action.
   ``The BBC deeply regrets the Kenya Police action in interferring
with its normal journalistic and publicity activities,'' Tusa said
in a statement Wednesday night.
   Saleh and Thorlby are in Kenya to interview listeners about the
reception of a recently refurbished BBC's relay station in the
Indian Ocean island republic of Seychelles.
   Police took Saleh and Thorlby to an unidentified government
building and questioned them about their Nakuru visit, the BBC
employee said, and then took them to a police station and locked
them in cells.
   Earlier in the day, Saleh and Thorlby had met government
officials and school teachers.
   ``No one told them what was happening,'' the colleague said.
   Saleh and Thorlby on Wednesday evening were driven to the
Criminal Investigation Department in Nairobi, the Kenyan capital.
They were handed back their personal belongings, including
passports and money, and ordered to report back on Friday. Police
kept their recording equipment and BBC promotional posters.
   Kenya regularly criticizes the foreign media, and in recent past
has singled out the BBC's coverage of the East Affrican nation.
   Moi, in a speech marking the 10th anniversary of his presidency
Oct. 14, criticized the BBC and said it supports subversives.
   Tusa had earlier defended the London-based organization and said
that efforts to get the offical view on events were hampered by the
inaccessibility of government officials and their reluctance to be
interviewed.
   Moi said Tusa had said ``BBC has been accurate, factual and
true. I agree. They have been accurate, factual, true in supporting
subversives.''
   Tusa issued a statement rejecting the charge and regretted the
``unwarranted escalation of attacks on our journalism.''
</TEXT>
