<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Elections 1stLd-Writethru a0526 10-20 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Elections, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0526,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Groups Plan National Protest On Election Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEDES with 2 grafs to CLARIFY that protest scheduled for next
Wednesday. PICKS up 3rd graf, `State-of-emergency regulations .. .'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid organizations
today called for a nationwide protest on the final day of voting in
segregated municipal elections.
   Officials of churches, trade unions and human rights groups said
in a statement that the protest next Wednesday was intended to
demonstrate opposition to ``these apartheid elections in the
clearest possible way.''
   State-of-emergency regulations prohibit calls for politically
motivated strikes and work stoppages, but previous national
protests during the 28-month-old emergency have taken the form of
widespread general strikes.
   The government has outlawed calls for an election boycott. This
prohibition has been defied openly by anti-apartheid clergymen,
including Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
   Wednesday is officially designated as Election Day, but the
government, seeking to maximize the turnout, has allowed voters to
cast votes in advance during a 12-day period ending Saturday.
   The elections mark the first time South Africans of all races
are voting at the same time, and the government depicts the
balloting as an important extension of democracy. Anti-apartheid
groups disagree, saying black municipal councils are
government-controlled and rejecting participation in local
elections until blacks get voting rights on the national level.
   ``The municipal elections are undemocratic, fradulent and
unjust,'' said Titus Mafolo, an official of the banned United
Democratic Front, at a news conference announcing the protest.
``These elections are being forced on our people by the security
forces, the state propaganda system and collaborators.''
   In Soweto, the largest black township, less than 4 percent of
the 347,000 registered voters had voted as of Wednesday, officials
said. Nico Malan, the white town clerk who oversees Soweto, said he
would be satisified with a final turnout of 20 percent.
   In several large townships, no elections are taking place
because of a lack of candidates. Elsewhere, black candidates' homes
have been bombed in what the government says is an intimidation
campaign waged by the outlawed African National Congress.
   The main focus of the white election is the contest between the
governing National Party and the extreme-right Conservative Party,
which seeks to intensify segregation laws. The Conservatives are
favored to outpoll the Nationalists in Transvaal, the most populous
of the four provinces.
   Earlier this year, in an effort to placate conservative whites,
the government drafted a bill to tighten enforcement of the Group
Areas Act, which mandates residential segregation. On Wednesday,
President P.W. Botha postponed action the bill, leaving little
chance it could become law before Election Day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
