<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Zaire     10-20 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Zaire,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zaire's Foreign Minister Postpones Visit To South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scheduled visit today by
Zaire's foreign minister has been postponed indefinitely, the
government announced.
   South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha said the three-day
visit by his counterpart from Zaire, Nguza Karl-I-Bond, was
postponed due to ``unforseen circumstances.'' There was no
elaboration and no firm indication whether the visit would be
rescheduled.
   There have been unconfirmed reports the Zairean delegation
requested meetings with leading black opponents of the government,
including jailed African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela
and Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
   In recent weeks, South Africa has launched an ambitious
diplomatic offensive to ease its long-standing isolation from the
rest of Africa.
   President P.W. Botha, who has been in power since 1978, had not
held a summit in black Africa until he met last month with
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano. Botha has followed up that
trip with visits to Malawi, Zaire and the Ivory Coast.
   He pronoucned his Oct. 1 meeting with Zaire's President Mobutu
Sese Seko a success, although no joint agreements were announced.
Mobutu said afterward that Botha had promised that Mandela would
soon be released unconditionally, but South African authorities
have refused to confirm this.

