<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0815EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FordFight     10-20 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford Fight,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settlement Approved In Ford Trust Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a year after auto tycoon
Henry Ford II's death, his family apparently has settled its
squabble over the $350 million trust he left behind.
   Following weeks of discussion among more than a dozen lawyers,
the Ford family hopes to move quickly from the public eye, said
Ford's son, Edsel Ford II.
   ``My father was a very personal man, as is the Ford family, and
my father would have found these proceedings very unpleasant,'' he
said. ``I'm just happy it's over.''
   The pact gives Ford's widow and third wife, Kathleen DuRoss
Ford, at least $10 million this year and a minimum of $1.5 million
in subsequent years. She also receives the couple's homes in Palm
Beach, Grosse Pointe, Mich., and London, and rights to purchase
three other Ford residences.
   The two-page accord approved Wednesday by Palm Beach Circuit
Judge Vaughn Rudnick appeared satisfactory to Mrs. Ford's foes in
the dispute, her stepson Edsel and her late husband's financial
adviser, William H. Donaldson.
   Donaldson, a New York investment banker, will receive $1 million
for his first year of service and $550,000 for the next two years.
He will resign after three years, according to the settlement.
   As the dispute was settled, Mrs. Ford was in England and Edsel
Ford was in Detroit.
   ``This means it's all put to bed,'' said Robert Montgomery, Mrs.
Ford's attorney. ``I think all parties are satisfied.''
   Attorneys disclosed some terms of the settlement Tuesday and
Edsel Ford confirmed details Wednesday.
   The settlement terms were far more generous to Mrs. Ford than
the provisions in the original trust.
   In the settlement, Mrs. Ford, 48, will receive an annual
allowance equal to 3 percent of the trust, Edsel Ford said. All
parties agreed to abide by that amount, he said.
   Ford's trust, signed May 17, 1984, guaranteed Mrs. Ford an
annual allowance of $1.5 million and any additional funds she
needed to maintain her lifestyle.
   Under the agreement, she said she would stop efforts to have
Donaldson removed as a trustee. Mrs. Ford objected to Donaldson
because he had asked for an annual salary of $1 million.
   Ford died at age 70 on Sept. 29, 1987, in Detroit. He filed his
will in Palm Beach County, his legal residence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
