<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO-Nitze     10-20 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO-Nitze,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nitze Wins NATO's 1988 Atlantic Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Nitze, President Reagan's special
adviser on arms control matters, has been awarded NATO's 1988
Atlantic Award for his consultations with America's allies during
the INF talks, NATO said today.
   The annual award, worth nearly $8,000, goes to Nitze for his
``outstanding contribution to the cohesiveness and strength of the
Western alliance,'' NATO said in a statement.
   He will receive the award at a ceremony at NATO headquarters at
an as yet unspecified date later this year.
   Nitze was selected by a a panel of NATO officials under the
chairmanship of Gabriel Robin, the French ambassador to the
16-nation Western alliance.
   It cited his efforts to brief America's allies on the Geneva
talks that produced the U.S.-Soviet Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces treaty to remove hundreds of medium-range nuclear missiles
from Europe.
   His consultation efforts yielded ``unanimity of support and
cohesion for the final draft of the treaty among all NATO states,''
NATO said.
   ``This unity and cohesion...is essential to the Alliance
partnership for peace. The leadership exemplified by the commitment
of Ambassador Nitze and the high quality and number of his
contributions to the Alliance are precisely the elements that have
made the Allliance so successful in the last 40 years.''
</TEXT>
