<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sawyer'sLimo     10-20 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sawyer's Limo,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Getting A Limo That Critics Say Is Fit For A King</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer will soon be tooling around
town in a new custom limousine, but his opponents may get some
political mileage out of it as well.
   ``This kind of limousine is made for a sheik from Arabia,'' said
Alderman Lawrence Bloom, who will challenge Sawyer in next year's
special election.
   Alderman Edward Burke, another mayoral hopeful, dubbed Sawyer
``Limousine Gene.''
   The limousine, being assembled at a suburban Schaumburg plant,
will replace the city's 10-year-old protocol vehicle, said Howard
Saffold, chief of the mayor's security detail. But he and Sawyer
denied reports of a plush armor-plated vehicle.
   ``That would have cost between $60,000 and $90,000 ... We do not
have an armor-plated, bulletproof car. We can't afford it,'' Sawyer
said.
   Saffold said he didn't know the cost of the car, but that it had
an $8,000 security feature that he would not discuss.
   The new limo will supplement a $28,000 Cadillac Fleetwood sedan
purchased last year for the mayor's everyday use when a 1983 model
ran into maintaince problems, Saffold said.
   The new car, he said, will be used ``to hold kings and queens
from other countries, business people who are either doing business
with Chicago or anticipate doing business in Chicago.''
   During a radio taping Wednesday, Sawyer said his current car
broke down not long ago between appearances. ``I had to wait for
... for half an hour or 45 minutes,'' he said.
   Sawyer, who was made acting mayor in December following the
death of Harold Washington, also said he's getting a car that other
mayors have enjoyed.
   ``It occurs to me that if I'm correct (Richard J.) Daley had a
limousine; Jane Byrne had a limousine. Everybody else had a
limousine,'' he said.
   Asked why he can't use a smaller city car, Sawyer replied,
``Only one person can ride with me, and I don't know whether that's
appropriate for a city this size.''
   New York Mayor Ed Koch has a limousine; Los Angeles Mayor Tom
Bradley is chauffeured in a city sedan.
</TEXT>
