<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-POWs     10-20 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-POWs,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Rejects Iraq's Proposal for Release of Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has rejected an Iraqi plan for
repatriating prisoners of war from the Persian Gulf conflict,
Tehran radio said today.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Iran's parliament
speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani, as saying Iraq must accept a United
Nations-sponsored plan for ending the eight-year war before
prisoner exchanges can start.
   According to the Red Cross, Iran has 50,182 prisoners and Iraq
has 19,284 prisoners. But U.N. officials and diplomats in Iran and
Iraq believe Iran holds 60,000 to 70,000 POWs and Iraq 30,000 to
50,000.
   ``Iraq not doubt realizes the only way to have the prisoners of
war released is not to obstruct U.N. Resolution 598, and if the
Iraqi regime had accepted peace negotiations more than half the
prisoners would have been released by now,'' Rafsanjani was quoted
as telling the House.
   U.N. Resolution 598 calls for an immediate cease-fire,
withdrawal of troops to internationally recognized boundaries and
the exchange of prisoners.
   Iraq earlier this week proposed to the International Red Cross
and U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar that
repatriation of prisoners should begin on humanitarian grounds if
Iran reciprocates.
   But Iraq also made it clear that its offer was unrelated to
peace negotiations, which stalled five days after a cease-fire was
declared in the Iran-Iraq war on Aug. 20.
   Rafsanjani was quoted as saying Iran is willing to ``release the
prisoners of war as soon as possible, but in the framework of
Resolution 598.''
   Iran's ambassador to the United Nations, Mohammed Ja'afar
Mahallati, said in New York on Wednesday that technical issues on
prisoner exchanges must be settled within the framework of the U.N.
resolution. He also said Iran wants withdrawal to internationally
recognized borders to be the next step.
   The peace talks have deadlocked over Iraq's insistence that the
disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms its southern border
with Iran, should be cleared of silt and ships sunk early in the
war.
   Iran has rejected the dredging demand, saying it is a secondary
issue that can be settled later in the negotiations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
