<DOCNO> AP881020-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burundi     10-20 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burundi,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Appoints Ethnic Hutu Prime Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Pierre Buyoya of Burundi
appointed a member of the majority Hutu people prime minister,
Radio Burundi reported today.
   Adrien Simbomana was appointed on Wednesday, about two months
after 5,000 people were killed in fighting between the Hutu and the
Tutsi, the East African nation's dominant ethnic minority.
   Simbomana's 23-member Cabinet is dominated by the Hutu, who hold
13 portfolios. The Tutsi hold 10.
   The state-owned radio, monitored in Nairobi, said Buyoya, a
Tutsi, remained defense minister, a position he held in the
previous government. The powerful post of interior minister went to
Lt. Col. Aloys Kadoyi, another Tutsi.
   Simbomana is a former deputy speaker of the National Assembly
under ousted President Jean-Batiste Bagaza. He is the governor of
Muramvya Province and was recently appointed vice president of the
commission charged with studying the problem of national unity.
   The violence began Aug. 14 when Hutu attacked Tutsi living among
them in the north, hacking hundreds to death with machetes and
burning people alive in huts.
   Soldiers of the Tutsi-dominated military sent to restore order
attacked the Hutu after seeing what had happened to fellow Tutsi.
More than 40,000 people, mainly Hutu, fled to Rwanda, Burundi's
northern neighbor.
   Hutu comprise about 84 percent of Burundi's 5 million people and
the Tutsi 15 percent. The Tutsi have controlled the government and
the military since the tiny landlocked former Belgian colony gained
independence in July 1962.
   Ethnic problems date from the 15th century when the Tutsi, a
tall, Nilotic people, migrated from Ethiopia and imposed feudal
rule on the short, stocky Hutu living in communes.
   Under Belgian rule, the Tutsi maintained their dominant role and
at independence formed the government.
   In 1972, the Hutu tried to overthrow the government, beginning
with a massacre of hundreds of Tutsi. The rebellion was crushed and
the government retaliated by killing between 100,000 and 300,000
Hutu, including most of the tribe's intelligensia, according to
human rights groups.
   Buyoya, in a recent tour of the country's 114 districts, said
last week that some Burundians still harbor ethnic animosity and
want to avenge the August massacres.
   ``Whoever is caught sowing seeds of animosity in any part of the
country will receive severe punishment,'' Buyoya said on Oct. 15.
   Buyoya, 41, seized power in a Sept. 3, 1987, in a bloodless
military coup that toppled Bagaza's 10-year-old government. Bagaza,
a Tutsi, was attending a Francophone summit in Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0851EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-Fire     10-20 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Fire,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Closes Oil Refinery In Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire swept through a large oil refinery
in northern Taiwan today, causing severe damage to the plant and
forcing it to close, officials said. One worker was slightly
injured.
   The fire, which was caused by a leaking pump, occurred at the
state-run Chinese Petroleum Corp., 30 miles west of Taipei, and did
an estimated $6.9 million in damage, company officials said.
   The blaze forced the evacuation of thousands of people living
near the plant and was put out in three hours by firefighters
assisted by helicopters.
   The refinery will be closed for about two months to replace the
equipment destroyed by the fire, officials said.
   The plant produces 30,000 barrels of low sulfur fuel a day, or
about 10 percent of total consumption in Taiwan.
   Kuan Yung-shih, president of Chinese Petroleum, told reporters
his company will increase fuel production at its other refinery in
southern Taiwan and resort to emergency imports to meet the fuel
demands.
</TEXT>
