<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia 2ndLd-Writethru a0514 10-20 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0514,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BELGRADE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Serbs Jeer Party Leaders At Mass Rally</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details of rally. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Serbs jeered Communist
Party leaders today and turned their backs on Politburo members who
tried to speak during a rally in the ethnically troubled province
of Kosovo.
   Taunts of ``Thieves!'' and ``You betrayed the people!'' greeted
Politburo members Marko Orlandic and Kasura Jasari, Kosovo's
Communist Party head, when they arrived to address the Serbs in
Kosovo Polje, a suburb of the Kosovo capital of Pristina.
   The Serbs are unhappy at the outcome of a three-day Central
Committee meeting which, they say, did little to solve the
country's ethnic and economic crisis.
   Students in Kosovo, an autonomous province in the republic of
Serbia, boycotted classes to express their dissatisfaction with the
meeting. The boycott was staged by Slavs, who include both Serbs
and ethnic Montenegrins.
   The rally began with about 5,000 Serbs waving flags, singing
national songs and chanting, ``Central Committee members, you have
shown your true face!''
   At the Central Committee meeting in Belgrade, which ended
Wednesday, a Serbian member of the Poliburo failed to win a vote of
confidence from committee members. It was a blow to the Serbs'
fight for greater control over Kosovo.
   Dusan Ckrebic was the only one of 10 Politburo members facing
the vote who could not muster a majority from the 165-member
Central Committee. He has offered to resign.
   National party chief Stipe Suvar said it was the first time a
member of the Politburo had failed to win such a vote.
   When Orlandic and Jasari arrived, the crowd booed and jeered. At
least one stone was hurled at the podium, but it missed.
   Protesters had hoped the Central Committee would take steps to
protect Kosovo's minority Serbs and Montenegrins from alleged
harassment by the majority Albanians.
   The crowd gathered in a large school field and literally turned
its back on Orlandic and Jasari, moving away from the podium to the
far side of the field.
   After about 15 minutes, local party officials persuaded about
half the crowd to go back to the podium, but the other half left.
   Many in the crowd carried pictures of Serbia's Communist Party
leader, Slobodan Milosevic, and waved Serbian and Communist Party
flags as they sang national songs and chanted, ``Kosovo is
Serbia!'' and ``A strong Serbia is a strong Yugoslavia!''
   Milosevic's drive to impose more Serbian control over Kosovo has
angered fellow Communist leaders. They fear he is using popular
emotion to increase the influence of Serbs, Yugoslavia's largest
ethnic group, in national affairs.
   A Milosevic supporter, Politburo member Vasil Tuporkovski,
implied these leaders had acted in tandem to deliver a blow to
Milosevic by making Ckrebic lose the confidence vote. Ckerbic, a
close ally of Milosevic, received only 68 votes in the secret
ballot. He needed 83.
   An ``unprincipled coalition'' was behind the action, Tuporkovski
said. His charge was reported today by Serbian media.
   Serbs have threatened to leave Kosovo if they are not given more
control over the province, which borders Albania. Ethnic Albanians
make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million population.
   Protesters are also unhappy with Yugoslavia's economic
situation, which is at its worst point since World War II.
Inflation was 217 percent over the past 12 months, unemployment is
15 percent, and the foreign debt is $21 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
