<HEAD>City Council To Consider Curb On Racial, Sexual Slurs By Aldermen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council will consider a resolution
asking aldermen to stop using racial slurs and ethnic or gender
insults, but during a hearing on the measure some aldermen found it
difficult to avoid insulting witnesses.
   The council's Rules Committee on Wednesday approved a proposal
that would establish guidelines for debate and questioning of
witnesses during council committee meetings to assure people of
fair hearings ``without fear of persecution or harassment.''
   Dem Hopkins, the owner of a North Side gay bar, accused some
aldermen of harming the gay community by referring ``to human
beings who happen to be gay as animals and sissies'' during a
recent fight over a proposed human rights ordinance.
   That drew a sharp retort from Alderman George Hagopian, an
outspoken opponent of gay rights legislation.
   ``Do you mean to tell me if I see someone who walks like a duck,
talks like a duck, and acts like a duck, I can't call it that?''
Hagopian asked.
   Hopkins' reply _ ``You call it a person, alderman'' _ was
interrupted by the committee chairwoman, Alderwoman Anna Langford,
who chided Hagopian for being out of order.
   The resolution to curb aldermen's language was introduced by
Alderwoman Kathy Osterman who was upset about the way some aldermen
badgered nominees to the police and school boards on their
religious backgrounds and the derivation of their last name's in
recent hearings.
   The proposed resolution would bar council members from engaging
in irrelevant and inappropriate questioning of witnesses about
their religious preferences, gender, ethnic or cultural backgrounds.
   One alderman, Robert Shaw, complained the proposal would only
``hamstring'' the council's work.
   The full council will consider the measure next week.
</TEXT>
