<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Scandal     10-20 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Scandal,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Recruit-Cosmos Aide Arrested For Bribery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors arrested a former real estate company
executive today for allegedly trying to bribe a lawmaker
investigating an insider trading scandal involving the firm,
Justice Ministry officials said.
   Hiroshi Matsubara, 47, a former top aide to the head of
Recruit-Cosmos Co., was charged with offering cash to Yonosuke
Narazaki of the opposition Social Democratic Alliance, officials
said.
   Prosecutors said Matsubara offered Narazaki the money to cover
up the company's sale of unlisted stock to top politicians and
business leaders who sold the shares after the stock jumped in
value in a public offering.
   Authorities said Matsubara brought a candy box containing
$38,000 to Narazaki on three occasions in August and September and
asked him to relax his investigation.
   One attempt last month was filmed by a Tokyo television network
that Narazaki allowed into his home.
   ``Please save Recruit,'' Matsubara told Narazaki in the footage,
which Nippon Television Network has broadcast repeatedly during
newscasts. ``We understand politics cost money. We intend to
support you for the rest of your political career.''
   Narazaki refused to accept the money and filed a complaint last
month with the Tokyo District Prosecutors' Office against
Matsubara, Recruit-Cosmos President Tomoyuki Ikeda, and Hiromasa
Ezoe, founder of the parent Recruit Co. Ezoe resigned his post
immediately after the scandal broke in July.
   On Wednesday, prosecutors searched the offices of the two
companies and Matsubara's residence and confiscated more than 1,000
boxes of documents.
   ``We believe there are several other conspirators in the
scheme,'' Yasuchika Negoro, director of the Criminal Justice
Department at the Justice Ministry, told Parliament today.
   It was the first time prosecutors entered the scandal.
   ``The gate of the Recruit scandal has just opened,'' Narazaki
told reporters, referring to the Watergate scandal that led to the
downfall of President Nixon in August 1974.
   The insider trading scandal surfaced last summer when it was
disclosed that dozens of politicians, business leaders and
journalists acquired and sold shares in Recruit-Cosmos.
   Trading stock on privileged information has been a common
practice in Japan, but new laws passed since the scandal unfolded
deal more stringently with insider trading.
</TEXT>
