<HEAD>Student Sent Home With Condom Earring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school student who wore a
packaged condom as an earring was sent home by school officials who
said his unusual jewelry caused a disruption.
   Janesville Parker High School senior Jeff Rabiola said he
dangled the condom from his ear Tuesday to encourage classmates to
use birth control.
   ``Some laughed, and some said it was immature, disgusting and
gross,'' he said. ``But it's only immature if you don't use
condoms, and it's AIDS that's disgusting and gross.''
   After refusing a teacher's suggestion that he remove the
earring, Rabiola was sent to the administration office, he said.
   Assistant Principal Joel Moore, who said he doubted Rabiola's
sincerity, said the student was asked to leave school because the
unusual jewelry caused a disruption.
   Rabiola returned to school Wednesday _ without his earring _ and
no further action was planned, Moore said.
