<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0430 10-20 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Courts Reagan Democrats In Ohio With Jobs Promise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Quayle speech; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, Much of; DELETES pvs grafs 12-15 bgng, Quayle sought, and
grafs 19-21 bgng, ``I'd be, to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Dan Quayle promised jobs and
economic prosperity as he courted Reagan Democrats today in the
hotly contested campaign for votes in industrial Ohio.
   In a speech to 1,000 students at Marietta College, GOP nominee
George Bush's vice presidential running mate said the Reagan
administration had created 12 million new jobs, and rejected
suggested they were low-paying.
   ``It adds up to a job for all who want to work,'' Quayle said.
   He said that for the first time ever, the government stands
ready to keep its promise of full employment.
   Campaign aides said Quayle would hammer away at the jobs theme
during a day-long tour through eastern Ohio.
   Spokesman David Prosperi said polls _ which he did not identify
_ showed Bush with a narrow lead over Democratic rival Michael
Dukakis in Ohio, and that Quayle's job today was to expand that
lead by stressing ``jobs, jobs and more jobs.''
   Quayle planned appearances in McConnelsville, Zanesville and
Newark, Ohio, before heading south Friday to Tennessee and Georgia.
   In rural Missouri on Wednesday, Quayle assailed Dukakis as
``dangerous and naive'' and having different values than those,
like himself, who come from the Middle West.
   Much of Quayle's regional pitch centers on family issues, but he
broadened his appeal to include defense policy as the campaign
begins a television campaign on the same theme.
   In a speech to college students in Liberty, Mo., Quayle asked if
``you really want the person that's going to sit across from the
General Secretary (Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev) to be a
liberal governor?''
   Dukakis' views on defense, Quayle said, are ``dangerous and
naive'' because he ``would unilaterally give up U.S. advantages
before even sitting down with the Soviets.''
   The speech was a toughening of the rhetoric that aides went out
of their way to underscore to reporters.
   Working to paint a picture of a relaxed and confident campaign,
Quayle even made a surprise stop at a barbecue restaurant in
Independence, Mo., to personally pick out three huge platters of
ribs for reporters traveling with him. He put down two crisp $100
bills to pay the check.
   He also said he'll be taking the weekend off, though the
election is less than three weeks away.
   ``So we don't make any mistakes those last two weeks,'' Quayle
said. ``Don't want to get tired and mess up. Might possibly cost
you to lose the election.
   ``I'm being cautious. It's also called going home,'' he said.
   Quayle had opened his campaign day in Chicago where he held
closed-door meetings with Jewish supporters.
   He emerged from the meetings saying Republicans are shooting for
a ``clear majority'' from that traditionally Democratic voting
group.
   ``Evidently we haven't done as good a job as we should have in
communicating where the Republican Party stands vis a vis Israel,
where the Republican Party stands vis a vis the Jewish community,''
Quayle said.
   Quayle ended his campaign day with a rally in Parkersburg, W.
Va., where he was greeted by protesters chanting ``coward'' and
``chickenhawk,'' referring to his National Guard service at the
height of the Vietnam War.
   ``Is that a Dukakis supporter out there?'' asked Quayle. ``If I
had to support Dukakis, I'd yell, too.''
</TEXT>
