<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FluShots     10-20 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flu Shots,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds To Give Elderly Free Shots Under Test Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of elderly Americans will receive free
flu vaccinations this year under a test program that could lead to
free shots for all the nation's Medicare recipients, according to
published reports.
   Federal health officials call the $50 million program an
unprecedented preventative effort that could prolong thousands of
lives, The Atlanta Constitution and The New York Times reported
today. The elderly are considered most at risk for fatal flu
complications, but Medicare does not now cover the shots.
   Federal officials are expected to announce next week the six to
10 sites nationwide that will be the first to receive federal
funding for the shots.
   They hope the special program can inoculate 4 million to 8
million people annually against influenza. About 22 million
Americans now regularly receive flu shots.
   The program will be administered by the Atlanta-based Centers
for Disease Control and the federal Health Care Financing
Administration.
   CDC epidemiologist Dr. Nancy Arden said the sites may include
nursing homes, hospitals, state and county health departments,
medical schools or other programs for elderly Americans, to
determine the most cost-effective way to reach the most senior
citizens.
   The program, authorized last year by Congress, gives health
officials up to four years to demonstrate the value of influenza
shots for the elderly. Health officials have been concerned that
only 20 percent of the nation's elderly get yearly flu shots.
   If the test program proves cost-effective, by cutting the cost
of treating people who become sick with influenza, flu inoculation
will be covered for all the nation's 32 million Medicare recipients.
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates that it would cost
Medicare $39 million a year to immunize all recipients against
influenza.
   Officials estimate that flu costs the country more than $1
billion annually for hospitalization and up to 10 times that much
for other costs, including doctors' visits and lost work time.
   Flu and pneumonia, its most common complication, together are
the leading cause of death from infectious disease in the United
States, contributing to about 68,000 deaths each year. Between 80
percent and 90 percent of those deaths occur in people over 65.
   In years of epidemics, officials say, the number of flu deaths
can exceed 50,000.
   The American Lung Association recommended this week that elderly
people and children and adults who live with them get annual shots
to reduce the risk of outbreaks. In the past, the association had
recommended annual flu shots only for elderly Americans and people
who are chronically ill.
</TEXT>
