<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0432 10-20 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Vows to Correct Every GOP `Falsehood'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Bentsen speech; picks up pvs 9th graf
bgng, In the teleconference; DELETES last 4 grafs bgng, Joe
O'Neill, to tighten; teleconference with students scheduled to
begin at 1:45 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen vowed today to
``take them on'' and answer every negative Republican campaign
advertisement, despite his acknowledged risk that the fight-back
strategy might obscure the Democrats' broader message.
   ``I'm going to take myself on an assignment,'' he told workers
at a huge General Electric appliance plant here. ``Every time they
issue a falsehood ... I'm going to take them on and straighten that
one out.''
   Bentsen said the presidential campaign should be fought over
issues like health, housing and America's economic future. But he
said the Republicans instead were distorting the prison furlough
issue and lying about Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis' position
on gun controls.
   Bentsen, a World War II veteran, said he took it ``as a personal
insult to me'' that the Republicans were trying to portray Dukakis
as weak on defense.
   ``We have seen the Republicans running on symbols and twisting
the facts,'' said Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential
candidate.
   ``We're going to tell them that you can't devalue the currency
of our democracy,'' he said.
   Bentsen spoke after touring the dishwasher plant that is part of
a giant GE complex employing more than 13,000 people. He shook
hands with workers and viewed robot equipment that has helped boost
plant productivity and profits.
   Bentsen told reporters Wednesday that the GOP's negative
campaign ads were ``an outrage.''
   He cited the script of a new commercial featuring Dukakis riding
in a battle tank and claiming that the Massachusetts governor
opposed every new defense program, which Bentsen said was
``completely untrue.''
   From Louisville, Bentsen headed for Texas to take part in an
hour-long national student satellite teleconference from Corpus
Christi State University.
   In the teleconference, Bentsen will answer questions from
students from 26 colleges in 11 states. Those scheduled to
participate at campuses around the country included the Rev. Jesse
Jackson and Sen. Al Gore of Tennessee at Memphis State and former
Kentucky Gov. Martha Layne Collins at the University of Kentucky.
Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton was to serve as moderator.
   Although Bentsen says he'd rather spend his time discussing home
ownership, trade, education, and other Democratic issues, he
conceded those messages were not yet getting through. His attack
lines, meanwhile, are proving popular at rallies where the crowds
seem more pumped up than before.
   A Louisville crowd roared Wednesday night when Bentsen described
his opinion of how the Republicans have distorted Dukakis' record.
``Down in Texas, we'd say they painted him lower than a snake's
belly in a wagon rut,'' he said.
   Bentsen met briefly with reporters on Wednesday before leaving
California, where he unveiled his new tactics. He acknowledged the
Republican campaign was working and it showed in the polls.
   ``That's why I finally had enough, because apparently these kind
of charges when they're not answered, even though they are as
ludicrous as they are, have some damaging effect,'' he said.
   ``I'm not going to put up with it any more,'' he said. ``I'm
going to take them head on every time they distort the truth''
through election day.
   ``This is my idea,'' Bentsen said. ``This is not something I was
asked to do.''
</TEXT>
