<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     10-20 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Gives Pep Talk to House Democrats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson urged House Democrats
today to campaign vigorously for Michael Dukakis, their party's
presidential nominee, when Congress adjourns for the year.
   ``Governor Dukakis supplies the priorities, we can supply
passion,'' Jackson told reporters after his half-hour session with
lawmakers in the House chamber.
   Democrats have been taking a pounding in recent days with
national polls showing Republican nominee George Bush widening his
lead over Dukakis less than three weeks before the Nov. 8 election.
   ``Nineteen days is a lot of time,'' said Democratic National
Chairman Paul Kirk, who also addressed the House members. ``I don't
see trouble, I see opportunity.''
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, who heads the 255-member House
Democratic Caucus, said the message from Jackson and Kirk was that
``it's not over till it's over, we need your help, there's still
three weeks to go.''
   About 175 House Democrats attended the session, she said.
   ``It was an energizing meeting we all needed,'' Ms. Oakar said.
``We've been working around the clock here. It's hard to think of
national offices when you're working on drug bills.''
   House and Senate leaders had hoped Congress would adjourn two
weeks ago. But both chambers have been trying to complete work on a
massive anti-drug bill, which they hope to accomplish by Friday.
