<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Callaghan in Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister James Callaghan collapsed at
a memorial service today and was taken to a hospital, a hospital
spokeswoman said.
   Lord Callaghan, 76, Labor prime minister between 1976 and 1979,
became ill at St. Margaret's Church, near Parliament, at a service
for a former colleague and was taken to nearby St. Thomas' Hospital.
   A hospital spokeswoman said Callaghan, who suffered a mild heart
attack in June, was being kept at the hospital for observation.
   ``Jim Callaghan was taken slightly ill. We are not quite certain
what the problem is. He was fully conscious when he arrived. His
condition is comfortable but we are keeping him in for
observation,'' she said on condition of anonymity.
   ``It is a hot day and he was at a memorial service. You can draw
your own conclusions from that,'' she said.
   The service was for Lord Peart, agriculture minister in the
Callaghan government.
   The domestic news agency, Press Association, quoted other people
attending the service as saying Callaghan's problem became apparent
during a part of the service when the congregation was standing.
Callaghan became weak and said he needed to sit down, the agency
said.
