<HEAD>Defiant Nuns Vow Two Days Of Silence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Carmelite nuns protesting what
they claim is the liberalization of their cloister have agreed to
temporarily cease talking to the news media and public about their
impasse.
   The five rebellious nuns, who have locked themselves in the
monastery's infirmary, agreed to the request of their prioress to
spend two days in prayer and contemplation, said Sister John of the
Cross, a spokeswoman for the group.
   ``We never want anyone to say we're disobedient,'' said Sister
John.
   The nuns barricaded themselves in the infirmary of the Monastery
of the Most Blessed Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel on Oct. 4.
   They claim the conservative nature that attracted them to the
Discalced Carmelite order has been violated by the new prioress,
Mother Theresa Hewitt. They say she has introduced television,
sweets and more socializing than had been customary.
   Mother Theresa Hewitt and officials of the Paterson Roman
Catholic diocese say the nuns have had disciplinary problems and
refused to accept the prioress' authority.
   The diocese tried to transfer the nuns, who locked themselves in
the infirmary to avoid what they felt would be immediate expulsion.
   Earlier this week, the five nuns refused to deal with a
Carmelite priest, the Rev. Kevin Culligan, arguing that he lacked
proper Vatican credentials.
