<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Shakeup     10-20 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Shakeup,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Press Agency Chief Named to Foreign Policy Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the government press agency Novosti,
Valentin M. Falin, has been elevated to a new foreign policy post
in the Communist Party apparatus, Soviet officials said today.
   Falin, 62, was named to a job that pairs the responsibilities of
two formerly separate posts held by Anatoly F. Dobrynin and Vadim
A. Medvedev.
   Falin will head the newly reorganized International Department
of the Soviet Communist Party's policy-making Central Committee,
Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov told reporters at a
government briefing.
   The International Department, previously headed by Dobrynin, was
responsible for relations with non-ruling communist parties and
overall foreign policy.
   A separate Central Committee office dealt with ruling communist
parties abroad. Under a revamping of the Central Committee, the two
departments have been combined and the overall title is the
International Department, another Foreign Ministry spokesman, Yuri
A. Gremitskikh, said later in an interview.
   A Central Committee employee, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Falin was appointed to his new post last week.
   His departure left both Soviet news agencies without a chief.
Sergei A. Losev, director of Tass, died earlier this month. His
successor has not been named, and Gerasimov said Falin's old job
was now open.
   Falin will report to Alexander N. Yakovlev, a key ally to
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev who was named in a major Kremlin
shake-up Sept. 30 to head a new foreign affairs commission of the
Central Committee, Gerasimov said.
   In the shakeup, Dobrynin, a former Soviet ambassador to
Washington, was retired, and Medvedev was elevated to the ruling
Politburo and put in charge of ideology.
   Two deputies to Falin have also been named to posts as part of
the reorganization of the International Department. Gerasimov
identified them as Karen N. Brutents and Rafael Fedorov.
   Falin served as Soviet ambassador to West Germany in 1971-1978
and was appointed chairman of Novosti on March 10, 1986.
   Another former Soviet ambasssador, Alexander S. Kapto, who
served in Cuba from 1986 until this year, was named head of the
Central Committee's Ideological Department, Tass, the official news
agency, reported. There, he will presumably report to Medvedev.
</TEXT>
