<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeaponsCharge     10-20 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weapons Charge,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineer Arrested on Charge of Buying Weapon Parts to Send
Overseas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCK HILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-month undercover operation by
U.S. Customs agents led to the arrest of a city electrical engineer
who has been charged with obtaining sophisticated weapons parts for
shipment overseas.
   Agents arrested Ali Foyuzi Yousefi, 45, on Wednesday, said
police Lt. Charles Cabaniss. He was charged with violating the
Federal Arms Exportation Control Act, said Larry Hunter, head of
U.S. Customs office in Columbia.
   Hunter said Yousefi was an illegal alien. When asked what
country the parts were being shipped to, he responded: ``Mr.
Yousefi is an Iranian.'' He did not elaborate.
   The parts involved belonged to a Hawk missile, a source close to
the investigation told The Rock Hill Herald.
   Yousefi was questioned for about two hours at his office at the
city's Operations Center before officers led him away in handcuffs.
His house also was searched for evidence.
   Yousefi was to be arraigned before a federal judge in Columbia
today.
   Cabaniss said police were notified by federal investigators in
mid-July of the operation by the Customs Department, which began
its investigation after learning that a Rock Hill man had contacted
several U.S. Defense Department contractors in California several
months ago.
   In the undercover operation, Customs agents met with the Rock
Hill man several times to arrange the weapons purchase. Cabaniss
said the man used several aliases in his dealings with agents.
   The parts were delivered to Yousefi last week _ an action that
prompted a full week of constant surveillance of the engineer,
Cabaniss said.
   ``Once he took possession of this stuff, we never lost sight of
him,'' Cabaniss said. About 20 federal agents were brought in last
week as the operation neared an end.
</TEXT>
