<HEAD>Southern California Firefighters Close To Containing Blazes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters in Southern California have nearly surrounded a
4,200-acre fire in the Angeles National Forest, and ancient
redwoods in Sequoia National Park are no longer threatened by
another wildfire, officials said today.
   The Divide Fire, in the Angeles Fire above Los Angeles' San
Fernando Valley, was 90 percent contained this morning. The fire
was started Sunday by a 10-year-old boy playing with matches.
   The firefighting force has been reduced and the 850 firefighters
left on the lines were mostly mopping up the interior of the burned
area, officials said.
   The 2,700-acre blaze near Sequoia's Giant Forest, where some
trees are 2,000 years old, was 70 percent contained, said U.S.
Forest Service spokesman Earl Clayton. A cigarette apparently
dropped by a fisherman started the fire Sunday morning.
