<HEAD>Afghanistan Says Car Hits Mine, Killing American And 6 Others</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS graf after 7th, `Three American...' to UPDATE with
reported rocket attack. Pick up 8th pvs, `Radio Kabul...'
^By KATHY GANNON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American, four Pakistanis and two
Egyptians were killed when their car, loaded with weapons for
Afghan rebels, hit a mine in southeastern Afghanistan, Radio Kabul
said today.
   The Afghan government radio, monitored in Islamabad, said the
seven were killed in Zabul province but did not say when. No names
were given.
   It said the car was loaded with arms and ammunition for
U.S.-supported Afghan guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed
government.
   A Western diplomat said he received a ``vague'' message today
reporting the death of an American and other foreigners inside
Afghanistan. But he said on condition of anonymity that the report
was not confirmed.
   On Sunday, Radio Kabul said two Americans were killed during a
government attack on rebel positions near Gardez, 60 miles
southeast of Kabul, the Afghan capital. It did not identify the
Americans other than to say they were advisers helping Moslem
insurgents, who have been fighting the Marxist government for the
past 10 years.
   Western diplomats said no American citizens were in Afghanistan
on official business.
   Three American journalists have been killed covering the
conflict inside Afghanistan.
   The radio said six rockets hit the capital today, killing two
people and injuring two.
   Radio Kabul also said Afghan security officers seized three
British-made long-range missiles near Kabul on Sunday.
   A rocket attack launched by Afghan insurgents killed nine people
Wednesday and injured 17 near Kabul airport, Afghan security
officers said. They said two Soviet women and a 2-year-old Soviet
girl were among those killed.
   The Soviet Union sent troops to Afghanistan in December 1979,
and 100,000 have helped the government fight the rebels. The Red
Army began withdrawing May 15 in line with a U.N.-brokered pact.
Half of the troops left by Aug. 15 and the remainder are to be out
by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
