<DOCNO> AP881020-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AIDSConference     10-20 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Conference,0788</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Reaching Some of Earth's Most Isolated Populations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IXTAPA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the streets of Khartoum, capital of the
desert African nation of Sudan, 7 percent of homeless children test
positive for exposure to the AIDS virus.
   In northern Thailand, the first positive AIDS tests popped up
just this year.
   In the jungles of Suriname, reachable only by air or boat, at
least five members of a South American tribe are dying of AIDS.
   Steamboats, trucks, family reunions and space rockets have all
helped AIDS spread to some of Earth's most isolated populations,
according to researchers, sociologists and health workers at the
First International Symposium on Education and Communication About
AIDS being held here this week.
   ``There are 40 million street children in the world, and we
suddenly realized they're all at risk for AIDS because so many turn
to prostitution,'' said Peter Dalglish, who founded Street Kids
International and ran an AIDS testing program in the Sudan.
   Dalglish, citing UNICEF figures for the number of homeless
children in the world's largest cities, said the deadly disease
entered the Sudan via truck drivers and Nile River steamers from
central Africa, where AIDS incidence is high.
   Poverty, guerrilla war, illiteracy, countrysides empty of
televisions or even radios, and lack of resources combine to
frustrate workers trying to reach isolated populations.
   ``We're talking about some countries where a national health
budget of one dollar per person per year is a drain on the
economy,'' said Dr. Manuel Carballo, head of the social and
behavioral unit at the World health Organization in Geneva.
   All the negative factors affect the jungles of southern
Suriname, home to 35,000 Maroons descended from African slaves who
escaped from coastal plantations.
   Despite their seeming isolation, said Dr. Ruben del Prado, the
space age helped ease the path of the AIDS virus when Maroon men
traveled to French Guyana to work on roads and on buildings at the
European Space Agency's launch facility at Kourou.
   ``Where they were infected _ Suriname or French Guyana _ is a
sensitive political question,'' said del Prado, who works for
Medical Mission, a private interreligous organization in Suriname.
``But French Guyana is where they went, and there is a great inflow
and outflow of Europeans there'' _ a factor associated with the
spread of the virus.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is transmitted through
sexual contact, infected blood transfusions and the sharing of
syringes. It impairs the body's ability to fight off disease, and
no cure has been found.
   The cases detected among the Maroons were not just positive
tests or exposure to the virus, which can incubate for years, but
advanced cases of the disease itself, he said.
   Del Prado, who spent three years among the Maroons, said health
workers haven't been able to enter the area for a year because of
an insurgency movement against the central Surinamese government.
   He worries that AIDS, once at large in the closed Maroon
society, will become rampant because of frequent exposure to
tropical and venereal diseases, complete lack of education or
social support and the fact that sexual activity routinely starts
as early as age eight.
   In Thailand, it is Bangkok's sex industry that poses a danger,
even in the remote north, said Werasit Sittitrai, AIDS project
coordinator for the Thai Red Cross Society.
   ``In northern Thailand, there are almost no girls 15 to 20 years
old,'' said Sittitrai. ``They're all in the south and it's quite
open. Families visit their girls in the south, boyfriends, they'll
all stay in the same hotels.''
   The first case of evidence of AIDS in the north cropped up last
summer, but Sittitrai, who is running an agressive outreach program
for prostitutes, is optimistic that the epidemic will be contained.
   ``We believe we can teach even prostitutes how to have safe sex
if we keep working,'' he said.
   Cultural and political factors can make areas newly open to AIDS
difficult to work in, health professionals say. Dalglish said he
talked to Arab merchants who freely admitted having sex with boys,
``but they don't consider that homosexuality so they won't admit
one of the risk factors exists.''
   ``There's usually a period of denial,'' said Anthony Meyer, who
is head of health promotion for WHO's global program on AIDS.
``Then you see a national committee made up of scientists; then you
see the health minister, the education minister joining the
committee, and you know they're taking it seriously.''
   That happens, said Sittitrai, ``because of the pressure of
AIDS.'' The disease keeps spreading, and people keep dying, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0128 </DOCNO>
