<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Reforms     10-20 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Reforms,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Launches Campaign For Economic Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials launched a nationwide campaign to rally
citizens behind new economic reforms, the Xinhua News Agency
reported Thursday.
   Officials of the Secretariat that conducts the daily affairs of
the ruling Communist Party are meeting with provincial officials to
try to ``unify the nation's thinking and action.''
   Local officials, who have gained substantial autonomy over
economic decision-making, largely have ignored government efforts
to reduce the more than 20 percent inflation rate and widespread
black market activity.
   The new campaign indicates the leadership's determination to
assert central control and enforce austerity measures.
   Hu Qili, head of the Secretariat, told the meeting that the
purpose of the drive was to make party officials and citizens
``rally around'' a program to restore economic order, Xinhua said.
   The government last month ordered reductions in capital
investment and spending, a halt to most public construction
projects, tighter loan policies by banks and a crackdown on illegal
business practices.
   Implementation of the reforms, first proposed more than two
years ago, were delayed in order to allow prices of consumer goods
to adjust to market forces.
   The central government has the double burden of convincing local
officials to cooperate with the changes and assuring citizens of
their commitment to development and economic reform.
   The official Economic Daily responded to the new campaign
Thursday in a front-page editorial that tried to placate worries
about economic strategies.
   The article posed a series of questions challenging the new
policies, and answered each one reassuringly.
   ``If reform doesn't go forward, won't it go backward?'' it asked.
   The answer: ``The adjustment of the timetable for price reform
is not a retreat, but merely a step backward before the main
attack.''
   Addressing concerns that tighter central control will stifle
needed development, the newspaper said: ``Reform cannot be simply
equated with giving up all centralized control. The reform
necessitates a new division of central and localized powers.''
</TEXT>
