<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Ecclesia-Abuse     10-20 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ecclesia-Abuse,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broussard Blames Media For Daughter's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a religious group whose daughter
was killed in Oregon said today that negative media coverage of his
organization was responsible for her beating death.
   ``Irresponsible media put me in a precarious situation,''
Eldridge Broussard Jr. said in an appearance on Oprah Winfrey's
syndicated television talk show.
   Broussard is head of the Los Angeles-based Watts Christian
Center and the now-defunct Ecclesia Athletic Association.
   ``For the last year and a half I have had to walk around this
country as a suspected cult leader,'' he said, adding reporters had
labeled him ``the new Jim Jones.''
   Broussard's 8-year-old daughter, Dayna Lorea, died Friday.
Authorities say the death was the result of beatings at a camp run
by Broussard outside Portland, Ore., for youngsters from the Los
Angeles district of Watts.
   Four men associated with Broussard's group have been charged
with manslaughter in the child's death.
   But Broussard, 35, denied today that children were beaten or
abused at the camp.
   He told Ms. Winfrey they were ``spanked,'' and that the
military-like discipline reported at the camp was necessary to
enable the children to endure city life.
   ``Abuse may be to do anything that does not prepare them to be
on their toes in a rather paranoid, trigger-happy Los Angeles
situation,'' Broussard said. ``We teach our children the moment
someone of authority says something to you, you snap to it.''
   Broussard said standards of discipline in Oregon were different
than those in Watts, and that if authorities from Los Angeles were
to inspect his daughter's body they would draw different
conclusions than those reached by Oregon officials.
   He said the negative publicity Ecclesia received when the group
arrived in Oregon last year cost his group financial backing and
led to suspension of its activities. As a result, Broussard said,
staff members were performing duties for which they lacked proper
qualifications.
   ``I feel that if we hadn't been misinterpreted by the media, our
people wouldn't even have been in Sandy that night,'' he said.
   Broussard said Ecclesia was dissolved last year and the children
who were taken into custody by state officials in Oregon were part
of the Watts Christian Center school and training program.
   Broussard, smiling and apparently unemotional for most of the
hourlong show, at one point broke down in tears, asking Ms. Winfrey
to help him uncover the real facts surrounding the case.
   ``I don't believe anyone else will give me a chance,'' Broussard
said.
   After his daughter's death, 53 children attending the Watts
Christian Center school and training program headed by Broussard,
were taken into custody at a rural house near Sandy, about 30 miles
east of Portland.
   Two other children involved with the group were taken into
custody in Los Angeles.
   The Clackamas County Juvenile Department has charged that
children at the camp were routinely beaten with paddles or
electrical cord. Some children were beaten up to 800 times while
others were forced to watch and keep count, the department said in
a court petition.
   Donald Welch, director of Clackamas County Juvenile Court, said
leaders of the group had beaten and whipped children as an integral
part of its program to heighten athletic performance, much like
harrassment commonly used in military-style basic training.
</TEXT>
