<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Chile     10-20 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet's Cabinet Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet's Cabinet
resigned today, the government announced. Opponents hoped the move
would clear the way for talks on democratic reforms.
   Orlando Poblete, the government secretary-general with
ministerial ranking, said he and the 15 other Cabinet members
handed in their resignations to give maneuvering room to Pinochet,
loser of an Oct. 5 referendum.
   The resignations allow the 72-year-old leader ``to select his
people and take the steps he considers proper in this
post-plebiscite stage'' of government, Poblete said.
   Poblete made the announcement to reporters at the government
palace immediately after a brief meeting of the full Cabinet. He
gave no details, but it was widely assumed that Pinochet would
accept at least some of the resignations and that key changes would
be made.
   Pinochet, the right-wing army commander, lost by more than
800,000 votes in the yes-no ballot ballot on a proposal to extend
his 15-year rule to 1997. He won 43 percent of the vote, and 55
percent voted ``no.''
   The morning after the vote his Cabinet offered their
resignations, but Pinochet rejected them, evidently needing time to
evaluate and pick replacements.
   According to the 8-year-old constitution, his term expires in
March 1990, when the winner of an open election planned for
December 1989 will assume power.
   A 16-party opposition coalition that led the campaign for
Pinochet's defeat has called for several reforms in the
constitution. It maintains that the changes are needed for full
democracy under the new elected government.
   In the two weeks since the vote the coalition's leaders have
said they were waiting for a Cabinet change as a sign that Pinochet
was willing to negotiate the changes.
   Key Cabinet members, including Poblete, helped direct Pinochet's
political campaign for the referendum and have been blamed for his
defeat.
   Pinochet has maintained no changes will be permitted in the
constitution, especially in its timetable for a return to elected
rule. The opposition has called for him to show more flexibility
and said government intransigence could spark unrest.
   Pinochet took power in a 1973 coup that deposed the elected
government of Salvador Allende, a Marxist who died in the coup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
