<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CrashVictims     10-20 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Victims,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Victims' Relatives Say Air Force Puts No Value on Lost Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRAN RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of 10 people killed when an Air
Force jet careened into a hotel visited the accident scene today on
the first anniversary of the crash and accused government officials
of showing little compassion.
   ``The U.S. Air Force has failed to treat survivors of the crash
with human dignity, rather the Air Force has chosen to hide behind
Indiana's wrongful death law,'' said Robert Goldberg, whose
daughter, Beth, was among the victims.
   ``This unjust law declares that the lives of single adults
without dependents are worth nothing,'' he said.
   Air Force Master Sgt. Larry Martin, who lost his daughter, Dawn
Shelly, said, ``Since my daughter's death, the Air Force has shown
little compassion for our family. We have not received one letter
or phone call or personal visit from a chaplain.''
   The family members say they want a jury to decide whether the
crash was caused by negligence. And if it was, they believe a jury
should be able to award damages.
   Indiana's wrongful death law does not allow damages for adults
who died because of someone else's negligence but who have no
dependents.
   The Air Force and the hotel's owners have been unable to agree
on a cost for damages and the Ramada Inn hotel remains mostly
untouched since the accident, with the smell of smoke still
lingering. There are pieces of metal dangling from the ceiling,
hotel papers stained with water and charred edges that still litter
what once were rooms.
   The accident happened when Maj. Bruce L. Teagarden, en route
from Pittsburgh to Nellis Air Force Base in Nevada, tried to land
his powerless fighter jet at the nearby Indianapolis International
Airport.
   Teagarden was making his second attempt at the runway when he
ejected and the A7-D Corsair plummeted, skipping off a bank
building before ramming into the lobby of the Ramada across the
street.
   Nine hotel employees were killed at the scene. A salesman who
had stopped to make a telephone call died several days later.
   Teagarden, who suffered only minor injuries, was cleared of any
wrongdoing.
   A memorial service arranged by the Marion County Sheriff's
Department was scheduled for later today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
