<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HeartDrugApproval     10-20 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heart Drug Approval,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Defends Decision To Delay Heart Drug Approval A Year Ago</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release 5:30 p.m. EDT, time set by source</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a Food and Drug Administration
panel responsible for a delay in approving a drug that breaks down
blood clots say there is no room for emotionalism in the handling
of new drugs.
   Dr. Peter R. Kowey of the Medical College of Pennsylvania, in
Philadelphia, and other members of the panel took the unusual step
of writing an article about their action for Friday's Journal of
the American Medical Association.
   They described pressure from the public, press and
pharmaceutical companies to recommend FDA approval of the drug TPA,
or tissue plasminogen activator.
   The pressure included an editorial in The Wall Street Journal
calling for the immediate release of TPA despite researcher
concerns. The editorial argued that the panel's decision to
postpone approval would ``sacrifice thousands of American lives on
an altar of pedantry.''
   Following the panel's decision, the FDA requested additional
information from the drug's manufacturer, Genentech Inc. of South
San Francisco. A second and third panel reconsidered the drug and
finally gave approval in November 1987, six months after the
decision to postpone the OK.
   TPA is an enzyme used to break down blood clots, particularly in
the vessels feeding the heart muscle following a heart attack. As
with other clot-dissolving drugs, recipients risk internal bleeding.
   Kowey said the panel members decided to reply to the criticisms
because of the complex reasons for their decision and the attention
it received.
   ``People began to lose sight of what the facts were,'' he said.
``Emotionalism can be very dangerous to the public. All the
physicians knew was that we had turned down the drug. This (the
article) gives us a way to tell people what we were thinking.''
   Kowey said the panel had ``very real concerns'' that the drug
might cause excessive bleeding. Based on the available data, the
members decided that ``the presumed benefit of the therapy might be
unacceptably mitigated by its risk.''
   Kowey said he thought the medical journal article could help
educate physicians treating patients who do not understand the FDA
approval process.
   ``The FDA, to its credit, did not succumb to the media
campaign,'' the authors wrote. ``Commissioner (Frank) Young and his
staff endorsed the committee's findings, but, most appropriately,
did promise to expedite review of any new information the sponsor
wished to present in support of the application.''
   The authors maintain the panel made the correct decision in
recommending a delay.
   ``Although the decision-making process is complex, maintaining
an objective attitude is mandatory to ensure that safe and
effective drug products reach the marketplace,'' according to the
authors. ``The public airing of problems having to do with this and
other new drug applications and the strong stand taken by the
committee and the FDA should convince industry, the medical
community, and the public that the method of drug review is sound.''
   In the past two years, public outcry has successfully prodded
the FDA to speed up the approval process of drugs that could help
patients suffering from serious diseases.
   Young announced Wednesday a new plan to reduce the time required
for human testing of drugs for life-threatening and severely
debilitating diseases, which he said included severe heart disease,
AIDS, Parkinson's disease, deadly cancers and blindness.
   Young said the TPA experience played a crucial role in the new
FDA policy, as agency officials learned they could intervene in the
drug development process to hasten approval by asking pointed
questions and eliminating unnecessary research.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
