<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Irish 2ndLd-Writethru   10-20 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0559,0824</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Proposes Ending Suspects' Right To Remain Silent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with government announcing proposal
to end right of silence. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today proposed ending the right of
criminal suspects in Northern Ireland to remain silent as part of a
new crackdown on the Irish Republican Army.
   The measure, which will end a historic right dating from the
17th century, was put forward immediately in the Commons and is
likely to become law within three months.
   The annoucement by Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King came a
day after the government banned broadcast interviews with members
of the outlawed IRA and 10 other militant Roman Catholic and
Protestant groups in Northern Ireland.
   The measure announced today applies to all criminal suspects in
Northern Ireland, but it is aimed at terrorist suspects.
   Another Cabinet minister, Douglas Hurd, said the government is
considering introducing similar legislation to end suspects' right
to silence in England and Wales.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative Party has a huge
majority in the 650-member Commons, so the measures are likely to
be approved.
   King, in a statement accompanying his announcement to Commons,
said:
   ``Members of terrorist organizations are being trained to refuse
to respond to questions put by the police _ and this technique is
increasingly being adopted by those suspected of serious crimes,
including racketeering. Justice is being thwarted.''
   The IRA is fighting to drive the British out of the majority
Protestant province of Northern Ireland and unite it with the
Catholic Republic of Ireland.
   This is the first time a British government has announced it
will introduce laws to end the right to silence.
   Courts now are not allowed to take into consideration that a
suspect refused to answer police interrogation.
   In a written statement to the Commons, King said under the new
law a judge will be able to draw ``whatever inferences appear
proper'' from the fact that a suspect refused to answer police
questions.
   Sources said judges and juries will be able to conclude that a
suspect's silence is an indication of guilt, particularly if the
suspect produces a detailed defense in court after refusing to
answer police questions.
   King said the Republic of Ireland also has restricted the right
to silence of suspects as part of its drive against the IRA.
   Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal political wing, said the measure
``effectively moves that (British) government closer to the
governments of Chile and South Africa.''
   ``The right to silence is a century-old civil liberty, enshrined
in the legal systems of most of the world's civilized countries,''
Sinn Fein said in a statement.
   Spokesman Kevin McNamara of the opposition Labor Party said in a
radio interview, ``Northern Ireland is being used as a laboratory
for draconian measures to be used later in other parts of the
United Kingdom.''
   In addition to ending the right to silence, the government has
said it plans legislation this winter enabling it to freeze and
seize the funds of terrorist organizations.
   It also plans to require candidates in Northern Ireland
elections to take an oath disavowing violence.
   This is aimed at Sinn Fein, which is formally committed to
``armed struggle'' to unite Northern Ireland with the Republic of
Ireland under a leftist administration. But the Sinn Fein
leadership says it will have no problem taking a no-violence oath.
   Hurd on Wednesday banned radio and television interviews with
members of the mainly Roman Catholic IRA, Sinn Fein, the Ulster
Defense Association, a militant Protestant organization, and other
Northern Ireland groups.
   The ban, which was imposed by decree and did not require
legislation, provoked an immedate outcry from opposition and civil
liberties groups.
   But Hurd, the Cabinet minister responsible for broadcasting,
said: ``The government has decided that the time has now come to
deny this easy platform to those who use it to propagate
terrorism.''
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said the move set a ``damaging
precedent'' but, like the other British network, the commercially
funded Independent Television, said it would comply.
   Sinn Fein likened the ban to Soviet bloc censorship.
   Timothy Renton, deputy minister of the Home Office, told
American reporters in London: ``The whole aim of this (ban)... is
to remove that extra weapon _ the ability to go on television
immediately afterwards to speak in justification of an explosion or
a bomb.''
   The ban, which follows closely a 15-year ban on IRA and Sinn
Fein interviews in the Republic of Ireland, does not affect foreign
networks or the British print media.
   Sinn Fein, which gets about one-third of the vote of the
Catholic minority in Northern Ireland, has one member in the
British Commons, Gerry Adams, who has never attended, and about 70
members on local Northern Ireland councils.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
