<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reporter'sNotebook     10-20 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reporter's Notebook,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Bush Campaign: Optimism, Humor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAGINAW, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While George Bush warns against
overconfidence by his supporters, evidence abounds that the
cautionary note is not sinking in with his entourage. Many are
convinced he'll be living in the White House come January.
   A local Secret Service agent matter-of-factly provided a typical
example this week.
   He walked up to Bush's official photographer, David Valdez, in
the hallway of a hotel where Bush holed up before a late afternoon
speech.
   The agent said he had a friend who was chaplain for a New York
police organization and this chaplain ``wants to know if he can
represent them at the inauguration. Who should he talk to?''
   Valdez, mindful of his boss's public admonition that any member
of the campaign who shows overconfidence or signs of letting up in
the final push ``is history,'' made no comment on the man's
request. Instead he tactfully suggested the agent look for some of
the traveling campaign staff.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush later spoke at a local high school where some of Michael
Dukakis' supporters showed that a bit of this year's political
lexicon has made the crossover from campaign jargon to everyday
usage.
   As Bush's motorcade rolled by the line of Dukakis demonstraters
outside Heritage High School, two raised a large cardboard sign
that read, ``Spin this, Atwater.''
   Spin is the word for what political operatives often do when
talking to reporters _ they evaluate the current political
situation or a given event in terms that serve their campaign's
strategy and make their candidate look as good as possible.
   Spinning has a negative connotation among people who see it as
attempted manipulation or outright deception.
   Lee Atwater, Bush's campaign manager, is one of the masters of
spin.
   Atwater, who does not generally travel with the campaign,
happened to be on the road with Bush this day. When a TV crew got
the sign and showed it to him, he laughed and seemed quite pleased
at the acknowledgement of his speciality.
   He later raised the sign aloft in the press bus while asking if
anyone had any questions, and continued the day's spinning in the
campaign plane later with the sign perched atop his seat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
