<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Marcos-Contempt 3rdLd-Writethru a0600 10-20 0837</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos-Contempt, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0600,0855</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court: Ferdinand Marcos is in Contempt of Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to recast lead to clarify that Reagan
today declining to discuss case, sted not intervene, move up
reference to newspaper report; Picks up 3rd graf, `The 2nd ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. appeals court has denied Ferdinand E.
Marcos' bid to avoid the threat of jail for failing to comply with
grand jury subpoenas, and President Reagan reportedly is refusing
to intervene.
   At the White House today, the president declined to discuss the
case. ``I just don't want to get into the subject because it is
something that may not come to my desk at all,'' he said when asked
if he would intervene.
   The Los Angeles Times reported today that the president has
decided not to intervene on Marcos' behalf.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Wednesday upheld a
lower court finding against the ousted Philippines president and
his wife, Imelda, that subjects them to possible arrest for civil
contempt of court.
   Marcos, 71, and his 59-year-old wife have been targets of a
federal grand jury probe investigating charges that Marcos
allegedly diverted enormous sums of government money to secret bank
accounts after he fled the Philippines. In August the couple balked
at complying with a series of subpoenas, prompting the contempt
charge by Judge John Walker.
   Generally, persons found in civil contempt can be jailed for the
life of the grand jury, usually about 18 months, or until they
comply with the court's directive, whichever comes first.
   But U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani, whose office is conducting
the investigation, refused to comment on what steps might be taken.
   Reagan also was asked today if he had promised Marcos a ``safe
haven'' in the United States. The president replied, ``I couldn't
have made a blanket statement of that kind.''
   The president based his decision of non-interference on evidence
indicating that Marcos allegedly diverted U.S. aid money to the
Philippines for his own use after he fled his country and took
refuge in the United States at Reagan's invitation, the Los Angeles
Times reported earlier today.
   Meanwhile, in the Philippines, President Corazon Aquino said
today that U.S. prosecution of Marcos would hasten her government's
recovery of the billions of dollars he allegedly plundered during
his 20-year rule.
   Mrs. Aquino said U.S. authorities had not informed her whether
they plan to arrest Marcos.
   The chairman of the Presidential Commission on Good Government
said last week he may delay filing criminal charges here against
Marcos so the United States could go ahead with its own prosecution.
   Mrs. Aquino's government has long been threatening to indict
Marcos on criminal charges but so far has filed 39 civil suits
against him seeking to collect $96.7 billion in damages.
   Officials say in private that criminal charges have not been
filed because of fears that Marcos' return would destabilize Mrs.
Aquino's administration. The Philippine Constitution prohibits
trial in absentia.
   Several times since taking refuge in Hawaii in February 1986,
Marcos has personally appealed to Reagan for help with his legal
problems, and Mrs. Marcos sent Nancy Reagan a handwritten letter in
September 1986, the Times said.
   The two-page letter asked Mrs. Reagan for her ``invaluable help
to prevent'' the couple from being deposed under court order by
attorneys for the Philippines government, said the Times, which
obtained a copy of the letter.
   ``I understand that a `suggestion' from the `White House' or the
`State Dept.' could prevent these indignities to an ally and
friend,'' Mrs. Marcos wrote, according to the Times.
   A grand jury in New York has been investigating since June 1986
whether the Marcoses violated federal racketeering laws, according
to the appeals court's 21-page opinion.
   ``Essentially the government believes the (Marcoses) _ and
others acting in concert with them _ fraudulently diverted enormous
sums of money that belonged to the Philippine government and the
government of the United States, which money was intended for the
benefit of the Philippine people,'' the three-member appeals court
wrote, outlining the allegations against Marcos and his wife.
   Specifically, the grand jury was investigating reports that the
couple or their agents may have used embezzled funds to buy real
estate and other items in the United States and transferred other
misappropriated money to secret Swiss bank accounts.
   ``The grand jury has not handed down any indictments,'' the
appeals court noted.
   The subpoenas sought the Marcoses' fingerprints, palm prints,
voice and handwriting examples, along with their authorization for
foreign banks to turn over their financial records.
   When the couple refused, claiming through their lawyers that
they still retained head-of-state immunity, prosecutors presented
an Aug. 9 diplomatic note from the Philippines government waiving
``any immunity that the Marcoses might possess.''
   The appeals court, in an opinion written by Circuit Judge
Richard J. Cardamone, noted that the language of the Philippines
government's waiver of the Marcoses' immunity ``could scarcely be
stronger'' and therefore thwarted the couple's claim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0427 10-20 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0427,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Likens Bush Campaign To Watergate Cover-Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede COLUMBIA, MO.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 16 grafs new with Dukakis speech; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, Dukakis campaign; DELETES last 6 grafs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis struck back at
George Bush's negative attacks today by comparing his Republican
rival's campaign to the Watergate cover-up of the Nixon White House.
   ``Truth was the first casualty in the Nixon White House and it
was the first casualty in the Bush campaign,'' Dukakis said in a
speech to Southern New England Telephone Co. employees.
   ``I believe the American people value the truth in politics and
I'm going to do everything I can to make sure the truth wins,'' he
said.
   In campaign appearances in Illinois and Missouri on Wednesday,
Dukakis denounced Republican campaign literature as ``garbage'' and
``a pack of lies.''
   The Massachusetts governor also stressed his commitment to
family values and the concerns of working Americans today, and said
Bush was both unknowing and uncaring.
   ``I'm never going to forget the people I've met during this
campaign,'' Dukakis said. ``People who need a helping hand, not a
cold shoulder.''
   Dukakis flew to Connecticut after three days of campaigning in
the Middle West and was immediately asked about a Hartford Courant
poll which said he was trailing Bush by 10 percentage points in
this New England state that borders his home state of Massachusetts.
   ``You know the polls. They go up and down,'' he responded.
   In his speech to the telephone workers, Dukakis said:
   ``George Bush doesn't care that working women earn only 64 cents
for every dollar that men earn. ...
   ``George Bush doesn't even know that almost 40 million Americans
_ mostly working people and their families _ don't have a dime's
worth of health insurance. ...
   ``George Bush wants to help the people who already have it made.
I want to help every American family make it.''
   The Democratic nominee described his family as ``more precious
to me than anything in the world. And no matter what else one has
in life, there's nothing more important than that.''
   Later today, Dukakis was heading to New York to film campaign
commercials and attend the annual Alfred E. Smith charity dinner,
where he will share the spotlight with Bush.
   The dinner, sponsored by the Roman Catholic archdiocese of New
York, customarily attracts the presidential candidates of both
major parties, who are under instructions to keep their remarks
humorous rather than political.
   On Wednesday, during a bus tour through rural southern Illinois
and Missouri, Dukakis erupted angrily over a steady barrage of
Republican attacks on the Massachusetts prison furlough program.
   Dukakis campaign officials, trying to counter the damage done by
Bush crime ads, were considering airing their own commercial.
   With Dukakis admittedly trailing Bush in these closing weeks of
the campaign, his strategists also were looking for ways to get his
message out to voters and close the gap.
   ``We're playing with different ways to more dramatically
communicate with people,'' said Dukakis adviser Leslie Dach.
   Among those under consideration were buying five minutes on the
major television networks for a Dukakis speech, and the purchase of
larger blocks of time _ as long as 30 minutes _ for either a town
meeting style program or a national call-in show.
   ``All sorts of different options are being weighed,'' said press
secretary Dayton Duncan.
   In the effort to widen his audience, Dukakis also was appearing
on the ABC show ``Good Morning America'' on Friday and probably
would be on the ABC program ``Nightline'' next week.
   Dukakis and Bush were invited to separate interviews on
``Nightline,'' but the vice president declined.
   The Democratic nominee got mixed news on the polling front.
   A new ABC News-Washington Post poll released Wednesday said Bush
was leading Dukakis by seven points, a margin cheered by the
Democratic candidate's aides who were looking for any sign that a
recent NBC News-Wall Street Journal poll that had the margin at 17
points was incorrect.
   A Louis Harris poll said the Bush lead was nine points. A week
earlier, the same survey said Bush was leading by two points.
   Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas said the candidate
decided to respond forcefully to the Republican attacks after he
was shown material mailed to voters by the Illinois Republican
Party.
   ``All The Murderers, and Rapists, and Drug Pushers and Child
Molesters in Massachusetts Vote for Mike Dukakis,'' a brochure was
headlined in bold type.
   The material alleged that convicts in Massachusetts have the
right to vote.
   It cited the governor's opposition to the death penalty and his
support for the state's controversial prison furlough program.
   In Quincy, Ill., Dukakis held up the GOP campaign material and
told an outdoor rally, ``This is garbage, this is political
garbage.''
   ``This isn't worthy of a presidential campaign.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
