<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras     10-20 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Nicaragua Should Be Pressured Into Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Honduran president said other
nations should pressure Nicaragua ``to become a democracy'' and
blamed the Sandinista regime for the hundreds of thousands of
refugees from the civil war.
   President Jose Azcona Hoya said 55,000 Nicaraguans are in
refugee camps along his country's southern border, in addition to
about 8,000 Contras who retreated after U.S. military aid ended in
February.
   Azcona Hoya blamed Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government for
the problem. ``A government that creates refugees and political
exiles cannot be a good government,'' he said in an interview
Tuesday.
   He said there must be an ``international reaction to pressure
Nicaragua into a political solution'' of the problem.
   ``Let us assume that (President) Reagan was wrong and his
policies of support for the Contras were wrong. Well, now the
United States is stepping aside. There is no more military aid,''
Azcona Hoya said.
   ``What is to be done? Other countries must become involved and
force Nicaragua to become a democratic country. It is time the
democratic countries of the world take a firm stand on this,'' he
said.
   The Contras are receiving non-military aid under a $17 million
program Congress approved in March, the same month Nicaragua's
leftist government and the Contras began a cease-fire. The truce is
still in place, but peace talks that would lead to a permanent
solution have broken down.
   Last month, Honduras issued a call at the United Nations for a
peace force involving Canada, Spain and West Germany to patrol its
borders with Nicaragua and El Salvador. Few believe the proposal
will be carried out.
   Azcona Hoyo called it ``a drastic move to show that we are not
interested in attacking Nicaragua,'' whose government ``has not
acted like someone concerned about peace.
   ``When they could push for a dialogue, they have toughened their
stand internally, jailing political opponents. Now that the Contra
is silenced completely they go to the opposite side and do not try
to look for reconciliation.''
   Honduras, the recipient of substantial U.S. military aid, hosts
U.S. military forces and has long harbored Contras in their war
against the Sandinistas. More than 1,000 U.S. soldiers are
stationed in Honduras.
   The United States has built installations in Honduras to monitor
activity in Nicaragua and staged joint military exercises with
Honduras. The Americans have directed Honduran troops to the border
at least once to repel Nicaraguan troops chasing Contras.
   More than 200,000 Nicaraguans live in Honduras, a nation of 5
million people. Honduras is also home to tens of thousands of
refugees from the civil war in neighboring El Salvador.
</TEXT>
