<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash-Film,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hollywood Production Company Interested in TV Movie on Deadly Bus
Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families affected by a church bus
crash that killed 27 people have begun cooperating with a Hollywood
production company interested in making a television movie or
miniseries about the accident.
   Bill Nichols, whose son died in the May 14 wreck, said he and
members of the other families realized ``somebody's going to make a
movie of it, and we wanted to have some input.''
   A representative of Krantz Productions Inc. of Studio City,
Calif., is expected to meet with the families next month.
   Nichols said the families and Krantz want to emphasize the
danger of driving under the influence of alcohol.
   Larry Mahoney, 35, was allegedly drunk and was driving the wrong
way on Interstate 71 when his pickup truck collided with a Radcliff
church bus carrying 63 youths and four adults near Carrollton.
Twenty-seven people, including 24 of the youths, died during a fire
that erupted soon after impact, and many others were injured.
   Mahoney returned Oct. 10 to his parents' home in Owen County
after relatives and friends provided $540,000 in cash and property
to secure his appearance in court.
   He is scheduled to go on trial Jan. 9 in Carroll Circuit Court
on 27 counts of murder, 13 counts of first-degree assault, 44
counts of wanton endangerment and one count of driving under the
influence.
   Krantz spokesman Brian LaPan said Tuesday that the company was
still developing the project. He said representatives will discuss
various aspects of the movie with the families sometime after the
producer returns late next week from Europe.
   Nichols said his contact with Krantz indicated ``the movie will
focus on a few of the individuals on the bus.''
   The families will suggest some people to spotlight, he said,
such as Lee Williams, whose wife and two daughters died on the bus;
John Pearman, the bus driver who died, and Christy Pearman, his
daughter who was burned and had severe problems with smoke
inhalation; Carey Aurentz, a girl who had to have a foot amputated;
and the families who lost their only children.
</TEXT>
