<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FarmersFined     10-20 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers Fined,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mspi Farmers Fined for Pumping Water During Drought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven Mississippi Delta farmers have been
fined by the state Department of Natural Resources for violating
bans on irrigation during this past summer's drought.
   In a related development, the Commission on Natural Resources
has voted to ban irrigation pumping from several other Delta rivers
and bayous because of continued low water.
   Officials said the ban would not affect growing crops at this
time of year but would restrict manmade flooding for waterfowl
habitat.
   The bans are the latest in a series of restrictions on water use
in a region of the state once known for its abundance of water.
   The drought lowered water in the Delta, which normally drains
into the Mississippi River, and streams which flow into it are too
low to replenish it.
   ``We have one heck of a problem with water in the Delta,'' said
Commissioner Robert Travis of Jackson.
   During its Wednesday session, the commission imposed a reduced
fine on the only Delta farmer to request a hearing on the summer's
irrigation ban violations.
   Donald Aylward of Pace, manager of Laban Planting Co., said he
felt the fines for violating orders banning pumping from Delta
streams were unreasonable.
   The commission voted to reduce Aylward's fine to $1,500 because
he agreed to pump well water from one of his upstream farms into
the Bogue Phalia River to replace water he was pumping from the
river downstream. He had faced a maximum fine of $6,000.
   Six other farmers were fined the maximum.
</TEXT>
