<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Officer'sHunch     10-20 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Officer's Hunch,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Heads Off Bank Robbery Suspects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAINTREE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty policeman heard a radio
report that a Bank of New England branch office had been robbed,
and he had a hunch about where the crooks might go.
   Lt. Donald Murphy, who was at home when he heard the report
Tuesday, sped to the South Shore Plaza mall because he thought the
robbers might go there to switch cars.
   His hunch paid off when he spotted four men running down a slope
from a highway to the mall parking lot.
   Murphy watched the four split up into two getaway cars. He used
his portable radio to call for backup and then followed one of the
cars into Quincy.
   After a chase, another car blocked the car Murphy was following
and he was able to arrest two men.
   The suspects in the other car, believed to have contained the
$30,000 stolen from the bank, were not caught.
   Two guns and a police radio receiver were found in the trunk of
the car Murphy chased. Murphy said the suspects apparently stopped
monitoring police activity on the radio after the robbery.
   ``They thought they had it made,'' he said. ``They thought they
were going to drive right out of this.''
   Thomas M. Kavanaugh, 29, and John J. Maguire, 39, both of
Boston, were arraigned Wednesday in Quincy District Court on
charges of armed robbery while masked and illegal possession of a
firearm.
   Murphy said both men are convicted felons with extensive records.
</TEXT>
