<HEAD>Lufthansa Jet Skids Off End of Runway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lufthansa jumbo jet carrying
88 people skidded off the end of a wet runway Thursday and ended up
with its nose stuck in grass, but no one was injured, airline
officials said.
   The accident occurred at the Duesseldorf airport about 2 p.m. as
the DC-10 landed in rainy weather.
   The jet, carrying 75 passengers and 13 crewmembers, stopped
``with its nose wheel stuck in a wet grassy area just off the end
of the runway,'' said Lufthansa spokesman Klaus Ulrich Mueller.
   Airline spokeswoman Heidi Buchheister said the plane was flying
from Frankfurt to Toronto, via Duesseldorf.
   Lufthansa said the pilot reported poor braking conditions ``due
to water standing on the runway.''
   Duesseldorf is about 125 miles north of Frankfurt.
