<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissileDestruction 1stLd-Writethru a0516tenedOfferByManagementGroup
10-20 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missile Destruction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Initial Missile Destruction Finished in Arizona; Soviets to Depart</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Soviets leaving; Picks up
4th graf, `One Tuesday...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With 41 American cruise missiles sliced up
like split steel bananas, Soviet inspectors who observed the
destruction under provisions of the Intermediate-Range Nuclear
Forces Treaty began their trip home today.
   The 11 Soviets, including military and civilian members of the
Soviet Union's on-site inspection agency, rested at Davis-Monthan
Air Force Base before departing this morning about a U.S. military
jet.
   They planned to fly to Travis Air Force Base near San Francisco,
where some planned to go to the Soviets' permanent treaty
monitoring site at Magna, Utah, before returning to Moscow, said
U.S. Air Force Col. Larry Jones.
   On Tuesday and Wednesday, three civilian American teams at
Davis-Monthan's Aerospace Maintenance and Regeneration Center
worked around the clock with handheld saws and plasma arc torches.
   In 28 hours they completed the task of cutting in half the first
batch of 41 Air Force ground-launched cruise missiles, 41
protective canisters and seven launch vehicles, called transporter
erector launchers, putting an end to the destructive potential of
weapons once capable of delivering nuclear warheads.
   The warheads, along with fuel and guidance systems, had been
removed before the dismantling process, with the nuclear armaments
being turned over to the Department of Energy for storage,
officials said.
   The last of the 41 missiles was dismantled Wednesday evening
with the Soviets watching, said Capt. Chuck Roque, an Air Force
spokesman. Original target time for completing the cuts was Friday,
72 hours after the Soviets' arrival Tuesday.
   Under the INF Treaty, 443 Air Force land-based cruise missiles,
many of which have been deployed in Europe, are to be destroyed
within the pact's first three years. In addition, 403 Army Pershing
missiles are slated for destruction, along with 1,846 Soviet
missiles of six types.
</TEXT>
