<HEAD>Candidates Sidestepping Concerns of Hispanic, Blacks And The Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hispanic leaders on Thursday charged both
presidential candidates with ignoring issues affecting Hispanics,
black and the poor to avoid being labeled liberal.
   ``Neither candidate or campaign has done a reasonable job of
addressing these concerns or articulating an economic agenda that
will lift us out of the height of economic depression,'' said Ruben
Bonilla Jr., general counsel of the League of United Latin American
Citizens, a Hispanic umbrella organization.
   ``We believe they are not addressing the issues because they
don't want to antagonize or offend the Anglo community,'' LULAC
president Jose Garcia De Lara told a press conference.
   ``We want to hear them say what we are going to do to eliminate
poverty in this country, what governmental beneficial programs are
we going to initiate, what are we going to do about the lack of
affordable housing?'' he said.
   De Lara mentioned Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis' housing
plan based on cashing in an Individual Retirement Account to use as
a down payment on a house.
   ``The problem is that the poor do not have IRAs _ this shows how
out of touch these candidates are,'' he said.
   Bonilla singled out for criticism Dan Quayle, the Republican
vice presidential nominee.
   He said the Indiana senator has ``the most regressive voting
record on Capitol Hill,'' noting the candidate's opposition to
bilingual education, voting rights act, bilingual ballot, child
nuturition programs and his support of taxing certain veteran's
benefits.
   De Lara said the organization does not plan to formally endorse
any candidate.
