<HEAD>Homeless Demonstrators Cleared from Quayle's Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Thursday arrested 19 candle-carrying
demonstrators from Minnesota who crowded into Sen. Dan Quayle's
office on Capitol Hill to demand more aid to the homeless.
   ``Sen. Quayle has consistently voted against affordable housing
in the last eight years,'' Steve O'Neil of Duluth, Minn., told
reporters in a hallway of the Hart Senate Office Building.
   Homeless activists have been arrested daily for the past three
weeks for demonstrating at the Capitol. Earlier, they carried away
furniture from the office of Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., in a
symbolic ``eviction'' and chanted slogans in the Senate gallery.
   On Thursday, the Capitol Police were waiting for the
demonstrators when they descended on the office of the Republican
vice presidential candidate, an Indiana senator.
   The police allowed the demonstrators to light candles in
Quayle's office and unfurl a large banner in his window that could
be seen from scores of other Senate offices.
   ``A thousand points of light or a million lives,'' the banner
said, referring to Republican nominee George Bush's ``thousand
points of light'' campaign theme about private, voluntary social
programs.
   Quayle was campaigning in Ohio on Thursday. His office staff
continued working without looking at the demonstrators, who urged
passage of legislation that would provide $25 billion to house the
homeless.
   About 15 minutes after the protest began, the police moved in
and arrested the 19 demonstrators. They were charged with unlawful
entry and demonstrating in a Capitol building, punishable by a
maximum $5,000 fine and six months in jail.
   They were to be arraigned in D.C. Superior Court.
   Like others arrested in recent homeless demonstrations, the
Minnesotans said they were loosely affiliated with the
Washington-based Community for Creative Non-Violence. That
organization's leader, Mitch Snyder, has had a long-running feud
with the Reagan administration over assistance to the homeless.
