<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-20 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASCAGOULA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One ``big cheese'' at the
recommissioning of the USS Wisconsin this weekend won't be in
uniform or making a speech.
   A 500-pound block of fine Wisconsin Cheddar will weigh in as a
mighty 5-foot-long replica of the 58,000-ton battleship, which was
refurbished at Ingalls Shipbuilding in Pascagoula.
   For 25-year-old Allen Hendricks, who gets to sculpt the $1,000
hunk, the job is the project of a lifetime.
   ``I've made a totem pole out of provolone and the leaning Tower
of Pisa is popular,'' Hendricks said. ``But it's not every day you
get to work with a 500-pound block of cheese.
   ``This is by far the biggest project I've done _ as far as the
event, the project itself and of course, as far as the cheese.''
   Hendricks' sculpture will be the star attraction Saturday at the
reception after the recommissioning.
   The cheese came courtesy of the Wisconsin Milk Marketing Board,
which will supply all the cheese at the reception.
   But this particular cheese is special, according to Hendricks.
It is completely hand-made, from start to finish _ including the
cloth wrappings that allow it to ripen naturally.
   Hendricks, who was flown in from Washington for the project,
spent 60 hours just planning and drawing designs.
   He plans to sculpt the guns and turrets from cheese and get
details such as radar antennae with bamboo and wire.
   Hendricks also plans to chip the massive base of the sculpture
so that the white streaks in the cheese will look like water.
   As for all the cheese he chips away, Hendricks said, ``To the
best of my knowledge, I'll probably have a cheese sandwich for
lunch.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLUFF CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The thought of slow-moving ducks
waddling on a curved road without protection was too much for Tim
White, so he shelled out the money for new crossing signs after the
originals were stolen.
   ``I just couldn't sleep at night thinking there is Bluff City
without any duck signs. It's your moral obligation to jump in and
do what you have to,'' the owner of White Advertising said.
   White said the warnings will have an added feature, a reflective
finish.
   ``It's one of those things that applies to my trade, which is
signs,'' he said. ``It's part of smelling the roses.''
   Ducks congregate along the stretch of road near Boone Lake and
often wander into the road. Mayor Billy Wells and another volunteer
paid $52 for the first set in May, fearing for the birds' safety.
Wells first tried to charge the city, but aldermen complained the
signs were a needless expense.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: American elm is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's official now. The mammoth elm that
has graced the Pottawatomie County landscape for what could be a
century has been declared the biggest American elm tree in the
United States by the American Forestry Association.
   Gary Naughton, the state extension forester who first measured
the elm in 1978, said he received a call Tuesday from the AFA
informing him that the tree, named the Louis Vieux Elm, was back on
top.
   The Louis Vieux was declared the biggest American elm in the
United States in 1985. The next year, a 125-foot tree in Virginia
unseated the Kansas elm, located on the Vermillion River between
Manhattan and Topeka, Kan.
   Now the Virginia tree has succumbed to Dutch elm disease, but
Virginians are not about to give up yet, Naughton said.
   ``The people in Virginia are just convinced that Virginia has
the biggest tree,'' he said. ``They're out in the woods every day
looking. For the moment, we're official.''
   Naughton said he thought the Louis Vieux eventually would have
bypassed the tree in Virginia on its own.
   The Louis Vieux was last measured three growing seasons ago in
May 1986. At the time, it was 96 feet tall, with a trunk
circumference of 299 inches and an average crown spread of 124 feet.

</TEXT>
