<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia Bjt   10-20 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, Bjt,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Serbs Hold Mass Protests in Kosovo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Serbs rallied in
ethnically troubled Kosovo province Thursday against a setback
dealt their nationalist leader, and they jeered two Politburo
members who tried to address them.
   Parliament eased an unpopular austerity program, allowing salary
increases for some workers that will compensate in part for the
annual inflation rate of 217 percent.
   Weeks of strikes and turmoil over ethnic and economic problems
have threatened the stability of Yugoslavia, a fragile federation
of several nationalities whose leadership has been weak since
President Tito died in 1980.
   About 5,000 people in a historic suburb of Pristina, Kosovo's
capital, taunted Politburo members Marko Orlandic and Kacusa Jasari
with chants of ``Thieves!'' and ``You betrayed the people!''
   They turned their backs when the party leaders tried to speak,
and police hustled Orlandic and Mrs. Jasari away when Serbs tried
to mob them.
   A crowd police estimated at more than 20,000 gathered nearby for
a later rally protesting a blow by the national party leadership to
the effort by Slobodan Milosevic, Communist Party chief of the
Serbian republic, to gain more control over Kosovo.
   The southern province, heart of ancient Serbia, borders Albania
and ethnic Albanians now make up 90 percent of the population.
   Yugoslavia consists of six republics and two autonomous
provinces, each with its own government and party structure. Serbia
is the largest republic and both provinces, Kosovo and Vojvodina,
are part of it but not fully subject to its control.
   Tito put the decentralized system of government in his 1974
constitution to prevent one republic from gaining sway after his
death, but the result has been ineffective government by compromise.
   Dusan Ckrebic, a Serbian communist closely identified with
Milosevic, lost a secret confidence vote Wednesday at the end of a
three-day session of the national party Central Committee.
   He was the only one of 10 Politburo members subject to the vote
who did not get a majority in the 165-member Central Committee and
has offered to resign. The vote was seen as a defeat for Milosevic.
   At the larger rally Thursday, Serbs chanted ``We will not give
up Ckrebic!'' ``We will not give up Dusan!'' and ``Central
Committee members, you have shown your true faces!''
   Kosovo's 200,000 Serbs and Montenegrins had hoped the Central
Committee would dismiss some ethnic Albanians jfrom the Kosovo
party leadership.
   No action was taken, however, nor were measures announced
against what the minority describes as constant harassment from
ethnic Albanians. Thousands of Slavs have left the province since
1981, when at least nine people were killed in an outburst of
ethnic violence.
   Orlandic and Mrs. Jasari, head of the Kosovo Communist Party,
tried to placate the angry crowd in Kosovo Polje, built on the site
of a 14th century battle in which the Serbs defeated the Turks.
   Few listened and after about an hour some Serbs tried to grab
the microphone. The Politburo members were driven away in their
black limousine, down a side street under police escort.
   Miloslav Minicof the Serbian Central Committee promised those
attending the later rally that their demands for the ouster of Azem
Vlasi, an ethnic Albanian party leader in Kosovo, would be
considered by the federal leadership. The crowd began dispersing
peacefully as darkness fell.
   A 15-member committee of Kosovo Serbs was formed to press for
the dismissal of ethnic Albanian leaders. It announced plans for
street protests and urged Slavic members of the Kosovo leadership
to resign as an example and protest.
   Milosevic told a crowd of workers in a Belgrade industrial
suburb only the Serbian party had the right to decide whether his
ally Ckrebic should resign from the national Politburo.
   Stipe Suvar, chief of the national party, said loss of a
conference vote by a Politburo member was unprecedented.
   Party leaders from other regions have been angered by
Milosevic's support of nationalist rallies by Serbs, and suspect
him of seeking greater power at their expense.
   Parliament's relaxation of the austerity program allows raises
of 140-152 percent for workers in profitable enterprises and in
social services like health and education.
   The changes were approved by the International Monetary Fund,
which demanded the austerity program as a condition for helping
Yugoslavia deal with its $21 billion foreign debt.
</TEXT>
