<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle     10-20 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Courts Blue-Collar Workers With Full Employment Pitch</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZANESVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate
Dan Quayle courted blue-collar workers and students in a hotly
competitive state Thursday, declaring economic recovery during the
Reagan administration means ``a job for all who want to work.''
   Rejecting the Democrats' contention that many new jobs are
relatively low-paying, Quayle said, ``This economy is generating
millions of jobs in high-paying occupations. Taken together, wages
and fringe benefits have gone up 40 percent, about a third faster
than inflation.''
   In addition to his statements on traditional Republican themes,
he challenged businesses in a state where the Democrats have been
strong to offer day care and to include minorities in the economic
recovery.
   ``Smarter employers will understand they can't recruit good
people if they have employment practices that force them to choose
between being good workers and good parents,'' said Quayle.
``Employers who aren't so smart will fail, and deserve to.''
   A remaining economic challenge ``is the full integration of
blacks and Hispanics into the economy,'' he said. ``The last seven
yeras have built a foundation for doing exactly that.''
   On another subject, at a shopping mall rally, Quayle ridiculed
Dukakis' complaints that the Republicans have distorted his record
on crime issues.
   ``Let's give a few facts on crime, and I'll try not to add any
comments that further embarrass Mr. Dukkakis,'' Quayle said.
   He said Dukakis ``opposes the death penalty no matter how
horrible the crime'' and ``defended his furlough program throughout
his governorship.''
   ``He refused to change it until forced to do so by public
pressure in this election year,'' Quayle said.
   He recited other positions he said showed Dukakis was weak on
crime and led a crowd of more than 1,000 in chanting ``Good night,
Mike.''
   Earlier, before cheering college students, he touted the
administration's economic record.
   ``It means for the first time ever, we can make and keep the
promise of a job for every American who wants a job,'' said Quayle.
``It adds up to a job for all who want to work.''
   He said the Reagan administration has created 12 million new
jobs paying more than $20,000, including more than 5 million
averaging closer to $30,000 a year.
   Polls indicate the presidential race in Ohio is close, and
Quayle stumped through the eastern part of the state in an effort
to secure a Republican victory.
   The message, aides said, was aimed at blue-collar voters by
telling them the nation is far better off than when President
Reagan took office.
   Reagan campaigned in Ohio on Wednesday to emphasize the
importance Republicans are placing on the Midwestern industrial
state.
   Underscoring the economic message, Quayle was joined in his bus
caravan by Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin.
   His bus caravan wound through small industrial communities on
Thursday with stops in McConnelsville, Newark, Columbus and
Chillicothe. He planned on spending Friday in Georgia and Tennessee
before taking the weekend off the campaign trail.
   ``Don't want to get tired and mess up,'' said Quayle, explaining
his time off less than three weeks before the Nov. 8 election.
``Might possibly cost you to lose the election.''
   Quayle spoke with groups of schoolchildren briefly dismissed
from class, telling them to ``pay attention to your teachers. You
know what? You might grow up and run for vice president some day.''
   In his speeches, the message was sharper though he said he was
only raising issues Dukakis won't discuss.
   ``If I had their liberal ideas, I guess I wouldn't want to talk
about them either,'' said Quayle. ``Since they don't want to talk
it, we'll talk about it.
   ``You know and I know that their liberal approach to economics
will take us backward to higher inflation, high interest rates,
higher unemployment.''
   The bus caravan was a festive affair winding through the fall
colors, taking an occasional break for small-town parades in
antique automobiles.
   It started on a gloomy day in dense fog, conditions Quayle likes
to call ``Dukakis weather,'' but that weather soon gave way to
bright sunshine.
</TEXT>
