<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-US     10-20 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-US,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Government Seeks Swifter Improvement in Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday following a
visit by a U.S. deputy secretary of state that relations with the
United States are not improving fast enough.
   The Oct. 12-13 visit by Deputy Secretary of State John C.
Whitehead was ``a step forward in mutual relations, though it is
not yet what one could expect,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman
Stefan Staniszewski.
   It was Whitehead's second visit to Poland this year and his
third since a thaw in U.S.-Polish relations began in early 1987,
leading to a lifting of U.S. Economic sanctions imposed after the
1981 martial law crackdown on the Solidarity trade union.
   ``The United States, despite its earlier declarations
encouraging us to bold reforms, in fact continues to stick to its
wait-and-see attitude,'' Staniszewski said.
   Staniszewski said he was referring to a lack of steps to develop
economic relations, including aid from the United States to Poland,
U.S. backing of aid through international organizations, and
investment in Poland by private American companies.
   As far as specific possibilities of utilizing credits, Whitehead
could only mention loans allowing Poland to buy up to 8,000 tons of
surplus U.S. food, he said.
   If Poland were to use the credits to buy butter, the most
expensive item, then they would be worth $16 million, he said. ``We
can buy butter cheaper elsewhere,'' he added.
   Whitehead said at the conclusion of his visit that future aid to
Poland depended on favorable trends in political and economic
liberalization. He also said that the United States continues to
hope for relegalization of Solidarity.
   Poland has a foreign debt of nearly $40 billion, the highest in
the East bloc. It seeks Western credits to allow it to rebuild
aging factories and develop new sources of hard-currency earnings.
</TEXT>
