<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Candidates-Peace     10-20 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Candidates-Peace,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Religious Leaders Prod Bush, Dukakis On World Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Religious leaders from several denominations
urged presidential candidates George Bush and Michael Dukakis on
Thursday to stop talking about what weapons they would support and
lay out plans for a more peaceful world.
   ``There is yet time in this campaign to move beyond the sterile
and spiritless argument over Midgetman versus MX missiles, over
conventional buildup versus Star Wars,'' Roman Catholic Bishop
Thomas J. Gumbleton of Detroit told reporters.
   The bishop, joined by top Protestant and Jewish ministers,
called for Bush and Dukakis to spell out how they would ensure
world peace, protect global security without nuclear weapons and
strengthen the role of the United Nations.
   Earlier this month, 100 members of a new organization, ``Choose
Peace, Religious Leaders in Defense of Creation,'' signed letters
mailed to both candidates urging each to ``define your
comprehenvise, long-term plan for peace, with the specific steps
you would take during your administration to move toward its
fulfillment.''
   Members said their organization is non-partisan.
</TEXT>
