<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     10-20 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0796</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Denies Members Removed For Opposing Rebel Reconciliation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior official of the ruling party
on Thursday denied that party members were removed because they
opposed President Najib's drive for a peaceful settlement with
U.S.-backed rebels.
   Government radio, meanwhile, said seven people, including an
American, were killed when their car hit a mine in southeastern
Afghanistan.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, Pakistan, said the car was
loaded with weapons for the guerrillas. It said the seven,
including the American, four Pakistanis and two Egyptians, were
killed in Zabul province but did not say when and gave no names.
   On Sunday, the radio said two U.S. advisers to the rebels were
killed during a government attack on rebel positions near Gardez,
60 miles southeast of Kabul. Western diplomats have said no
American citizens are in Afghanistan on official business.
   The party official, Mohammad Wali, said that since Soviet troops
began leaving Afghanistan on May 15, 20,000 ``terrorists'' have
entered Afghanistan from Pakistan and 450 cars containing weapons
have been found.
   Wali spoke to Western and Soviet-bloc reporters at a briefing on
Wednesday's meeting of the Central Committee of the People's
Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   He said Najib accused the United States of taking advantage of
the Soviet withdrawal to intensify shipments of arms to the rebels.
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979, and
about 100,000 have helped the Marxist government fight the rebels.
Under a U.N. agreement signed in April, all the troops are to be
out by Feb. 15.
   Two party Politburo members were dismissed Wednesday, but Wali
denied it was because they disagreed with Najib.
   ``The health of the two was not so good,'' said Wali, chief of
the Central Committee's organization department.
   One of the pair, Zalour Razinjo, is in his early 30s and is not
known to have any ailments.
   The other, Saleh Mohammad Zarry, is believed to be in his 60s.
The chief known threat to his health was an assassination attempt
last spring, a foreign diplomatic source said on condition of
anonymity.
   This source and other observers said Zarry and Razinjo opposed
the Red Army withdrawal.
   Wali said the pair did not disagree with ``national
reconciliation,'' the government's term for a negotiated settlement
and the focus of Wednesday's meeting.
   About 15 hours before the meeting started, state-run television
said some party members were arrested but did not say how many. An
offical source said they were seized because they opposed national
reconciliation. Wali said he did not know how many were arrested.
   Various foreign observers said between 17 and 350 were arrested,
including three members of the Central Committee. Afghan observers
said the total was in the dozens.
   Wali said the Central Committee has 97 members, far below the
140 reported by well-placed Afghan and foreign observers. He did
not report any recent dismissals and he declined to say how many
attended Wednesday's session.
   Wali said Najib told participants the party has given up ``the
monopoly of power, and the party is ready to take further peaceful
steps.''
   Najib is the leader of both the government and the party, but he
has tried to portray them as separate entities.
   Last spring, he made a show of broadening the base of his
government by appointing a non-party member, Mohammad Hasan Sharq,
prime minister. The 32-man Cabinet headed by Sharq, a pragmatic
political survivor with good ties to Moscow, has at least 14
non-party members.
   But Politburo members retain five key ministerial posts:
defense, state security, interior, foreign affairs and
communications. The Politburo had 13 members until Wednesday's two
dismissals.
   Asked whether the Central Commitee planned to take more party
members out of the Cabinet in the interest of national
reconciliation, Wali said the party is ready to compromise, but he
declined to say how and to what extent.
   Wali said Najib also stressed the need for talks with guerrilla
commanders on an individual basis. The Pakistan-based rebel leaders
have refused to deal with Najib and the party.
   In other developments Wednesday:
   _ The official Soviet news agency Tass said two members of the
anti-government Islamic Society of Afghanistan were sentenced in
Kabul to death and two others sentenced to prison for a car bombing
that killed 14 people and injured 30. It said the Sept. 11 bombing
was masterminded in Pakistan.
   _ Tass said 10 rockets were fired at the capital Wednesday and
that one hit a house, killing two children and wounding their
parents. On Wednesday, about 60 rockets were fired, killing nine
people and wounding 25, Tass said.
</TEXT>
