<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1707EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BarredLawyer     10-20 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Barred Lawyer,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Posthumous Reinstatement of Black Attorney to Florida
Bar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: In lede, The Florida Bar is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black man who fought for almost 30
years for the right to practice law in Florida was posthumously
reinstated to The Florida Bar on Thursday by a unanimous state
Supreme Court.
   In its decision to reinstate Virgil Darnell Hawkins, the court
said, ``Hawkins' struggle for equal justice under the law should be
memorialized.''
   Hawkins, who died Feb. 11, resigned from the bar more than three
years ago.
   His struggle began in 1949 when, at the age of 41, he was denied
admission to the University of Florida School of Law because of his
race. Seven years later, the U.S. Supreme Court ordered that
Hawkins was entitled to prompt admission to the university.
   However, the Florida Supreme Court refused to admit Hawkins to
the university because of the potential for ``great public
mischief'' resulting from admitting blacks to white state schools.
   The ``public mischief'' referred to in the opinion consisted of
threats by white parents to have their children leave or transfer
schools if blacks were admitted.
   Hawkins finally attended law school in Boston, but was later
denied permission to take the Florida Bar exam because the school
was unaccredited.
   In 1976, the Florida Supreme Court, in an attempt to remedy
injustices of the past, ordered that Hawkins be admitted to the Bar
without having to take the exam.
   The next year, at the age of 69, Hawkins opened his law office
in Leesburg, ``seldom turning away an indigent client in need,''
the court noted.
   However, Hawkins ultimately faced disciplinary proceedings as a
result, the court said, of a practice that reflected his age, the
strain of practicing alone and the lapse of years since law school.
   He pleaded no contest to misappropriating $15,000 in clients'
funds and filed a petition to resign from the bar that was accepted
on April 18, 1985.
   ``When I get to heaven, I want to be a member of the Florida
Bar,'' Hawkins told the court. He died Feb. 11.
   Many attorneys from throughout the state joined a petition filed
by Harley Scott Herman of Leesburg to reinstate Hawkins
posthumously.
   Rutledge Liles, president of The Florida Bar, applauded the
court's decision to do so, noting Hawkins' ``unique contributions
to opening the practice of law in Florida to persons of all races.''
   ``To his undying memory, it is a tribute to the man that he
fought successfully and unselfishly to correct such a wrong,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
