<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CaliforniaSenate     10-20 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-California Senate,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Close California Senate Race Features Two Similar Politicians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pete Wilson and Leo McCarthy bristle
at suggestions that they're politicians cut from the same cloth.
   Similar in experience, temperament and speaking style, Wilson,
who is seeking his second term as California's junior senator, and
McCarthy, his Democratic challenger, are both cautious career
politicians who are more inclined to pragmatic compromises than to
extreme ideological posturing.
   Little wonder it has taken this long for the contest to catch
fire.
   Wilson has led in every poll, but the margins have steadily
slipped from a high of 22 percent in early 1987 to a low of 3
points last week. The race appears tight in the closing weeks.
   The candidates are each spending millions in California's
super-heated television wars. One Wilson ad shows the closed gates
in front of a posh San Diego condominium complex where McCarthy
owns two units and wonders ``Where does all of McCarthy's money
come from?''
   A McCarthy ad has drawn howls of protest from Wilson's campaign.
It features Republican Senate Leader Bob Dole talking about a 1985
budget vote that was so close an ill and sedated Wilson was wheeled
in from the hospital. ``I said vote yes. He voted yes. We rolled
him out again. He does better under sedation,'' Dole says.
   Wilson, 55, and McCarthy, 58, are both attorneys who have spent
most of their adult lives in public office. Wilson was elected to
the state Assembly at age 33, and McCarthy to the San Francisco
Board of Supervisors, also at age 33.
   They served together in the Assembly for three years, 1968
through 1971, when Wilson was elected mayor of San Diego. McCarthy
went on to become Speaker of the Assembly, a post he held from 1974
to 1980, while Wilson served 11 years as mayor. Wilson was elected
to the Senate in 1982 in the same election that McCarthy won his
first of two terms as lieutenant governor.
   Even though their careers took parallel paths, their differences
are clear on the issues.
   Wilson is a fiscal conservative who believes the key is less
government interference, while McCarthy is a liberal who doesn't
hesitate to use the authority of the government to achieve his
goals.
   ``We shouldn't spend money in Congress to create jobs,'' says
Wilson. ``What we should spend it for is to keep America strong in
order to keep America free.''
   McCarthy takes exactly the opposite approach, criticizing
Wilson's record of unwavering support of the economic policies of
President Reagan and Vice President George Bush.
   The contrast is even sharper on defense and foreign policy
issues.
   ``We ought to take $1 billion from Star Wars and put it in the
classroom so our kids can get a decent education,'' McCarthy says.
   Wilson has supported aid to the Contras in Nicaragua, backs
Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative defense system and champions
California's defense industry.
   McCarthy has been an outspoken critic of Reagan's policies
throughout Central America, and especially in Nicaragua, and is
skeptical of the levels of spending throughout the defense
department.
   They both shun the anti-abortion and prayer-in-school political
agenda of the far right, and like McCarthy, Wilson is an advocate
of child care and major reforms in health care for the elderly.
   Wilson also has a much stronger environmentalist record than
most Republicans, including a strong stance against oil drilling
off the California coast.
   But while Wilson's moderate record on environmental and social
issues has blurred the differences for the average voter, McCarthy
has the support of the majority of activists for those issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
