<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TransplantBaby     10-20 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transplant Baby,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman with Heart Transplant Gives Birth to Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 41-year-old woman who had a heart
transplant two years ago said Thursday she was elated at the birth
of her first child, a 3{-pound boy who ``knows my voice already.''
   ``He doesn't like to be messed around with a whole lot,'' said
the child's father, Gary V. Snell Sr., who joined his wife,
Bernita, and week-old son, Gary Jr., in a press conference at the
Medical College of Virginia Hospitals. ``He's a little fighter.''
   The boy, delivered eight weeks prematurely on Oct. 14, is only
the third child known to be born to a heart transplant recipient.
The other two births were in Europe and California.
   ``During the early stages of my pregnancy, I thought it was
cardiac rejection,'' said Mrs. Snell, who received her new heart
Aug. 17, 1986, at the hospital center.
   Yet despite the risks posed by the strain of carrying a child
and having to take anti-rejection drugs from the transplant, she
decided against initial counseling to terminate the pregnancy.
   Dr. James A. Thompson, a cardiologist, said Mrs. Snell's heart
therapy was not altered during her pregnancy, and she came through
the most critical first three months without problems.
   Dr. Patricia Hays, Mrs. Snell's obstetrician, said the special
circumstances of the case made an induced early delivery a
consideration until Mrs. Snell had a premature rupture of the
membrane.
   The infant's condition is not unusual for a premature baby, and
Gary Jr. is expected to be home with his parents by Thanksgiving,
the doctors said.
   ``So far, everything looks perfectly normal,'' said Dr. Gary
Gutcher, chairman of the medical center's division of neonatology.
   Mrs. Snell, who was released from the hospital Tuesday, said she
makes the 75- to 80-mile drive every day from her home in Hampton
to the hospital with her 38-year-old truck driver husband to see
their son.
   ``I'm so glad I did it,'' she said. ``I'm thankful to God for
him.''
</TEXT>
