<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1918EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Whales-Tow     10-20 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whales-Tow,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter Tow A Learning Experience</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trapped Whales, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRUDHOE BAY, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Towing a 185-ton barge 230 miles
across Arctic ice with a huge Skycrane helicopter to try to save
three ice-bound whales is not the sort of job for which you can
practice.
   ``None of us has ever towed anything like this before. Period,''
Chief Warrant Officer Tom Williams said Thursday. ``But we're
confident in flying the helicopter.''
   ``We're kind of learning as we go,'' he said. ``We learned a lot
yesterday. We were a little apprehensive, but we're more relaxed
now.''
   Williams is co-pilot of the primary Alaska Army National Guard
Skycrane helicopter dragging an ice-breaking barge to Point Barrow
in an effort to break open a channel for three whales trapped at a
small breathing hole surrounded by miles of ice. A second Skycrane
also is available.
   The Skycrane, dubbed Isabel by its three-man crew, was designed
for lifting heavy loads, not acting like a tractor. But it tugged
and pulled the barge for four hours across five miles of muck,
shallow water and sand bars Wednesday before darkness stopped the
operation.
   ``We sure got hopeful. We were able to move it pretty well there
for awhile, then it bogged down again,'' Williams said. ``We're
trying to get out of that area to deeper water, basically, where we
think we can travel. When we hit pockets of deeper water we can
travel pretty well.
   ``Once we get into open water, the fellow operating the barge
says we'll be able to make five, up to 20 knots.''
   The $3 million barge was donated by VECO Inc., an oil field
construction and service company. It is 80 feet long, 61 feet wide
and 26 feet tall and rides on an air cushion generated by
diesel-driven fans, like a Hovercraft, allowing it to be towed over
water, ice or solid ground.
   It can carry 100 tons and has a deck large enough to carry at
least three tractor-trailer rigs.
   The helicopter can lift about 25,000 pounds, not enough to lift
the barge but enough to tow it on its air cushion.
   Skycranes are the second-largest helicopters in the U.S.
military inventory. They are second only to HH-53 troop carriers
used by the U.S. Marine Corps, Guard officials said.
   There are probably 60 of the Vietnam-era Skycranes left in
National Guard units across the nation, with four in Alaska, the
aircrew said.
   Williams' aircraft, piloted by Chief Warrant Officer Gary
Quarles, is 18 years old. Its 45-foot rotor blades are powered by
twin engines generating 9,600 horsepower.
   The aircraft's cargo hook is attached to the bow of the barge by
about 700 feet of nylon and steel cable.
   From an altitude of as low as 25 feet, the helicopter pulls the
craft in a steeply nose-down attitude.
   ``We're kind of staring at the ice and hanging in our shoulder
harness,'' Williams said. ``We have to lock our shoulder harnesses.
It's real tiring from our viewpoint.
   ``While one pilot is flying, the other pilot is constantly
calling out power, nose-down attitude and reading the instruments.''
   The Skycrane must refuel about every two hours, Williams said,
and can't tow at night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
