<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ContraAid-Wilderness     10-20 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Aid-Wilderness,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Joins Senate's Warning To Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House joined the Senate on Thursday in
threatening a renewal of military aid to the Nicaraguan rebels
unless the Sandinista government observes the Central America peace
accords.
   The action came as the House, by voice vote, sent to President
Reagan a bill which designates 1.43 million acres of Forest Service
land in Montana as wilderness.
   The measure contains several unrelated, non-binding resolutions,
attached by the Senate, on foreign policy issues. In addition to
the warning about Contra aid, they formally embrace Chile's move
toward democracy and urge American allies to resist Soviet efforts
to acquire millions of U.S. dollars through third countries.
   The Contra amendment supports unspecified ``continuing efforts
to strengthen the internal democratic opposition and the
independent media of Nicaragua.''
   It also calls for ``maintaining the Nicaraguan freedom fighters
as one of the few `pressure points' on the Sandinistas by providing
the resistance urgently needed humanitarian assistance.''
   White House officials and GOP lawmakers have said prospects are
nil for obtaining a $16.5 million cache of weapons for the rebels
in the waning days of the 100th Congress.
   The dwindling Contra forces are subsisting on $27 million in
food, clothing and medical supplies approved by Congress last
month. They have received no weaponry from the United States since
lethal aid was halted in February.
   Though Congress has been strongly opposed to new military aid,
the bill says a Sandinista failure to comply with Central American
peace accords ``will inevitably cause the Congress to approve
additional military assistance for the Nicaraguan resistance.''
   The wilderness bill affects more than 6 million acres of Montana
and is the result of a compromise worked out among competing
interests, including conservationists and the timber and lumber
industries.
   The bill designates about 1.43 million acres of Forest Service
land as wilderness, 360,000 acres as special management areas, and
another 20,000 acres as federal study areas. It also releases for
non-wilderness uses more than 10 million acres in Montana's 10
national forests.
</TEXT>
