<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lithuania     10-20 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lithuania,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Chief Replaced in Lithuania After Less Than One Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party chief of Lithuania was
replaced Thursday, Tass reported, less than a year after he took
office and on the eve of a Lithuanian nationalist group's
conference.
   Ringaudas Songaila, a 58-year-old agricultural expert, retired
and Lithuanian party leaders chose Algirdas Brazauskas to replace
him, the official news agency said.
   Lithuania became the second Baltic republic to get a new leader
just before the convening of a local nationalist group. The changes
appear to signal the Kremlin's intention to put more reform-minded
officials in charge of the region.
   Brazauskas, 56, an engineer, is known in Lithuania as a
``strategist of the new,'' Tass said. It said Brazauskas ``has
proved to be a sincere advocate of change.''
   Songaila became the party head in December. Within a few months,
he had to deal with a burgeoning nationalist movement in the
republic of 3.6 million people.
   Nationalists on June 3 founded the Lithuanian Restructuring
Movement, and the group is to hold a conference Saturday and Sunday
in the Lithuanian capital, Vilnius.
   Activist Vytautas Bogusis, invited to the conference as a guest
of honor, said in a telephone interview Thursday that Songaila
never achieved much popularity. He stayed largely out of the public
eye and did not address rallies of the Restructuring Movement.
   Party chiefs in the Baltic republics of Estonia and Latvia have
spoken to nationalist groups there.
   ``He (Songaila) sits in the catacombs and has a Stalinist
conservative position. There has been no perestroika from him,''
said Bogusis, referring to Mikhail S. Gorbachev's economic and
political reform program.
   Bogusis, a member of a more radical group called the Lithuanian
Freedom League, said Songaila's reputation worsened after police
beat and kicked two dozen people and arrested at least 100 others
in nationalist protests last month.
   Bogusis said many Lithuanians blamed Songaila for the brutal
treatment of the demonstrators, who were protesting Soviet control
over the republic.
   Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia were independent countries from
shortly after the 1917 Bolshevik revolution until the Soviet Union
absorbed them in 1940 under a pact signed with Nazi Germany.
   On Oct. 4, the Latvian Communist Party's policy-making Central
Committee named the republic's president, Jan Vagris, as its first
secretary. He succeeded Boris Pugo, who was transferred to a job in
Moscow.
   The Latvian People's Front met Oct. 8-9, and adopted a program
endorsing radical nationalist demands for the republic to have more
autonomy in its economic, political and cultural affairs.
   Gorbachev's reformist Kremlin is allowing the Baltic republics a
measure of independence.
   At the urging of the nationalist groups, all three republics'
governments have adopted or are considering laws to legalize
display of the flags that flew when the areas were independent; to
make the dominant nationalities' languages official; and to free
local culture, businesses and industry from the control of central
ministries in Moscow.
</TEXT>
