<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Israel-Lebanon     10-20 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel-Lebanon,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Calls For Restraint In Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Thursday responded to
the latest outbreak of violence on Lebanon's border with an appeal
for security and stability _ and without directly calling on Israel
to forego revenge for the slaying of seven of its soldiers.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, a Lebanese militia, claimed
responsibility for the suicide bombing that caused the deaths. The
pro-Iranian group has been identified by counterterrorism experts
at the State Department as holding all nine American and six other
foreign hostages.
   Israeli leaders promised retaliation against the group. ``We
have to strike at these people of blood and terror everywhere and
at every opportunity,'' Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said in
Jerusalem.
   The soldiers were on the Lebanese side of the border, within a
security zone Israel maintains in order to prevent infiltration and
attacks.
   Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said ``the
United States regrets the tragic loss of life and injuries
sustained in south Lebanon yesterday. We deplore this bloody attack
and the continuing violence in Lebanon that has resulted in the
death and injury of so many people, Israeli and Lebanese alike.''
   Asked if he had any warning for Israel about revenge, the U.S.
official said: ``I don't have any reaction to that threat.''
   Redman said the slaying of the seven Israeli soldiers was ``part
of a continuing occurrence, unfortunately, that we have seen in
Lebanon. And it's exactly the kind of thing that we've been trying
to come to grips with by doing something in that country _ by
helping to do something in that country that can bring more
stability and security for everyone.''
   Asked if the State Department had urged restraint on Israel, the
spokesman said: ``I'm going to leave my reaction where it is. I'm
not going to try to deal with every possible aspect of this
question. It's a continuing problem in the area. We've been through
what we have referred to many times as a cycle of violence.''
   Pressed by reporters again, Redman said ``the whole thrust of
our effort throughout is to bring security and stability, and that
is another way of saying `restraint.' That is a continuing aspect
of what we have tried to do in the region.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz and other U.S. diplomats
have tried to promote Arab-Israeli peace talks as well as a
settlement of Lebanon's civil disorders. Neither problem has been
resolved.
</TEXT>
