<HEAD>REA Head Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold V. Hunter, head of the Rural
Electrification Administration for seven years, has resigned and
plans to return to farming in Oklahoma, Agriculture Secretary
Richard E. Lyng announced Thursday.
   Hunter's resignation will be effective on Oct. 28. He was
appointed to the REA job by President Reagan in 1981. The agency
provides financing for rural electric and telephone systems, and
currently has a loan portfolio of $60 billion.
   The agency job will be taken over by Deputy administrator Jack
Van Mark. Hunter plans to return to Enid, Okla., to join the
family's farming operation, which includes 1,780 acres specializing
in alfalfa, wheat and beef cattle.
