<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     10-20 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four More Political Parties Register</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four more political parties entered the
political arena Thursday, bringing to 28 the number registered with
the hard-line military government.
   State radio said the four are the Patriotic Youths Organization,
Youths Union for Burma's Progress, All Burma Democratic People's
Power Organization and the National Progressive Youths of Burma.
   Analysts said none of the four were politically significant,
with the possible exception of the Progressive Youths, which is led
by pro-communist lawyers who were student leaders.
   The All Burma Democratic People's Power Organizations includes a
number of lesser known film actors, directors and poets.
   Gen. Saw Maung ended weeks of massive anti-government protests
Sept. 18 by calling troops into the streets to shoot unarmed
demonstrators. The government says more than 450 people have been
killed in the law-and-order drive.
   But the government has allowed the formation of political
parties to contest a general election to be held sometime in 1989.
   Rangoon Radio also announced a ban on making, selling and using
firecrackers in the capital and other towns. During the annual
Buddhist Festival of Lights, which will be celebrated next week,
children traditionally set off firecrackers and other fireworks.
   Opposition leaders fear that the tight control over virtually
every aspect of life indicates free and fair elections will not be
possible.
   The government has pledged to remain neutral, but it is widely
believed that the power elite will back the National Unity Party,
which under a different name exercised unchallenged control since a
1962 military coup.
   The coup was staged by Gen. Ne Win, who formally retired in
July. But diplomats generally agree that Ne Win is still the real
power.
</TEXT>
