<DOCNO> AP881020-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     10-20 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Touts Police Backing, Accepts Dead Officer's Badge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, raiding turf that his aides say is
slipping away from Michael Dukakis, dramatized his campaign's
anti-crime message Thursday by accepting a police shield from the
father of a slain officer.
   Along with the badge of officer Edward Byrne came the
endorsement of about 30 police organizations, including the
40,000-member Police Benevolent Association of New York.
   ``It's time for America to take back the streets,'' declared the
Republican presidential nomineee in accepting the endorsments. He
called them ``an exclamation point'' for his campaign.
   Bush campaigned in New York and New Jersey and planned a Monday
foray into Connecticut, Maine and Vermont.
   Dukakis' Northeast political base ``is cracking,'' said Bush's
national political director, Rich Bond. ``We want to make his
electoral math impossible for him.''
   Bond said Bush was comfortably ahead in New Jersey and at least
drawing even in heavily Democratic New York.
   Bush was to share the dais later Thursday with Dukakis at the
annual Alfred E. Smith dinner sponsored by the Roman Catholic
Archdiocese of New York, a nonpartisan event that benefits Catholic
charities.
   The vice president accepted the police endorsements at a
Catholic high school in Queens, not far from the site where officer
Byrne was gunned down last February in his car while guarding a
witness in a drug case.
   Matthew Byrne, a retired New York police lieutenant, said he was
giving Bush his son's shield and commendation bar ``because we
believe he and his administration will stand up for us.''
   ``I was a police officer long before I was a grieving father,''
said Byrne, who also said he sided with Bush's advocacy of the
death penalty for those who murder police officers.
   Bush pinned the commendation bar on his lapel, and said Byrne
and the families of other slain police officers were ``not alone in
their mourning.''
   ``These tragic instances stand as a cruel reminder'' that the
war against drugs ``is a shooting war,'' Bush said.
   For the latest police endorsements, the Bush campaign selected
Christ the King High School, in the middle of a row-house lined
heavily blue-collar Democratic neighborhood.
   Once represented in Congresas by 1984 Democratic vice
presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro, the district is heavily
populated with ``Reagan Democrats,'' Democrats who voted Republican
in 1980 and 1984.
   The endorsements ``send a very powerful message,'' said Rep. Guy
Molinari, Bush's New York campaign manager. ``It will be very
helpful to the vice president and detrimental to Michael Dukakis'
position.''
   Bush had previously picked up similar police backings in Boston,
Hartford, Conn., and Patterson, N.J., while Dukakis has also
received a number of law-enforcement endorsements.
   Throughout his campaign, Bush has been seeking to depict Dukakis
as soft on crime, touting his own police endorsements and referring
repeatedly to a former Massachusetts prison program that permitted
some first-degree murderers to be released on weekend furloughs.
   On Thursday, Bush called that program ``disgraceful.''
   Phil Caruso, president of the New York Police Benevolent
Association, called Dukakis' past suppprt for the prison fulough
program ``maniacal'' and referred to the Democratic candidate as
``cut-em-loose Duke.''
   Other police groups endorsing Bush Thursday included the
Metropolitan Police Conference of New York State, the Port
Authority Police Benevolence Association and the Police Conference
of New York.
   Earlier, the vice president told a predominently Polish-American
audience of about 600 in South River, N.J., that he would deal with
the Soviets with a firm hand and suggested that Dukakis would not.
   ``He has a different concept of a strong presidency than I
have,'' Bush said, asserting that Dukakis would not have the
capability of acting quickly when U.S. interests were threatened.
   Despite recent reforms within the Soviet Union, Bush said, ``old
ambitions die hard. ... The leaves may be falling but the trees are
fundamentally the same.''
</TEXT>
