<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Hyperactivity-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a066AP)_NewYorkJetsdefensiveendMarkGastineau
10-20 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hyperactivity-Drugs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0665,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stimulants Given to 750,000 U.S. Children, Study Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf to CORRECT spelling of researcher's name to
``Barkley'' sted ``Barkely'' and location of his office to
Worcester sted Boston. Picks up 17th graf pvs, ``But Safer ....''
For release at 5:30 p.m. EDT. Time set by source.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 750,000 U.S. children are taking
stimulant medications to curb their overactivity or
inattentiveness, but researchers said Thursday it is not known how
many are getting the drugs appropriately.
   ``Medication treatment for hyperactive children in the United
States has emerged from its minor treatment role in the 1960s to
become dominant child mental health intervention in the late
1980s,'' the researchers said.
   ``A national estimate of 750,000 youth receiving (stimulant)
medication in 1987 can be viewed as a conservative one,'' they
wrote in Friday's Journal of the American Medical Association.
   For reasons unclear to scientists, drugs that otherwise are
stimulants act on the central nervous system to calm hyperactive
children, improve their attention spans and concentration and
reduce impulsive, disruptive and aggressive behavior.
   A furor has arisen over giving children stimulants such as
Ritalin, Dexedrine and Cylert. They once were prescribed mainly to
stem hyperactivity, but now also are given to non-hyperactive
children who have trouble paying attention, the researchers said.
   Both uses are appropriate if a youngster has a problem that
meets the strict psychiatric definition of ``hyperactivity'' or
``attention deficit,'' or a combination of the two, the researchers
said.
   ``If present trends continue, over 1 million U.S. children will
be receiving stimulant medication by the early 1990s, with possibly
one-fourth ... receiving the medication for inattentiveness
associated with a learning impairment,'' the researchers said.
   Dr. Daniel J. Safer, lead author of the study and regional
director of child mental health services for the Baltimore County
Health Department, said more research will be needed to determine
how many youngsters nationally are getting the drugs appropriately.
   But previous findings in Baltimore County, where 6 percent of
schoolchildren are given stimulants, left him ``generally
reassured,'' he said in a telephone interview Thursday.
   He said teacher ratings indicated that more than 90 percent of
children studied had clearly improved after taking the drugs, and
three-quarters of them had improved by more than 50 percent.
   ``We can't speak for the country, but in Baltimore Countny, we
feel the medication was generally quite appropriate,'' he said.
   Estimates of the national prevalence of stimulant use were drawn
from drug company estimates of production and school surveys, the
researchers said.
   At least 13 lawsuits in four states and the District of Columbia
have been filed on behalf of parents distressed at the effect of
Ritalin on their children. In one, for example, parents claimed the
drug caused insomnia, depression and loss of appetite in their son,
who was later diagnosed as having a brain injury not treatable with
the drug.
   Defendants in the cases have included pediatricians,
psychiatrists, teachers and school districts.
   A 19-year-old Los Angeles-based group called the Citizens
Commission on Human Rights, a long-standing opponent of psychiatry
and linked to the Church of Scientology, has made the goal of
banning Ritalin an all-out campaign. It has been instrumental in
many of the lawsuits.
   It claims the drug is highly addictive and is being given to 14
million children, putting them in ``a chemical straitjacket'' and
predisposing them to delinquency. The group says teachers and
schools are pressuring parents into giving it to troublesome
children.
   Russell Barkley, director of psychology at the University of
Massachusetts Medical Center in Worcester, has acknowledged that
some children are being medicated unnecessarily by medical
professionals who, among other things, are ``seeing the children
once a year and renewing the prescription by telephone.''
   But Safer characterized the California group as ``a few vocal
people who want to make a name for themselves.''
   ``There is clear agreement among physicians that the medication
is useful and that side effects were usually temporary and minor,''
he said.
</TEXT>
