<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StarkSailor     10-20 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stark Sailor,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sailor Still Not Competent For Trial, Judge Told</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former USS Stark sailor who can
trace some of his mental problems to a missile attack that killed
37 shipmates is unable to help defend himself on murder charges,
psychologists have told a judge.
   Walter Thomas Taylor remains incompetent to stand trial on
charges he killed a woman and her daughter, according to a report
issued Wednesday by psychologists at Florida State Hospital in
Chattahoochee for Circuit Judge R. Hudson Olliff.
   Taylor, 22, is charged with first-degree murder in the August
1987 slayings of Paula Smits and her 3-year-old daughter, Amanda,
of Mayport. If convicted, Taylor could face the death penalty.
   The killings occurred within days of the damaged Stark's return
to Mayport, its home port.
   The psychologists said they trace some of Taylor's problems to
the May 1987 missile attack in the Persian Gulf on the Stark. The
ship was hit by two missiles fired by an Iraqi jet.
   ``Mr. Taylor did report experience of auditory and visual
hallucinations involving seeing the faces of dead shipmates
superimposed on the faces of others,'' the report said.
   Taylor also experiences flashbacks to the Stark explosion when
he sees an explosion or killing on television, the report said.
   But the psychologists also said Taylor understands the charges
against him, as well as the possible penalties and might be
manipulating the system to avoid his trial.
   Olliff scheduled a hearing for next week to discuss the report.
</TEXT>
