<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Brazil     10-20 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Brazil,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Increases Import Duties On Brazilian Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Thursday increased import
duties on selected Brazilian products in retaliation for what he
said is Brazil's failure to protect U.S. pharmaceuticals and fine
chemicals from unauthorized copying.
   The president's proclamation said the new duties and the
products to which they will apply will be published in the Federal
Register.
   An administration official, speaking on condition he not be
identified, said the products would include paper products,
antibiotics, microwave ovens, television cameras and record players.
   The order stems from hearings held by the office of the U.S.
trade representative.
   Reagan said Brazil's failure to provide patent protection
``permits the unauthorized copying of pharmaceutical products and
processes that were invented by U.S. firms.''
   He said he determined that the appropriate response was to
impose increased duties of 100 percent on the selected products.
   He said the increases would remain in effect ``for such time as
is appropriate.''
   The trade representative is authorized to modify or terminate
them.
</TEXT>
