<HEAD>Woman Recants Murder Witness Story</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEENE, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a startling turnabout, a Keene woman has
said she lied when she told police and a grand jury that she saw
her ex-husband, Marlow's former police chief, kill a friend 10
years ago.
   Deborah Wentworth, 36, told state police Wednesday that she made
up the story that she saw Robert Chambers hit Russell Bean with an
hatchet in 1978.
   ``I fantasized it (was) true, that I was there, but I know I
wasn't,'' she told the Keene Sentinel. ``It's a horrible thing to
lie.''
   She said she made up the story because Chambers had abused her
during their nine-year marriage and she wanted revenge.
   Bean's body was found buried in Chambers's front yard in March,
after police responded to tips from Chambers' sister.
   Chambers, who divorced Wentworth and then married Bean's wife
about a year after Bean's disappearance, has denied involvement in
the death.
   A grand jury that heard evidence in May, including Wentworth's
story about having watched Chambers kill Bean, refused to indict
Chambers and a second-degree murder charge was dropped.
   Wentworth has an extensive history of mental problems and is an
outpatient at a mental health clinic in Keene. Police would not
comment on whether they would seek perjury charges against her.
   Prosecutors maintain that Chambers still is their only suspect.
   ``The status of the case remains thekov; and
M. Borisyuk, deputy secretary of the Communist Party committee of
the Chernobyl nuclear power station, site of the world's worst
nuclear accident.
   Americans chosen include U.S. Reps. Tim Penny, D-Minn., and Curt
Weldon, R-Pa.; Robert Bottoms, president of DePauw University; and
Michael Oppenheimer, a scientist with the Environmental Defense
Fund.
   Alexander Kondyakov, of the Committee of Youth Organizations,
said the summit would build on the three summits between Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev and President Reagan.
   ``We're going to send a kind of message from the emerging
leaders of these two countries to our respective governments saying
this kind of process should continue and develop in different
fields,'' Kondyakov said. ``We'd like to have stable and very good,
normal relations between our two countries which are very important
