<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EasternAirlines     10-20 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Airlines,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Flight Attendants Won't Join Effort To Block Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' flight attendants won't join
other unions in trying to block the $365 million sale of the
Northeast shuttle to real estate magnate Donald Trump, an attorney
said in court Thursday.
   Union attorney Arthur Luby said the Transport Workers of America
was attempting to negotiate a contract with Trump for the 300
flight attendants who work on the Boston-to-New York-to-Washington
shuttle, the only profitable operation at Eastern.
   Because of ``the very, very difficult working conditions,'' the
union ``couldn't in good conscience go and do something that forces
them to continue to work for Eastern when they might have a chance
to do something to improve their lot,'' Luby told U.S. District
Judge Barrington D. Parker at a hearing on the proposed deal.
   Two other unions, the International Association of Machinists
and Aerospace Workers, and the Air Line Pilots Association, have
announced plans to seek a preliminary injunction to block the sale.
   The two unions contend that the deal is part of an attempt by
Eastern's parent, Texas Air Corp., to undermine the strength of
organized labor. The company says it needs to sell the shuttle to
get needed cash in order to save Eastern from financial failure.
   The unions have sought to use the mandatory bargaining
provisions of the Railway Labor Act to stop Eastern from laying off
employees and cutting operations by the financially troubled
airline.
   Parker, whose order barring Eastern from laying off more than
3,000 employees was overturned last month by a federal appeals
court, gave the two unions until Nov. 21 to request a preliminary
injunction.
   Although he suggested that the unions might be ``baying at the
moon'' in light of the appeals court ruling on the layoffs, Parker
said he considered the shuttle deal ``a discreet issue and I am
prepared to hear arguments on a discreet issue.''
   The shuttle deal is scheduled to be completed on Dec. 15. Parker
indicated he would hold a hearing in the first two weeks of
December, a schedule that sets the stage for another eleventh-hour
court battle between Eastern and the unions.
</TEXT>
