<1ST_LINE>u p AM-GenderGap 1stLd-Writethru a0730 10-20 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gender Gap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0730,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gender Gap Lessening as Bush Support Grows Among Both Men, Women</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS poll data in graf 3 bgng ``Between May...'' to 41 to
44 percent, sted split 41 to 41; ADDS numbers on male split for
October in graf 4 bgng ``Men meanwhile...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' huge advantage over George
Bush among women has been all but wiped out as the Republican
candidate has gained support among both men and women, a study
indicated Thursday.
   Bush has picked up support from women along with his gains among
men due to a combination of factors, said Ethel Klein, a Columbia
University political science professor who worked on a study for
the Business and Professional Women's Clubs.
   Between May and October the ``gender gap'' between the
preferences of men and women narrowed significantly. Women gave
Dukakis an 18-point lead in a May CBS-New York Times survey, but by
October 8-10, they were favoring Bush at 44 percent to 41 percent
for Dukakis.
   Men meanwhile favored Dukakis by 1 percentage point in May and
Bush by 8 points in the Oct. 8-10 survey, when they were split 41
percent for Dukakis and 49 percent for Bush.
   ``By September, when the general election began in earnest, the
Reublicans took control of the campaign agenda,'' leading to a
general shift in preference toward Bush, Klein said in a written
report.
   She said the Bush campaign was able to attract women by
addressing economic concerns, including health care, work and
family responsibilities and questions of values and ideology at a
time when Dukakis did nothing to lure voters along those lines.
   However, Klein noted, the same message was pulling men to the
Bush corner at the same time.
   ``The gender gap is not going to make a difference in a race in
which all the dynamics are going one way. In this race all the
dynamics are going Republican,'' she told a news conference.
   ``These women are not voting for George Bush because they have
become convinced that Reagan's economic policies worked and
therefore we should stay the course,'' Klein contended in a summary
of the survey. ``Many women who are economically vulnerable are
supporting George Bush because they have no sense of where the
Democrats would lead them.''
   The gender gap that existed at the end of the primary season was
a factor of party affiliation, dislike by women of the Reagan
administration record, economic circumstances and women's greater
uncertainties about the nation's economic future, the study said.
   At that time, Dukakis was mostly unknown and Bush was not well
liked, the study said.
   After the summer nominating conventions, the ``kinder, gentler''
George Bush emerged, in the phrase he used in his acceptance speech
to describe his vision of America.
   ``This new persona revealed a man who played with his
granddaughter in the morning and reviewed the troops after lunch.
Men really liked this George Bush and decided to support him for
president,'' the survey indicated.
   ``Women were less enamored with this George Bush than men,'' but
they did not dislike Bush any more than they had and his negative
ratings among women dropped 6 points between May and September,
going from 34 to 28 percent.
   By September, when character emerged as an issue, male Bush
supporters who strongly liked him and disliked Dukakis accounted
for 31 percent of his support compared to 21 percent among women.
That compared to 9 percent strong support among men and 7 percent
among women in May. The figures grew to 36 percent among men and 28
percent among women in October.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis was strongly liked by 19 percent of the men
and 19 percent of the women in May. That went to 20 percent among
men and 18 percent among women in September, and 22 percent among
both men and women in October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0677 10-20 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Gets Friendly Reception From Campuses Via TV</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Dec. 7 to Sept. 7 in quote in 5th graf, Said Gore</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen went on the
counterattack against Republican critics Thursday with the
backslapping help of Jesse Jackson and other Democratic allies on a
television hookup with college students in 11 states.
   Michael Dukakis' vice presidential running mate took friendly
questions on more than a dozen issues, from gun control to welfare
reform, during the hour-long session. Several of the student
questioners, selected in advance by the Bentsen campaign,
identified themselves as College Democrats.
   At most of the campuses linked by satellite television, the
Texas senator found a partisan backer hosting a rally.
   Jackson, who was at Memphis State University with Sen. Al Gore,
D-Tenn., told students the 1988 campaign was ``not about Dukakis'
lack of passion, but Bush's lack of compassion and Quayle's lack of
understanding.''
   Said Gore: ``You know George Bush thought Sept. 7 was Pearl
Harbor Day. And he thinks the election has already taken place.''
   Bentsen laid out the same positions he has stressed in his stump
speeches.
   On gun control, he said, ``I wouldn't be on the ticket with a
fella who was going to take my shotgun away from me.''
   He said Republicans ``have talked vaguely of a thousand points
of light and a gentler America _ while savaging the electorate with
vicious negative campaigning.''
   As the microphone switched from city to city, Bentsen received
warm welcomes from such Democratic luminaries as former Kentucky
Gov. Martha Layne Collins; Michael Kennedy, son of the late Sen.
Robert F. Kennedy, D-N.Y., and actor Rob Lowe.
   Bentsen's press secretary, Mike McCurry, said the event cost
about $14,000 and that about 3,000 students took part. He said the
satellite feed was made available to TV stations nationwide.
   ``Obviously, we're delighted with the format,'' McCurry said.
``It's a great way to campaign in 11 states simultaneously'' with
local reporters at each site.
   Bentsen's popularity on campuses as caught his campaign staff
somewhat by surprise. Some students in the audience at Stanford
University had camped out Wednesday to hear him speak Thursday.
   ``Lloyd Bentsen is BMOC (big man on campus),'' McCurry said.
   Speaking earlier to workers at a General Electric plant in
Louisville, Ky., Bentsen promised to respond to Republican campaign
charges until Election Day Nov. 8.
   ``I'm going to take myself on an assignment,'' he said. ``Every
time they issue a falsehood ... I'm going to take them on and
straighten that one out.''
   Bentsen said the GOP was lowering the level of the campaign by
distorting such issues as the prisoner furlough program in
Massachusetts, where Dukakis is governor.
   ``We have seen the Republicans running on symbols and twisting
the facts,'' he said.
   Bentsen, a World War II veteran, said he took it ``as a personal
insult to me'' that the Republicans were accusing Dukakis of being
weak on defense.
   ``We're going to tell them that you can't devalue the currency
of our democracy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
