<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-20 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Across The Mississippi Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered across the central third of the nation
Thursday, and some spots got heavy rain.
   A stationary front extended across northern Texas into
southeastern Louisiana with rain falling just north of the front,
and an area of low pressure sliding across the northern Plains
triggered showers over the upper Mississippi Valley.
   The most numerous showers were over Arkansas and into
Mississippi.
   Little Rock Air Force Base got 1.40 inches in the six hours up
to 1 p.m., and Eldorado, Ark., got 1.07 inches.
   Elsewhere, showers and a few thunderstorms developed over
southeastern Texas and northeastern Florida. And a few showers
moved into southern Arizona and southwestern New Mexico.
   Hurricane Joan was east-southeast of Bluefields, Nicaragua, with
winds up to 110 mph.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Hibbing, Minn., to 90 at Harlingen and McAllen, Texas.
Thursday morning's low for the 48 states was 12 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   For Friday, widespread rain was forecast from the Great Lakes
through the Ohio and Tennessee valleys into the middle and southern
Atlantic regions. Cool air following a front across western parts
of the Pacific Northwest will scatter rain along the coast.
   Highs in the 40s were predicted from northeastern Minnesota
through the northern Great Lakes into the northern half of New
England; in the 50s from the upper Mississippi Valley through the
lower Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley into southern New England;
in the 80s across the southern two-thirds of Florida and the
western Gulf of Mexico coast, and from northeastern New Mexico into
the valleys of California; in the low to mid 90s across the desert
Southwest; and in the 60s or 70s across much of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
