<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2041EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NEQuake     10-20 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NE Quake,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northern New Englanders Rattled by Earthquake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderately strong earthquake jarred
residents of parts of Maine and New Hampshire on Thursday, but no
property damage was reported.
   ``It shook the whole house. Pictures on the wall, everything in
it went flopping back and forth,'' said 78-year-old Leo Perron, a
resident of this glacial plains town near the quake's epicenter.
   ``I thought it was a load of lumber falling,'' said Sandy
Endicott, a secretary at P.H. Chadbourne & Co. lumber yard in
Bethel, Maine.
   George Nickerson, a maintenance supervisor at Chadbourne's, said
the temblor ``wiggled the maintenance garage.''
   The Weston Observatory in Weston, Mass., said the quake measured
4.0 on the Richter scale, enough to cause moderate damage. The U.S.
Geological Survey in Menlo Park, Calif., said the temblor measured
3.9 on the Richter scale.
   Walter Anderson, director of the Maine Geological Survey, said
the difference in the two readings could be regarded as
insignificant.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 4.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 3.5.The San Francisco earthquake of 1906,
which occurred before the Richter scale was devised, has been
estimated at 8.3.
   Thursday's quake struck at 9:09 a.m. and was centered five miles
northeast of Berlin, the Weston Observatory said.
   Authorities said rumblings and booms were reported all the way
from central New Hampshire to Yarmouth on the Maine coast, to
Augusta in the south-central part of Maine.
   Police in Berlin received more than 100 telephone calls Thursday
morning after the quake, but no reports of damage.
</TEXT>
