<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-AmericanDues     10-20 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-American Dues,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>America Pays Additional $28.8 Million in Back Dues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   the United States paid an additional $28.8
million toward its back dues Thursday, reducing the regular-budget
arrears to $337.5 million, a U.N. spokesman reported.
   Total U.S. arrears to the United Nations, including peacekeeping
operations and specialized agencies, amount to about $570 million.
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said Gen. Vernon A. Walters,
the U.S. ambassador, delivered the check Thursday. Walters would
not discuss the matter as he left U.N. headquarters.
   The United States has withheld part of its dues in an effort to
force the United Nations to adopt budgetary and administrative
reforms.
   President Reagan announced Sept. 13 that he was satisfied with
progress on the reforms and was approving immediate release of $188
million. That included $44 million for the last fiscal year and
$144 million for the one beginning Oct. 1.
   Two other payments have been made since Reagan's announcement _
$15.2 million in September and $85.6 million Oct. 14.
   That leaves $58.4 million still outstanding of the amount
Washington has promised.
   U.N. officials have said the State Department modified the
Reagan pledge and told Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
some of the money will be frozen until General Assembly adopts an
austerity budget. U.N. sources said the amount was about $59
million.
   The General Assembly's fiscal committee is to take up the budget
in December. A subcommittee recommended the austerity budget, which
also limits emergency spending, last month.
   Fred Eckhard, the U.N. financial spokesman, has said timely
payments by the United States are necessary if the organization is
to pay for new peacekeeping operations in the Persian Gulf and
possible similar missions in South-West Africa, Western Sahara and
Cambodia.
   Reagan has ordered the State Department to work out a plan for
repaying all past dues and assessments. U.N. Undersecretary Joseph
V. Reed has said the State Department told him it would cover three
to five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
