<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Suriname     10-20 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Suriname,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Police Detain Suriname Army Commander</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police beat and briefly detained
Suriname's military strongman, Desi Bouterse, and seven members of
his entourage after mistaking them for common criminals, the
Surinamese Embassy said Thursday.
   However, a newspaper quoted a police officer as saying the
foreign visitors were not beaten.
   Although he stepped down from the presidency after a civilian
took over this year, Bouterse remains Suriname's army commander and
de facto leader. He was in Brazil as head of a trade mission.
   Suriname lodged a formal complaint with the Brazilian
government, embassy official Ronald Samichar said by telephone from
Brasilia, the capital. Suriname, a former Dutch colony on the
northeastern coast of South America, shares its southern border
with Brazil.
   About 20 state policemen stopped Bouterse and seven members of
his mission Wednesday afternoon as the group strolled along a busy
street in downtown Sao Paulo, Samichar said. Some members of the
group were acting as bodyguards and carrying guns.
   Bouterse and the others at first showed diplomatic credentials,
but police apparently didn't understand the Dutch-speaking
Surinamese and took them for common criminals, the embassy official
said. Portuguese is the language of Brazil.
   The police punched and slapped the Surinamese officials,
handcuffed them and took them to a police station, Samichar said.
After they finally communicated who they were, the eight were
released with apologies, he said.
   The Sao Paulo State Secretary of Security, Luiz Antonio Fleury
Filho, said Thursday that police were investigating the incident.
He added that the attitude of police ``is almost an instinctive and
normal reaction when they encounter armed persons.''
   In Brasilia, the Foreign Ministry said it had asked the Justice
Ministry to investigate.
   The O Globo newspaper of Rio de Janeiro quoted a police officer
as denying that Bouterse and the others were beaten.
   ``They were detained because they were heavily armed, causing
police to suspect they were criminals,'' the officer, identified
only as Captain Coutinho, was quoted as saying.
   ``They were handcuffed and taken to the precinct, where they
said they were Surinamese police officers. After contacts with the
embassy, they were released,'' the officer said.
   The Associated Press could not reach Bouterse at the hotel where
he is staying.
   Bouterse frequently visits Brazil, a major trading partner and
creditor of Suriname. O Globo said Bouterse and his delegation were
expected to return as soon as possible to Suriname.
</TEXT>
