<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Grave     10-20 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Grave,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains of Revolt Leader Imry Nagy To Be Buried In Marked Grave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will allow the remains
of Premier Imre Nagy, who was executed and secretly buried after
leading the 1956 uprising, to be reburied in a marked grave, a
Politburo member said.
   ``Whatever the circumstances of the death, someone who has lived
in this country deserved to be buried in a (marked) grave,'' Janos
Berecz in a television interview Wednesday.
   Nagy, Defense Minister Pal Paleter and other leaders of the
popular anti-communist revolt were executed in June 1958 and buried
in anonymous graves.
   Berecz, a member of the Politburo, the Hungarian Communist
Party's supreme body, said no date has been set for the burials,
which he called a ``painful and time-consuming task.''
   ``The remains must be exhumed and an agreement reached with the
families concerned,'' Berecz said, adding that the families would
be free to make their own funeral arrangements.
   In an interview with the Dutch news agency Netherlands Press
Association in September, Berecz proposed a monument to Nagy as a
``gesture of humanity and reconciliation.''
   The government has granted a partial amnesty to some leaders of
the 1956 revolt, but has ruled out rehabilitation for Nagy and his
associates.
   The amnesty covers the revolutionaries sentenced to prison for
crimes against the state or those whose death penalty had been
commuted to imprisonment. But the pardon does not extend to those
convicted of treason or espionage or convicted of murder, robbery
or causing danger to the public, the official MTI news agency said.
   No figures were available on how many of the pardoned are still
alive.
   On Oct. 23, 1956, a popular anti-communist revolution broke out
in Hungary. A new coalition government under Nagy declared the
country neutral and withdrew from the Warsaw Treaty Organization.
But Janos Kadar, one of Nagy's ministers, declared a
counter-government and asked the Soviet Union for military support.
   Soviet forces suppressed the revolution and Nagy and some of his
ministers were abducted and executed. Kadar became premier and
nearly 200,000 Hungarians fled the country.
</TEXT>
