<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Korea 2ndLd-Writethru a0652 10-20 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Korea, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0652,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Sees Possibility of Troop Withdrawals From Korea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 pvs, bgng: ``Gaston ...'' to CORRECT spelling
of Sigur.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Thursday he sees the
possibility that the United States could withdraw troops from South
Korea in the near future, but the State Department's top Far
Eastern specialist said there is ``certainly no intention'' to do
so.
   The president, entering a meeting with South Korean President
Roh Tae-woo, was asked by a reporter if he could ``envision a time
in the near future when the U.S. would be reducing its military
presence.''
   Reagan said, ``That is a possibility, but it would not be one of
us just withdrawing _ it would be one of (being) no longer needed.''
   The United States has long had about 42,000 troops stationed in
South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   Gaston Sigur, assistant secretary of state for East Asian and
Pacific affairs, asked after the meeting about Reagan's remarks,
said the two presidents did not discuss the subject of troop
reduction.
   ``We are not talking about anything taking place at any
particular time,'' Sigur said. ``We have no intention of anything
of that sort.''
   ``We would have to have a firm belief on the part of our country
and the Republic of Korea that the threat from North Korea was
over,'' he said. ``That threat is not over. We have certainly no
intention of changing our policy of maintaining our ground forces
in South Korea.''
   Korean Embassy children and Roh supporters waved flags as Roh
entered Blair House, the presidential guest quarters, before
meeting Reagan. In nearby Lafayette Park, about 50 people staged a
noisy demonstration against Roh's government and the U.S. military
presence in South Korea. The demonstrators' oriental drums,
clashing cymbals and chants of ``Roh Tae-woo, Out, Out, Out. U.S.
Troops, Out, Out, Out,'' were audible as the visiting presidential
party entered the White House.
   Choi Sung-il, chairman of the United Movement for Democracy and
Unification in Korea, said the demonstration was sponsored jointly
by his group and two others, Young Koreans United and the Coalition
of Young Koreans for Reunification of Korea.
   When asked if he detected any indications that the need for the
troops was lessening, Reagan replied, ``I couldn't put my finger on
some definite signs, but I can just say, seeing other areas of the
world that tensions have lessened, if there's a possibility of
that, yes, that should happen.''
   Asked whether he saw a greater prospect of this than when he
took office eight years ago, Reagan said, ``There have been a great
many changes over eight years, and I think it's possible to see
some things that we couldn't foresee then.''
   He said the U.S. role in relations between South and North Korea
``is to be of any help we can.''
   Tensions on the Korean peninsula have been almost constant for
more than 30 years, and Roh seeks accommodation with his country's
communist-ruled neighbor to the North.
   Roh proposed a summit meeting between the two Koreas in a speech
Tuesday at the United Nations General Assembly. He called for both
countries to meet with the United States, the Soviet Union, China
and Japan to lay the groundwork for an era of peace and prosperity
in northeast Asia.
   The State Department welcomed Roh's ``imaginative and
constructive policy of reconciliation and accommodation'' although
it did not endorse any specific proposal.
   On Wednesday, North Korea's deputy foreign minister, Kang Sok
Ju, spoke to the General Assembly and proposed creating a new
nation out of North and South Korea with a shared military command
and a National Assembly with equal representation from both sides.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Wednesday the
administration has no plans to remove North Korea from the list of
countries that U.S. officials say engage in international terrorism.
   He added that ``North Korea's well-established track record of
belligerence and state terror makes a very cautious approach to
this issue necessary.''
   But Redman reaffirmed that the United States is reviewing its
policy toward North Korea following the resumption of talks between
the two Koreas at Panmunjom, and the show of North Korean restraint
during the Seoul Olympics last month.
   There had been concern that North Korea would attempt to disrupt
the Olympics.
   A State Department official who briefed reporters on Tuesday on
condition of anonymity said the administration ``will probably have
an announcement'' on policy changes toward North Korea in a few
days.
   ``We certainly want to be responsive to President Roh's policy
changes and what he wants to do,'' the official said.
</TEXT>
