<HEAD>Government Hospitalizes Woman Who Reported Seeing Virgin Mary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials hospitalized a young woman
Thursday who has been visited by thousands of people since she
claimed early this month to have seen the Virgin Mary.
   ``Due to her health situation, the woman is suffering severe
mental disturbances which are usually accompanied by
hallucinations,'' said Yousef Gharaybeh, head of Amman's public
security department, according to the official Jordan news agency.
   He said nothing about crosses journalists and hundreds of other
witnesses reported seeing on the arms, neck and chest of Lina
Karabashi, 18.
   Gharaybeh said that Mrs. Karabashi was examined by doctors from
King Hussein Medical City, where police took her Thursday morning.
   An investigation ``found that Mr. (Samir) Karabashi was behind
all the false claims'' and he would ``face legal procedures to stop
him from contacting spirits,'' the security chief said.
   Mrs. Karabashi, he declared, ``is a poor, sweet girl who
deserves medical attention.''
   Monsignor Raouf Najar, the senior Roman Catholic official in
this predominantly Moslem nation, expressed anger at how the case
was handled.
   He said a priest was with the woman all day and had not seen her
undergo medical examinations. Hospital sources said a priest was
the only person allowed to visit Mrs. Karabashi.
   While she was in the hospital for a foot operation, crosses
appeared on Mrs. Karabashi's body and she claimed to have seen the
Virgin. She has had 19 operations on the foot, which was crushed in
a childhood accident.
   Thousands of people have gone to her home since she was released
from the King Hussein medical facility two weeks ago. Many brought
rosary beads for her to bless and a few claimed she had cured them
of physical ailments.
   So many people gathered at the Karabashi house that traffic
often was disrupted and police frequently were assigned to crowd
control.
