<HEAD>Brazilian Priest on Trial on Drug Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 77-year-old Brazilian Roman Catholic priest
admitted in court Thursday that he acted as a courier for a
Brazilian ring that smuggled cocaine to Italy and claimed the money
he received went to charity.
   ``Every Brazilian priest has a little business on the side,''
the Rev. Lino Christ told the court as he and three other
Brazilians went on trial on charges of violating Swiss narcotics
laws.
   Conviction could mean up to 20 years in prison.
   A co-defendant told the court regarding the clergyman's charity
claim that the priest had a mistress in Copacabana and spent the
money on her.
   Christ, a priest at the parish of Santa Catarina in Rio de
Janeiro, was arrested last December after Geneva airport customs
officials seized nine kilograms of cocaine (just under 20 pounds)
hidden under a false bottom of his suitcase. The cocaine had a
street value of more than $1,750,000.
   The priest first told investigators someone he did not know gave
him the suitcase to deliver upon arrival but the man forgot to give
him the address.
   Customs officials had become suspicious because his passport had
been stamped frequently at European airports. In court, he admitted
Thursday having made several trips between Rio and Milan, Italy,
via Geneva and Zurich, Switzerland, and Copenhagen, Denmark.
Payment for each trip was $10,000.
   The three co-defendants include a woman architect, 36, her
32-year-old boyfriend, and a 42-year-old woman travel agent who the
prosecution says was among the masterminds of the ring.
</TEXT>
