<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Trademark     10-20 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Trademark,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Sends Revision of Trademark Laws to Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate sent legislation to President
Reagan on Thursday that alters the nation's trademark laws and
makes it easier for companies to sue each other over false
advertising.
   The measure, sent to the White House on a voice vote, would
allow businesses to protect a trademark for three years even if the
product it signifies is not yet for sale. Currently, companies can
only use a trademark if the product is already available to
customers, a requirement that critics say is often ignored by small
firms.
   Some courts have interpreted the existing trademark law to bar
companies from issuing false descriptions of their own products.
The new law makes it illegal for anyone to misrepresent ``his or
hers or another person's goods, services or commercial activities.''
</TEXT>
