<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CopemishCouncil     10-20 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copemish Council,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheels of Village Government Grind to Halt as Council Majority
Quits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Wynott Clapp in 4th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>COPEMISH, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The majority of the village council in
this tiny community has resigned, leaving the board without a
quorum and the hamlet without a way to pay its bills.
   ``It's been dumped in my lap,'' said Elizabeth VanHore, one of
three remaining council members following last week's resignations.
   Four members quit in part because of a family dispute. With no
quorum, the council is now unable to conduct the business of the
village, which is 25 miles southwest of Traverse City.
   But VanHorn said she and remaining Trustees Emmet Moore and
Wynott Clapp will meet soon to appoint a fourth council member who
in turn will join them in selecting a fifth and restoring a quorum.
   ``What we will do, to be fair, is advertise to anybody who wants
to serve on the council that they send in a resume _ to me, I
guess,'' she said. The council should be able to pay its October
bills and resume business as usual by the time of its next
scheduled meeting Nov. 10, VanHorn said.
   The standstill began during the Oct. 13 council meeting, when
Trustee Ted Kline resigned because he was moving to neighboring
Cleon Township. Village President Don Myers and Trustees Vickie
Mathis and Dennis Collins quit for different reasons.
   ``It just comes down to the difficulties we've had on the
council,'' said Myers, reached at his hardware store.
   Things began simmering last year, when state police investigated
allegations of missing village records and $2,000 worth of gasoline
and oil. No one ever was charged.
   In March, Linda Collins defeated incumbent Betty Collins _ her
sister-in-law and Dennis Collins's wife _ for the clerk-treasurer's
job. Myers said the bad blood resulting from that election and the
state police investigation left the council in constant turmoil.
   ``It got quite personal on a lot of this stuff,'' he said. ``I
just didn't want to be part of it any more.''
   What if no one applies for the openings?
   ``Don't say that to me,'' VanHorn said.
</TEXT>
