<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolygamistClan 1stLd-Writethru a0757 10-20 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Clan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0757,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preliminary Hearing Begins For Three Clan Members In Lawman's
Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with testimony from FBI agent
on events leading up to shooting; picks up 8th graf: `FBI Agent ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL ERTELT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents testified Thursday they saw
three polygamist clan members brandishing and at times firing
weapons during a standoff that ended in the fatal shooting of a
state corrections officer.
   Testimony on the opening day of a preliminary hearing for the
three, charged with second degree murder in the officer's death,
centered on the 13-day standoff with police at the group's Marion
farm last January.
   Third Circuit Judge Maurice Jones will decide after hearing
prosecution testimony whether there is sufficient evidence to bind
the three over for trial.
   Much of the testimony Thursday duplicated that given during an
earlier trial in federal court in which the three were convicted of
a variety of charges related to the Jan. 16 bombing of a nearby
Mormon chapel and the ensuing stalemate with 100 officers.
   Clan ringleader Addam Swapp, 27, his brother Jonathan Swapp, 21,
and John Timothy Singer, 22, have pleaded innocent. Lt. Fred House,
a 35-year-old police dog handler, died Jan. 28 during the
siege-ending shootout.
   House was slain as he was ordering two police dogs to subdue the
Swapp brothers as they walked back to the main farmhouse after
milking a goat. Evidence presented during the federal trial
indicated Singer fired the fatal bullet from a .30-caliber carbine.
   The judge overruled objections by defense attorneys that
testimony about events leading up to the shooting was irrelevant
and inflammatory. Assistant U.S. Attorney Creighton Horton said the
questions were relevant because they showed ``continuing armed
resistance'' by the defendants.
   FBI Agent Richard Intellini testified that Addam Swapp
shouldered and pointed his rifle toward officers on Jan. 28 moments
before House was shot.
   Intellini said House stood in the doorway of another home on the
compound and tried in vain to urge a police dog to subdue the Swapp
brothers.
   When the dog barked, Addam Swapp looked over his shoulder twice,
the second time raising his rifle and pointing it toward the
lawmen, Intellini said, adding that Jonathan Swapp started to slip
his rifle off his shoulder.
   Intellini said he then fired through a window, which shattered
and obscured his view. After he fired, he said he heard several
rounds hitting the house and wood splintering. Soon after, he found
House wounded.
   FBI agent Mike Kelly testified he was at a surveillance post in
a nearby home on Jan. 22 when he saw a window open in the Singer
home and a rifle protrude, then heard a gunshot and saw a muzzle
flash in the direction of the surveillance post.
   Under cross-examination, Kelly said the shot also was in the
general direction of a bank of lights set up by law officers to
illuminate the clan's compound.
   Agent Devlyon Barker said that on Jan. 25 he was taking photos
of the compound when Jonathan Swapp pointed a rifle in his
direction. Others testified of similar instances.
   The three defendants and Vickie Singer, 45, mother of John
Timothy Singer and of Addam Swapp's two wives, were convicted in
U.S. District Court in May on charges related to the bombing and
siege. Addam Swapp was sentenced to 15 years in prison, Mrs. Singer
to five years and Jonathan Swapp and John Timothy Singer to 10-year
terms.
   Addam Swapp, who was seriously wounded in the shootout, has said
the bombing was ordered by God as a sign of the impending collapse
of the Mormon Church and all government, and that it would trigger
the return of family patriarch John Singer, slain by police nine
years before for resisting arrest.
   The clan maintained Singer was killed in a church-state
conspiracy and that the family had been harassed for years by
police and neighbors.
</TEXT>
