<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Intellectuals     10-20 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Intellectuals,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Intellectuals Back Call for Free Trade Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catholic intellectuals nationwide are
demanding restoration of the outlawed Solidarity trade union,
loosening of party control on the economy and free access to the
mass media, it was announced Thursday.
   The demands from representatives of 49 Clubs of Catholic
Intelligentsia were listed in anticipation of promised round-table
talks between the opposition and authorities. But a club spokesman
said a ``deep impasse'' with officials was making the talks seem
increasingly remote.
   About 100 representatives of the clubs, one in each of Poland's
49 provinces, adopted the statement at a two-day meeting in the
southwestern city of Wroclaw Oct. 15-16, said Jacek Moskwa,
spokesman for the Warsaw club.
   The clubs, each of which is autonomous, represent about 18,000
lay Catholics nationwide and are considered centers of moderate
opposition to Poland's communist government. Three members of the
Warsaw club declined an invietation from Prime Minister Mieczyslaw
F. Rakowski to join his new government.
   The Warsaw club's president, Andrzej Stelmachowski, is acting as
mediator in setting up the round-table talks promised Aug. 31 by
Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak to Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa.
   But Moskwa said it was uncertain when the talks _ originally
scheduled for Monday _ might start. On Tuesday, the government said
they have been postponed until after Oct. 24.
   ``As of today, everything is in a very deep impasse,'' Moskwa
said.
   The sides disagree in their views of the round-table, with the
opposition insisting on ``a place for important decisions'' while
the government wants ``a discussion forum,'' Moskwa said. ``This is
the basic difference.''
   The statement passed by the club representatives said the talks
``should lead to ... principal changes in the shape of public
life.''
   ``We demand restoration of a legal framework of trade union
pluralism, including foremost the legalization of Solidarity,''
said the first of the statement's nine demands.
   ``Fulfilling this postulate is an essential condition for real
reform of political and economic life.''
   Another demand was for separating ``political authority from
economic authority,'' meaning the communist party would abandon
control of enterprises and party that loyalists in the
``nomenklatura'' would cease to get management jobs automatically.
   The statement also called for:
   _``Unrestrained access'' by democratic social groups, churches
and religious communities to television and radio;
   _Freedom to form political organizations, and economic, social
and cultural associations;
   _A system of parliamentary democracy with separation of powers
between the executive, legislature and judiciary;
   _Legalizing private schools and separating state activities in
education and culture from the ideology of atheism. ``The school
should not spread atheism,'' the statement said;
   _An end to all official forms of political indoctrination of
youth and the right of free and democratic social activity for
young people
   _Lifting of a 1957 law allowing legal abortions;
   _Democratization and self-government in rural life, with equal
treatment for private, cooperative and state farms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
