<HEAD>Former Mayoral Candidate Pleads Guilty to Statutory Rape</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with Boas comment and to
CORRECT sentencing date to Nov. 18, sted 17. Picks up 3rd graf:
`The original ...; SUBS grafs 7-8, `Attorneys for ..., to UPDATE
with sentencing recommendation. Picks up 9th graf pvs, `Boas
had...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger Boas, a failed mayoral candidate who
ran the city under two mayors for a decade, pleaded guilty Thursday
to charges stemming from having sex with teen girls at a brothel.
   Superior Court Judge Timothy Reardon accepted the surprise plea
and set Nov. 18 for sentencing on seven counts of statutory rape.
Twelve other counts were dropped in return for the guilty plea,
which reportedly allows Boas to avoid prison.
   ``I am very sorry for what has happened,'' said Boas at a brief
afternoon news conference at his attorney's office. ``I feel deep
remorse ... I will pay my debt to society. I hope, one day, to
return to that society a forgiven man.''
   The original charges, contained in a secret grand jury
indictment handed up Oct. 3, covered a 2{-year-period from starting
in November 1985, including his final 15 months as San Francisco's
chief administrative office and his 1987 mayoral campaign. He
placed a close third in last year's primary.
   The indictment grew out of a 16-month police probe, during which
five prostitutes testified they had sex with Boas.
   A campaign poster for Boas on Polk Street, a haven for runaways,
was spotted by one of the teen prostitutes and eventually led to
his indictment, according to police reports.
   One of the 17-year-old prostitutes told investigators, who
learned of the brothel about a year before, that she had sex with
Boas some 30 times, adding he called himself ``George'' and liked
to be referred to as ``Daddy.''
   Smith's office recommended a sentence of three years probation,
participation in a 12-month work program; $70,000 in fines or
contributions to programs for wayward and runaway girls; and
continued psychiatric counseling.
   Boas had faced a maximum of three years on each of the felony
counts of statutory rape, although a judge could have ordered the
sentences to be served concurrently.
   A city grand jury handed up the 86-count indictment of Boas and
13 others. Eight of the defendants were alleged customers and the
others were indicted for running the operation.
   Boas, a 67-year-old wealthy car dealer, served as chief
administrator under former mayors George Moscone and Dianne
Feinstein. He resigned in January 1987.
</TEXT>
