<HEAD>Swindall Says He May Call Himself To The Stand In Perjury Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Pat Swindall, acting as his own attorney for
his trial next week on federal perjury charges, told a judge
Thursday during a pre-trial hearing he may put himself on the
witness stand.
   Swindall was indicted Monday on 10 counts of lying to a grand
jury during a money laundering investigation. He is being given an
expedited trial at his own request to seek a verdict before the
Nov. 8 general election in which he faces Democrat Ben Jones.
   Jury selection is to get under way Friday morning in preparation
for the trial.
   The 38-year-old, two-term Republican has said he is defending
himself because no other attorney could prepare for the case in
such a short period of time.
   Swindall told U.S. District Judge Robert L. Vining there ``may
be some awkwardness should I choose to testify'' and said that with
the judge's permission he would enlist the aid of another attorney
to lead his testimony.
   The indictment stems from negotiations Swindall undertook last
year with Atlanta businessman Charles LeChasney to finance a
mortgage loan for his $1.2 million home.
   LeChasney, an acquaintance from Republican circles, introduced
him to Michael Mullaney, an undercover Internal Revenue Service
agent posing as a financier as part of a nationwide
money-laundering investigation.
   Secretly-made government tapes showed Swindall continued
pursuing the loan after being told it might be financed with
laundered drug money.
   He accepted a $150,000 check but returned it uncashed three days
later, saying he was suspicious of LeChasney's business dealings.
   The indictment charges that Swindall lied before the grand jury
in saying there were never any discussions about the possibility of
drug money involvement in the deal.
</TEXT>
