<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Military,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colonel Fired For Arrest, Torture Of Congressional Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army colonel has been dismissed
for ordering the arrest and torture of an opposition congresssional
candidate, military officials announced Thursday.
   ``We profoundly regret the indiscretion,'' said an armed forces
communique announcing that Col. Luis Alonso Carranza had been
dismissed and replaced.
   It said that on Oct. 14, Carranza ordered about 200 soldiers to
arrest Daniel Sarmiento, a farmer and congressional candidate for
the right-wing National Party, at Sarmiento's ranch in Olancho
province near the Nicaraguan border.
   Sarmiento told authorities he was brutally beaten before being
released two days later. He said soldiers also beat several family
members and ranch employees and threatened to kill them.
   Sarmiento said he underwent intense interrogation by Carranza,
who was trying to find out if National Party presidential candidate
Rafael Leonard Callejas was involved in subsversive activities.
   Presidential and congressional elections are scheduled for
November 1989.
   The armed forces said the action against Carranza ``is a new
guarantee that we are disposed to sanction effectively those who
exceed their authority.''
   It said the military would continue its crackdown on the
``subversive cell'' in Olancho province to ``guard national
interests and Honduras' sovereignity.''
