<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Botha     10-20 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Botha,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Threatens More Media Curbs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Irish, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha on
Thursday threatened to add to South Africa's already extensive news
media curbs unless journalists stopped quoting ``the propaganda of
tyrants.''
   Botha, speaking at an election rally, did not elaborate on what
measures he was considering nor did he specify the ``tyrants''
involved, but it was an apparent reference to the outlawed African
National Congress guerrilla group.
   He said if the media did not ``exercise self restraint'' the
government might introduce measures similar to those Britain has
placed on the Irish Republican Army. The British government on
Wednesday banned broadcast interviews with members of the outlawed
IRA and 10 other militant groups in Northern Ireland.
   Under existing media restrictions in South Africa, it is illegal
to broadcast statements by the ANC without government approval. The
state-run South African Broadcasting Corp. refers to the ANC as a
terrorist organization and does not interview its members.
   Botha spoke before a crowd of about 1,000 in Benoni, a town just
east of Johannesburg. Nationwide muncipal elections are set for
Oct. 26, and Botha's governing National Party is widely expected to
lose ground to the pro-apartheid Conservative Party.
   Botha also condemned talks between South African rugby officials
and the ANC which were held over the weekend in Harare, Zimbabwe.
   Danie Craven, the 78-year-old head of the South African Rugby
Board, said he hoped the talks would help end South Africa's
isolation in the sport. South Africa is barred from international
competition because of its apartheid policies of racial segregation.
   Botha said the ANC was trying to appear reasonable ``in order to
stab you in the back with a dagger.''
   ``There are still politically blind moles in the country who
fail to see this,'' Botha said in an apparent reference to Craven.
   The ANC, based in Lusaka, Zambia, wages a bombing and sabotage
campaign in its bid to oust South Africa's white-led government.
</TEXT>
