<HEAD>Man Ordered Held Without Bond in Bush Threat Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of threatening the life of
Vice President George Bush was ordered held without bond Thursday
by a federal magistrate.
   David Allen Russell, 21, is a threat both to himself and others,
Magistrate Stewart Elliott ruled after a hearing in U.S. District
Court.
   Russell, was arrested early Tuesday morning at the home he
shares with his mother, Beatrice, waived his right to a preliminary
hearing and was returned to the Daviess County Detention Center.
   Russell is charged with threatening to take the life of or to
inflict bodily harm on the vice president, and sending a
threatening letter through the U.S. Postal Service following a Bush
rally in Owensboro.
   Secret Service agents testified Russell has confessed to sending
two unsigned letters to President Reagan.
   The first letter was accompanied by three pictures taken of Bush
while he spoke at English Park in Owensboro on Sept. 27.
   ``I could easily have pulled the pistol out and killed him where
he was,'' said the writer, who claimed to have a concealed
.45-caliber pistol at the rally.
   Secret Service agents said Russell has purchased as many as six
guns. Russell has never been employed and has no close friends,
agents said.
   Charges against Russell carry a maximum 25-year jail term and a
fine of up to $6,000.
