<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeaponsCharge     10-20 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weapons Charge,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian National Charged With Illegal Weapons Exportation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian national who works as a city
engineer was charged Thursday with illegally exporting a vital
component of the sophisticated surface-to-air Hawk missile to
Europe.
   Ali Reza Foyuzi Yousefi, 45, of Rock Hill allegedly tried to
ship a cathode assembly to Zurich, Switzerland, in violation of the
Arms Export Control Act, U.S. Attorney Vinton D. Lide said.
   Yousefi appeared Thursday before U.S. Magistrate Charles W.
Gambrell, who scheduled a detention hearing for Monday.
   The government will argue that Yousefi should not be granted
bail, Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph R. McCrorey said. Even if
Yousefi is released on bail, the Immigration and Naturalization
Service will take him into custody, McCrorey said.
   Yousefi is an illegal alien because his work-related visa
expired in August 1986, said an affidavit signed by U.S. Customs
agent Larry Hunter.
   The affidavit said Yousfei, using the name Allen Young,
contacted Varian and Associates Inc., of Palo Alto, Calif., to seek
price quotes and repair information on sub-assemblies of a
high-tech microwave component considered a key part of the Hawk
missile's tracking and firing systems.
   According to the affidavit, ``Young's voice was recognized as
having a Persian or Middle Eastern accent. Williamson believed
Young was attempting to conceal this by simulating or `faking' a
southern accent. Young's request for information on the
sub-assemblies ... was considered by Varian officials to be
inappropriate and unusual.''
   A tip from Varian allowed an undercover agent to set up an
$89,000 deal with Yousefi, and sell him the first of 100 promised
cathode assemblies on Oct. 12, officials said.
   Yousefi went Monday to a Federal Express office at
Charlotte-Douglas International Airport in North Carolina to send a
package to Zurich, the affidavit said. Customs agents seized the
package and found the cathode, handwritten notes and two Polaroid
snapshots of a cathode, the affidavit said.
   Yousefi was arrested at his office in Rock Hill, a city of
35,000 people south of Charlotte and 77 miles north of Columbia.
   McCrorey would not comment on what country authorities thought
the cathodes were headed to. But the affidavit notes that since
1980, the United States ``has prohibited exporation of defense
articles to the countries of Iran and Iraq, in an effort to
maintain a neutral stance in the Iran-Iraq war.''
   Violation of the Arms Export Control Act carries a maximum
prison term of 10 years and a fine of up to $1 million.
   The attorneys who represented Yousefi on Thursday, Tom Roper of
Rock Hill and Jack Swerling of Columbia, did not return calls to
their offices after the hearing.
</TEXT>
