<DOCNO> AP881020-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     10-20 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`The Cocktail Hour,' A Play by A.R. Gurney, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When John, a frustrated, middle-aged playwright,
asks his upper-crust parents for their permission to produce a play
he has written about them, the reaction is swift and severe.
   Dad is furious, accusing his son of ``fouling the nest.'' Mom
says write a book instead. ``It's less public,'' she sniffs.
   John's artistic effort sets in motion ``The Cocktail Hour,'' a
wise, witty and humane comedy by A.R. Gurney that examines the
often myopic relationship between parents and children.
   The play, which opened Thursday at off-Broadway's Promenade
Theater, deals with family perceptions _ how parents view their
children, how children look at their parents and how children see
each other.
   In the case of John, his parents, Bradley and Ann, and his
sister, Nina, their particular views of each other have skewered
their entire lives. John, a stand-in for Gurney, is a bit of a
misanthrope. He's jealous of a younger brother named Jigger, the
darling of both parents. Jigger is talked about but never shows up
for the big family meeting to discuss John's play.
   The family conference is held during the cocktail hour, when
upscale people gather for upscale chatter. That strange tribe known
as WASPs have provided the principal characters of nearly every
Gurney play, having been most successfully delineated in ``The
Dining Room'' and ``The Perfect Party.'' ``The Cocktail Hour''
examines them in detail, exposing their flaws but doing it with an
affection that is almost genial.
   Consider the unhappy daughter, Nina. She feels neglected,
particularly after she learns that the daughter in John's play is
only a supporting role. She says she has spent her whole life in a
supporting role, looking after her parents when what she really
wants to do is go off to Cleveland to train guide dogs for the
blind.
   If Nina feels unappreciated, John is bitter, particularly at his
father, a man he says married for money, never had to work for a
living and got where he did through the right connections of family
and friends.
   Bradley, the patriarch, rails against the loss of values, in
family and in the arts, even though his own father committed
suicide for a reason never revealed in the play.
   It's left to John and his mother to forge a new relationship,
during what is the best scene in the play. In confronting the past,
they discover an unexpected bond.
   The scene is helped immeasureably by Nancy Marchand's portrayal
of the flinty but very proper matriarch. Miss Marchand is a marvel.
Wearing sensible but elegant pumps, a flowered dress and the
requisite pearls, she is a model of efficiency, a woman who will
make do, no matter what.
   Keene Curtis doesn't quite convey the aristocractic starch that
the father should have, but his indignation at his son's public
exposure of the family's faults is real.
   Bruce Davison as the playwright son has the difficult task of
turning what could be a traitorous character into someone who
genuinely is trying to find out about his family. And he succeeds.
Holland Taylor plays the brittle sister with a style and flair for
sarcasm that ooze upper class.
   Jack O'Brien has directed the play with restraint, not pushing
the actors into the laughs but letting the comedy develop from the
situations. Steven Rubin's plush living room set sprawls across the
Promenade's wide stage, and looks appropriately expensive. But then
the whole production is first-class.
   ``The Cocktail Hour'' mixes impeccable style, a low-key charm
and some high-style performances to produce a winning concoction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Cocaine     10-20 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Cocaine,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Haitian Government Hands Over Drug Haul To DEA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haiti handed over to the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration nearly 3,200 pounds of cocaine worth
millions of dollars seized by Haitian authorities since June, a
U.S. Embassy spokeswoman said Thursday.
   Susan Clyde said there was no formal agreement between Haiti and
the United States on disposing of the cocaine.
   ``The Haitian authorities asked the DEA to handle the operation,
I suppose, because of its superior drug-disposal facilities,'' she
said.
   In a statement published Thursday in the newspaper Le Matin,
Col. Georges Valcin, the Port-au-Prince police chief, said the
cocaine was handed over to DEA agents Tuesday and placed on a U.S.
Coast Guard vessel ``to be destroyed far from national territory.''
   Officials said the drugs included 950 pounds of cocaine
confiscated last Saturday aboard the Greek freighter Aphormajegs
off the coast of Haiti. Walter Brown, a DEA agent based in Haiti,
said the cocaine was of high quality and would have been worth $6.5
million on the street.
   The ship's owner and eight crew members were arrested.
   Last week, the United States announced it had granted Haiti
$200,000 to buy drug-detection equipment and intensify its efforts
against trafficking through the Caribbean nation.
   The United States has said Haiti must cooperate in the fight
against illegal drugs as a condition of resuming $70 million in aid
cut off after Haiti's aborted elections in November 1987 in which
gunmen killed at least 34 voters while soldiers stood by and did
nothing.
   On Wednesday, the United States, through the embassy in
Port-au-Prince, praised the new military government of Lt. Gen.
Prosper Avril ``for the seriousness with which the Haitian
government considers the problem of illegal transit of narcotics
through Haiti.''
   Haiti shares the island of Hispaniola with the Dominican
Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
