<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Fashion     10-20 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Fashion,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lacroix Shows Bright, Beautiful Clothes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian Lacroix wowed the fashion crowd Thursday
in his ready-to-wear show for summer with clothes that were bright,
witty and beautiful. After a spate of so-so clothes and shows,
Lacroix's offering was like a shot in the arm for fashion.
   Color right from Lacroix's sunny south was the big news _
marvelous reds, lime, bright blues, yellow in neat boleros or long
gold-buttoned jackets dipped in the back, teamed with white or
beige pants and jumpsuits. Skirts were just above knee level or
quite long.
   Some had predicted that Lacroix could never keep up his creative
pace, but he keeps on showing his talent, this time in less zany
clothes than the little-girl frou-frous that shot him to fame.
Besides lovely linen suits or flared coats over straight pants, he
showed some good wide jumpsuit shorts and longer pants.
   The combinations of acid green, olive, coral, lipstick red,
ruddy brown and lavender were stunning.
   The sunny south was always on his mind in wonderful combinations
of Provencal prints on jersey outfits with long, full skirts, as
well as the tunic knits with Picasso or Miro motifs on them. Sheer
pullovers had Greek vase motifs and heads of bulls _ vaguely
evoking Arles in southern France and its ancient history.
   Some of the bright boleros in pink and green worn with white
pants or full black skirts had handsome, swirly embroidery, looking
like strikingly informal party or cruise wear.
   After a great line of bathing suits _ some with little skirts _
Lacroix showed a whole series of champagne dresses with guipure
lace embroidery or tucks all over.
   He ended with a big line of every kind of fluid black or navy
cocktail dress imaginable. And there was not a pouf in sight by the
man who started them, unless one considers a puffy organza number
worn as a funny grace note to the show.
   Kenzo's offering was sunny too, though more sedate than his
usual show in a circus building. This time he showed in his
Left-bank shop. Just for fun he showed cotton tail-coats with
shorts, but his long and colorful linen suits with cropped trousers
or narrow skirts with a kick pleat in the back were serious fashion.
   He picked on the French Revolution bicentenary coming up to
highlight his show. The striped lean pants, tiered skirts and
revolutionary stocking caps came out in red, white and French blue.
   Besides cute suits with full short skirts, he showed long ivory
suits with jackets opened like a tulip shape over a panel
underneath, he got some costumey inspiration as well. Tiered Gypsy
dresses and zodiac-printed numbers had enough fantasy for any beach
party.
   And the beachcomber could do no better than the tropical leaf
and exotic bird prints on shorts, billowy sheer tops and shortie
beach cover-ups.
   Rei Kawakubo at Comme des Garcons has taken to showing wearable
clothes _ especially if you like full short culottes or bloomers.
With some nice harlequin-diamond or square black and white sheer
tops, the clothes had more symmetry than usual.
   The prettiest numbers were the filmy, shiny and sheer muslins or
organzas billowing in pastel layers of tops, overskirts and pants.
   Yohji Yamamoto showed enough black suits for an undertaker. But
his excellent and easy cut in the pants suits, jumpers and longer
dresses had a certain austere style.
   ``It's very wearable, handsome, and elegant _ my favorite
collection so far,'' said Selma Weiser, owner of Charivari, a store
with several branches in New York.
   Some of the dresses in light crepe with dropped-waist,
ballooning tiered effects with pastel shoulder wraps were
attractive under their Edwardian hats. And the trapeze dresses had
poor-girl chic, though they aren't budget numbers.
   For welcome color, Yamamoto showed saffron and rust
paisley-print full-skirted trench coats and suits with outsized
jackets and wide pants.
   Nino Cerruti's show had plenty of grown-up charm in narrow pants
suits, long or short skirts, and full shorts. A series of pinks and
beiges in silk and linen was based on fluid pyjamas, fitted jackets
with ribbed or welt seaming, a few loose duster jackets.
   The colors were mostly based on sand and navy, with some
remarkable dark silk flower-printed, flowing culottes worn with
tailored short jackets, a dinner suit for summer.
   Cerruti's prettiest summer late-day clothes were the long pants
or short white linen skirts generously edged in wide bands of
eyelet.
   Thierry Mugler is still enamored of too-tight clothes and
vampires. His show was something between a sci-fi TV miniseries and
a trip to Dracula's den. The spacewomen came out in slick jumpsuits
with crescent-shaped tucks all over or in complicated draped
dresses.
   His bright blue or turquoise suits had jeweled vampire-pointed
fronts on the jacket, clinging skirts. Vinyl details all over
included see-through plastic bustier bodices over sequined
iridescent miniskirts for a mermaid effect.
</TEXT>
