<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-ChemicalWeapons     10-20 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Chemical Weapons,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France Hopes Iraq Will Attend Conference on Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France will host a conference to support
the international ban on chemical weapons, and officials hope Iraq
will attend, a French disarmament specialist said Thursday.
   President Reagan last month proposed such a conference.
   Widespread and documented use of chemical weapons by Iraq
against Iran and reports of their use against Iraqi Kurds has
highlighted the issue of poison gas. The United Nations has
condemned Iraq's use of the illegal weapons, which the Baghdad
government has acknowledged.
   Ambassador Pierre Morel, a French envoy to a U.N. disarmament
committee, told reporters that the conference would be Jan. 7-11.
   ``We hope all the signatories to the (1925 Geneva Convention)
banning chemical weapons will attend, and Iraq is a signatory,''
Morel said. One-hundred and ten countries have signed the
convention.
   He also said the nations which had not signed the pact,
numbering about 50, would be welcome.
   Morel said the Paris conference would reinforce discussions in
Geneva aimed at establishing a universal ban on the weapons.
</TEXT>
