<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NIreland     10-20 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NIreland,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Protestant Gunmen Sentenced To Life For Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four young Protestant activists
were sentenced to life in prison at Belfast Crown Court Thursday
for the murders of two Roman Catholics and a fellow Protestant
activist last year.
   The four _ Darren Larmour, 22, Robert Molyneaux, 20, Alfred
Howcroft, 20, and Joseph Morrison, 23 _ are all members of the
paramilitary Ulster Defense Association.
   In passing sentence, Judge James Nicholson said Catholics should
appreciate the determination of the police in combating such crimes
by Protestant extremists.
   Nicholson said the legal Ulster Defense Association, formed in
1971 as an umbrella organization for Protestant vigilante groups,
was comparable to the outlawed, mainly Catholic Irish Republican
Army.
   He said the two Catholics, Edward Campbell and James Meighan,
were killed simply because of their religion and the Ulster Defense
Association man, Thomas Dickson, was killed because he was disliked.
   Had it not been for the determination of the police, the
killings would have gone unsolved, Nicholson said.
   ``But for their (police) efforts Catholics in north Belfast
would be in greater danger than they are now. Many of the relatives
and friends of the deceased must be aware that the police, and only
the police, could solve these murders,'' the judge said.
   Many Catholics in Northern Ireland are wary of the province's
predominantly Protestant police force, the Royal Ulster
Constabulary.
   Larmour pleaded guilty to murdering Campbell and Dickson.
Molyneaux and Howcroft each pleaded guilty to murdering Campbell
and Meighan. Morrison pleaded guilty to murdering Meighan and
Dickson.
   The Ulster Defense Association claims 18,000 members. The Ulster
Freedom Fighters, said to be the Association's military wing, is
outlawed.
   The British government on Wednesday banned television and radio
interviews with the Ulster Defense Association, the Ulster Freedom
Fighters, the IRA and eight other groups from both sides of
Northern Ireland's sectarian divide in a bid to deny guerrillas a
propaganda platform.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Protestant-dominated
Northern Ireland and unite it with the 95-percent Catholic Republic
of Ireland under socialist rule. Protestant militants oppose any
suggestion of uniting the province with Ireland.
</TEXT>
