<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RockThrowing     10-20 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rock Throwing,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Rock Throwers Are `Sick'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOMERVILLE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A volunteer firefighter and a rescue
squad member were charged Thursday with attempted murder for
allegedly throwing cinder blocks on cars from highway overpasses.
   Michael Havekost, 18, of Warren Township, a member of the
Millington Rescue Squad and Passaic First Aid Squad, and David
Domanski, 25, of Passaic Township, a member of the Millington
Volunteer Fire Department, each were charged Thursday with six
counts of attempted murder in Somerset County Superior Court.
   They were held in the Somerville County jail in lieu of $150,000
bail.
   ``They were creating their own incidents to make themselves
heroes,'' Trooper Daniel Cosgrove said. ``They were getting a kick
out it this. It's kind of sick to do it.''
   Cosgrove said witnesses reported that after each block-throwing
incident, a black sports car would appear on the scene to offer aid.
   ``It turns out Mr. Domanski owns a 1988 Pontiac Firebird similar
to the car described by witnesses at these incidents,'' he said.
   The two were charged with incidents along Route 78 on Sept. 19,
24 and 26. Three people were hurt in the incidents.
   Cosgrove said the two were arrested by Passaic police last week
on arson charges and released. During questioning in Passaic, one
of the suspects mentioned the cinder block incidents and state
troopers were called in, he said.
   Cosgrove said it was not immediately clear why they were
released after they were linked to the cinder block-throwing
incident.
</TEXT>
