<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NancyReagan     10-20 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy Reagan,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady Honored For Anti-Drug Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Lady Nancy Reagan, wearing one of her
trademark designer gowns, was honored by service clubs and other
organizations Thursday night for her ``Just Say No'' campaign
against drug abuse.
   Speaking at the conclusion of a testimonial dinner in her honor,
the first lady said, ``I think my work against drug abuse has
provided me with the most fulfilling years of my life.''
   President Reagan accompanied his wife to the dinner, but did not
speak.
   None of the speakers referred to the controversy that has dogged
Mrs. Reagan since it was disclosed this week that she has continued
to borrow designer clothing despite a 1982 promise to discontinue
the practice.
   The first lady's press secretary, Elaine Crispen, said the
glittering sequined gown Mrs. Reagan wore was from Adolfo, one of
her favorite designers. Mrs. Crispen did not say whether Mrs.
Reagan bought the gown or borrowed it.
   The Los Angeles-based designer said earlier this week that he
customarily loans Mrs. Reagan his gowns, rather than selling them
to her.
   Before the testimonial dinner, Mrs. Reagan was presented at a
private reception with the Colombian congressional order of the
Great Extraordinary Cross with Gold Star in recognition of her work
with young people in drug prevention programs.
   The award was presented by Amilcar Lopez Lopez, president of the
Colombian Senate.
   An unannounced speaker at the testimonial dinner was comedian
Bob Hope, who joined in tributes to Mrs. Reagan and added some
political humor.
   Of Vice President George Bush, Hope said, ``In the last debate,
he was so much better than usual that they tested him for
steroids.''
   Of Bush's controversial running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of
Indiana, Hope said, ``I don't think there's anything wrong with
sending a Quayle to Washington; after all, we send enough turkeys.''
   Host organizations for the dinner included Kiwanis, Rotary,
Lions, Optimist, Sertoma and Exchange clubs, joined by more than 30
national young groups, fraternal and social organizations and
agencies dealing with school-age drug and alcohol abuse.
</TEXT>
