<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Japan-SeaRights ADV26   10-20 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Sea Rights, ADV 26,0528</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, Oct. 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japan Shoring Up Two Rocks to Preserve Sea Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So what if two tiny, faraway rocks crumble or sink
into the Pacific? Japan might lose fishing and mining rights to
155,000 square miles of ocean, that's what, so it is spending about
$236 million to shore them up.
   The rocks called North Dew and East Dew, each barely large
enough for a person to sleep on, are Japan's southernmost points
and hold the key to treasure in this age of national
economic-control zones extending 200 miles from shore.
   Since April, about 200 workers using helicopters and
ship-mounted cranes have surrounded them with thousands of
four-pointed steel blocks, like anchors. The blocks form protective
circles 165 feet in diameter on a coral reef about 10 feet below
the surface 1,100 miles south of Tokyo.
   Haruo Aoki of the Construction Ministry's coastal department
said the work has cost 17 billion yen ($134 million) so far and
total is expected to be 30 billion yen. He said the circles will be
filled with concrete, beginning next year.
   At high tide, the rocks extend 3 to 10 feet above sea level. If
the tide should cover them, the reef no longer could be defined as
an island and Japan no longer could claim a 200-mile economic zone
around it.
   That means the nation's southermost point would move about 300
miles north, between the Volcano Islands on the east and the
Yaeyama Islands.
   North Dew and East Dew are about a mile apart on the reef, which
was an island called Parece Vela when it appeared on 17th century
Spanish navigation charts.
   The Japanese call it Okinotorishima (Remote Bird Island) and
official records say it was put under Tokyo's jurisdiction in 1931.
It is recognized as Japanese in the World War II peace treaty.
   Japan declared a 200-mile exclusive economic zone around the
reef in 1977, following the international trend to such areas of
control.
   Both rocks are shaped like mushrooms with thin stems attached to
the submerged reef, which is about three miles square. North Dew is
about 15{ feet in diameter and East Dew just over half that size.
   Agriculture Ministry figures say 2,577 tons of bonito, tuna and
other fish were caught in the 200-mile zone around them in 1985,
the last year for which figures are available. The catch was worth
$7 million at the current rate of exchange.
   No signs of oil have been reported but surveys are continuing to
determine whether mining of cobalt, nickel and other metals would
be feasible on the undersea mountain capped by the reef, said
Motohiko Kato of the International Trade and Industry Ministry's
National Resources and Energy Agency.
   The mountain rises 16,400 to 19,700 feet from the ocean floor.
   No estimate has been made of how much Japan would lose if the
rocks slipped below the surface and the area around Okinotorishima
became international, an Agriculture Ministry official said.
   End Adv for Wed PMs, Oct. 26
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0757EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-AnimatedAIDSFilm ADV27   10-20 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Animated AIDS Film, ADV 27,0675</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thur PMs, Oct. 27, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Canadian Hopes to Reach Children with Animated Film on AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cartoon movies are a universal hit with
youngsters, Peter Dalglish reasoned, so that should be the best way
to teach street kids of the world the perils of AIDS.
   The Canadian youth worker's short animated film ``Survivors'' is
being made on a budget of $500,000 ($415,000 U.S.) by the National
Film Board of Canada, whose award-winning experience with animation
dates back nearly five decades.
   It should be ready for distribution in 20 languages by the time
more than 10,000 health workers and other experts gather in
Montreal next June for the fifth international conference on AIDS,
for which no cure has been found.
   ``We're trying to reach kids in the 30 largest cities of the
developing world,'' Dalglish, 31, said in an interview. ``It's a
film for the front lines. I think we're two or three years ahead of
the game.''
   A preliminary version of the cartoon, without music or full
animation, has been tested on young audiences in the Philippines,
Kenya, Sri Lanka, Brazil and New York.
   ``We saw very strong identification with the characters,''
Dalglish said. ``The story tested extremely well.''
   Dalglish went to Africa after finishing law school and in
Khartoum, Sudan, founded Street Kids International, which forms
bicycle courier services to provide jobs. It now employs 20
children at any given time and is planning expansion to other
cities with capital raised in Canada.
   ``You have to be able to provide an alternative to
prostitution,'' Dalglish said. ``Given a choice, they'll all choose
riding a bicycle over sleeping with someone.''
   In Khartoum, he became increasingly concerned about the
potential for disaster as AIDS becomes a disease concentrated among
the urban poor.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   Canada has reported more than 2,000 AIDS cases and estimates for
1992 run up to 12,000, but the scene of ``Survivors'' is
specifically Third World, depicting children picking pockets or
turning to prostitution.
   No reliable estimates are available of how prevalent AIDS has
become among street children, who may number 40 million throughout
the world, but Dalglish said the prevalence of other sexually
transmitted diseases might make the projections pessimistic.
   He said the idea of an animated film was born in Khartoum when
he borrowed a projector from the U.S. Embassy to show his
youngsters a Tom and Jerry cartoon, and ``for the first time that
anyone could remember we had the complete attention of every kid in
the room.''
   ``Survivors'' is intended for showing to small groups of
children aged 6 to 14 with a youth worker present to lead a
discussion afterward.
   ``It makes it easy for kids to talk about AIDS, about health,
with street workers,'' Dalglish said. ``We could be subtle, while
being reasonably explicit at the same time.''
   He hopes to raise funds for accompanying instruction guides and
comic books.
   Dalglish and the production team went to Mexico and Guatemala so
the animators could get to know their audience and create an
authentic atmosphere, but the setting is intentionally vague in
order to broaden the film's appeal.
   Even New York street kids were intrigued by it, Dalglish said,
but ``Survivors'' is not really intended for those raised on
Saturday morning cartoons.
   The Canadian hopes explicit language in the film and instruction
about the use of condoms will not create barriers to its
distribution.
   ``We are recognizing the reality that exists in the street and
responding to it,'' he said. ``The kids see it as a moral film.''
   End Adv for Thur PMs, Oct. 27
</TEXT>
</DOC>
