<DOCNO> AP881020-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-DeregulationDecade ADV23-1stAdd   10-20 0942</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Deregulation Decade, ADV 23-1st Add,0962</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHN: June l987.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The government sprang into action, though some said it was too
late.
   Congress came close to approving a broad-ranging air traveler's
``bill of rights'' that called for airlines to disclose such things
as on-time performance, lost baggage and passengers bumped. It also
demanded that schedules be made more realistic and called for
restrictions on flights at virtually all major airports to solve
the delay problem, a provision particularly worrisome to the
airline industry.
   While the bill still rests in Congress, it was enough to prompt
the Transportation Department to direct for the first time a year
ago that the airlines disclose monthly consumer information
including their on-time performance.
   The department also called on the air carriers to make their
schedules closer to actual flying time and spread out flights at
the busiest airports during peak travel periods, ending such
absurdities as had been common at Chicago's O'Hare airport: 36
flights scheduled to arrive at precisely 9:15 a.m.
   This year the number of both delays and complaints has been down
dramatically, something industry experts attribute to the fact that
several of the largest airlines _ Continental, Northwest, and TWA _
have overcome early merger problems, and the tougher government
stance.
   In any case, airline deregulation was never intended to be ``a
Nirvana ... (We knew) there would be bumps in the road and
unforseen economic consequences,'' says Philip Bakes, now the
president of Eastern Airlines, but in the l970s a Senate staffer
influential in drawing up the deregulation law and later an
attorney for the Civil Aeronautics Board.
   ``The scorecard clearly says it's been good for the consumer.
But deregulation was never claimed to be a cure-all,'' says Bakes.
   Adds Kahn, ``The principle failures, by far, have been failures
on the part of government ... to fulfill its responsibilities.''
   Nowhere has the critism of the federal government been more
acute _ with the possible exception of its monitoring of safety _
than in its handling of airline mergers.
   ``There has been an almost total hands off approach by
government. You can call it a honeymoon. We went from total
regulation to total deregulation,'' says Edmund Greenslet, a
longtime airline analyst and follower of the industry. ``The
government said, literally, anything you guys want to do you can
do.''
   When the government in l985 approved United Airlines' request to
buy Pan American World Airways' Pacific Division, it unleashed the
avalanche of airline consolidation.
   ``The prime objective of every airline today is to establish
critical mass,'' says Robert Joedicke, an analyst for Shearson
Lehman Sutton.
   And the Transportatin Department, critics say, has done
everything it can to help in that objective. It reviewed 21 mergers
and approved them all.
   Northwest Airlines, which felt threatened by a strong United
pushing into the Pacific, absorbed Republic Airlines; TWA, wishing
to consolidate its hold on St. Louis, bought arch competitor Ozark
Air Lines; Texas Air Corp., the parent of Continental, went on a
buying spree and captured Eastern, People Express and Frontier;
Delta Air Lines, seeking to spread along the West Coast, merged
with Western Airlines; American Airlines, wanting to do likewise,
bought Air California; and USAir fearing it would become a target
itself, bought Pacific Southwest and then Piedmont.
   In the final years of the Civil Aeronautics Board nearly a
decade ago, a proposed merger of Continental and Western airlines
was turned down because of fears that it would create too much
concentration at Denver, recalls Elizabeth Bailey, a former board
member and now a dean at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh.
   Such mergers as TWA-Ozark and Northwest-Republic, both opposed
by the Justice Department, ``would have had a very hard, tough time
getting through our regulatory board,'' she says.
   ``In effect,'' says Oris Dunham, director of the Dallas-Fort
Worth International Airport, ``a private market cartel has begun to
form'' as the largest airlines have staked out their territories.
   In the markets dominated by one or two carriers the airlines
have ``begun jacking up prices'' and use long-term leasing
agreements, advantages of frequent flyer programs and their
airline-owned computer reservation systems to keep out competitors,
adds Dunham, the chairman of the Airport Operators Council
International.
   An analysis by the Boeing Co., says that at 18 ``hub'' airports
where a single airline had 50 percent of the traffic, travelers
flying through the hub on connecting flights pay as much as 30
percent below average fares. But travelers whose trip begins or
ends at the hubs usually pay as much as 40 or 50 percent more in
some cases.
   Mark Cooper, who watches the airline industry for the Consumer
Federation of America, calls it ``price gouging'' and suggests,
``Whatever benefits there are (under deregulation) are getting
awfully thin.''
   ``Deregulation should not mean and cannot mean that airlines can
create monopoly situations and, therefore, do anything they darned
well please,'' says Sen. Danforth, the Missouri Republican who is a
ranking minority members of the Senate Commerce Committee.
   The airlines deny they are doing anything but working with the
cards they have drawn under deregulation. And they suggest the
fares are far from unreasonable.
   ``It is difficult to understand that if the airlines are
overcharging the public, why then are there not impressive profits
being realized,'' says Robert Cozzi, vice president for revenue
management at Trans World Airlines.
   Last year the airlines had operating profits of $2.46 billion,
but largely because of high interest costs related to the purchase
of hundreds of new aircraft, their net profits were only $601
million, a scant profit margin of 1.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 23</NOTE>
