<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment bank advising Shamrock
Holdings Inc. on its hostile bid for Polaroid Corp. advised
dismantling the instant-camera giant, according to testimony in a
Delaware courtroom.
   Stanley Gold, president of the company controlled by Roy E.
Disney, testified Wednesday that no decision has been made on the
proposal from Wertheim Schroeder, Shamrock's investment adviser.
   Gold said Wertheim Schroeder recommended that Shamrock sell off
Polaroid's manufacturing businesses, cut back on research and
development, reduce the administrative staff and settle pending
antitrust litigation with Eastman Kodak Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $123,000 fine does not compensate for thousands
of defective heart pacemakers and corrosion-prone batteries sold by
Cordis Corp., a federal judge said in rejecting the company's plea
bargain.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Marcus pointed Wednesday to a Food
and Drug Administration pre-sentencing report saying Cordis
knowingly continued to distribute the defective equipment between
December 1983 and October 1985.
   Cordis is accused of 23 counts of selling defective pacemakers
between 1980 and 1985. The FDA said the devices, implanted under
the skin to regulate the heartbeat, could stop without warning.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European trade officials sought to put
to rest American fears that the giant consumer market that will be
formed in Western Europe in 1992 will discriminate against U.S. and
other foreign companies.
   Willy De Clercq, the top trade official of the European Economic
Community, said Wednesday, ``1992 will not mean protectionism.''
   De Clercq and other top officials of the 12-nation trading bloc
issued a statement designed to spell out the implications for other
countries of the move to create a single, European-wide market by
the end of 1992.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's milk production has slowed from
earlier expectations but still could rise enough to be at a record
level in 1988, an Agriculture Department report said.
   Part of the slowdown was attributed Wednesday to higher feed
costs resulting from the smaller drought-reduced grain harvests.
   U.S. milk output declined in 1987 to 142.5 billion pounds from a
record 143.4 billion pounds in 1986. This year's production was
forecast last spring to rise 2 percent to 3 percent from 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan marked the anniversary of the global stock
market crash with the ultimate vote of confidence _ the largest
equity issue in the world so far this year.
   The release of new shares in Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
Corp., the world's biggest company, appeared to have started
successfully Wednesday despite the stratospheric price of nearly
$15,000 per share.
   The third of at least four NTT issues planned by the government
totaled 1.5 million shares with a value of $22.5 billion.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Wednesday, yielding to an afternoon round of
selling in a mood of caution as Wall Street marked the first
anniversary of the crash of 1987. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials closed with a 22.58 point loss at 2,137.27.
   The dollar strengthened slightly in U.S. trading after barely
budging abroad. Gold prices were narrowly mixed. A brisk rebound in
oil prices knocked bond prices lower.
   Precious metals were lower; grains, soybeans, livestock and meat
were mixed.
</TEXT>
