<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     10-20 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Market Loses Ground On First Anniversary of Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   America's apartment sector staged a turnaround last month
despite a decline in single-family home building, while the stock
market slumped in last-minute trading as Wall Street recalled the
first anniversary of the crash of 1987.
   The stock market lost most of its gains of a day earlier as the
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials tumbled 22.58 points to close
at 2,137.27
   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department said the building of new
houses and apartments remained steady at an annual rate of 1.45
million units in September.
   Construction of single-family homes slowed 2.3 percent from
August to an annual rate of 1.05 million units, the government
said, but apartment construction soared 13.2 percent. In August,
the number of new apartments built fell 13.0 percent to the lowest
levels since the end of the last recession in 1982.
   Analysts had predicted a slowdown in housing activity this year
as interest rates increased. But the sector has held up somewhat
better than anticipated.
   According to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., 30-year,
fixed-rate mortgages hit a low of 9.84 percent in early spring,
climbed to 10.71 percent in mid-August and by last week eased to
10.33 percent.
   In the first nine months of this year, starts are running 10.5
percent behind the same period of last year, on track for about
1.45 million units by year end. Economists anticipate a further
decline next year.
   Building permits, a good indicator of future housing activity,
fell 4.4 percent in September to an annual rate of 1.40 million
units, after rising 3.1 percent in August.
   Driving Wednesday's stock market late in the day was a rumor
that the Washington Post would publish a story potentially damaging
to the presidential campaign of Vice President George Bush. The
Post denied it. But traders who had made profits in the market's
recent rise were primed to sell, and they did.
   Analysts also attributed last-minute selling to weakness in the
bond market and some selling by professional traders engaged in
computer program strategies. Bond prices were pushed down by a
sharp rise in oil prices.
   In addition, brokers some investors were being cautious in
advance of the government's scheduled report Friday on the consumer
price index for September.
