<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     10-20 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Soar on Eve of OPEC Committee Meetings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose sharply in the session
prior to meetings of two OPEC committees expected to focus on
rampant overproduction by the cartel's members.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, jumped 79 cents Wednesday to close at $15.40 a
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. On Tuesday,
the November contract plunged 60 cents.
   The wide price swings reflected traders' alternating optimism
and pessimism in advance of meetings of the OPEC strategy and
pricing committees to begin today in Madrid, Spain.
   Overproduction by the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries sent the price of oil skidding below the
$12.30-a-barrel mark recently. Hopes of an agreement to rein in
production brought prices back up in the past two weeks.
   Prices surged Wednesday ``on the anticipation of something
positive coming out of this meeting,'' said Jim Colburn, a broker
at E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc.
   Colburn said traders bought heavily Wednesday after the Kuwaiti
oil minister said his country would agree to abide by its OPEC
production quota if the cartel's other members also agreed to
respect their individual ceilings.
   Over the weekend, oil ministers of the six-nation Gulf
Cooperation Council met and proposed an overall OPEC production
ceiling of 18.5 million to 19 million barrels a day. The cartel's
daily output is now estimated at more than 21 million barrels.
   The GCC proposal was expected to be presented to the two OPEC
committees.
   Colburn said oil trading was expected to remain volatile in
coming weeks. OPEC has scheduled a full ministerial meeting on Nov.
21.
   Refined products traded on the Mercantile Exchange also were
sharply higher Wednesday. The November contract for wholesale
unleaded gasoline rose 2.14 cents to settle at 49.06 cents a
gallon, and the November contract for home heating oil picked up
1.56 cents to close at 43.85 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
