<DOCNO> AP881020-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Crash-Anniversary Bjt   10-20 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Anniversary, Bjt,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memories Of '87 Crash Come Flooding Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert O'Toole still remembers the sick feeling
in the pit of his stomach a year ago when the stock market hurtled
out of control.
   ``For an instant it looked like we were going out of business
and I saw 33 years going down the drain,'' recalled the 53-year-old
manager of over-the-counter stock trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.
   O'Toole lined up on the first anniversary of the crash Wednesday
for a special buffet lunch of steak, turkey, ham, salads and
champagne.
   ``This is our answer to the crash,'' he said. ``We're all still
here and we can afford lunch.''
   Skittishness created by the crash lingered in the market on
Wednesday as a political rumor helped drive the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrial stocks down 22.58 to 2,137.27.
   A year earlier, the average fell 508 points and $500 billion of
stock wealth was wiped out.
   The rumor was that the Washington Post would publish a story
potentially damaging to the presidential campaign of Vice President
George Bush. The Post denied it. But traders who had made profits
in the market's recent rise were primed to sell, and they did.
   Reporters from Brazil, France, Italy, Japan and New Jersey nosed
around for stories Wednesday, scholars discussed great panics of
the past, and author Tom Wolfe posed for pictures near the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Once again in the public eye, traders expressed disappointment
at the slowness of business this year but relief that the crash did
not permanently fracture the markets.
   CBS broadcast its morning show from a balcony over the floor of
the New York Stock Exchange. Outside, George Tonelli sold bumper
stickers reading, ``I survived the stock crash of '87. But I used
to drive a Mercedes.''
   Except for a few seconds of boos and cheers at the opening bell,
the NYSE operated as usual, an army of red- and blue-jacketed
workers swarming around clusters of green computer screens.
   Only Tuesday, the Dow Jones average had hit 2,159.85, its
highest point since the 1987 debacle. On Wednesday, the Dow had
been down about 12 points when the Bush rumor struck late in the
afternoon.
   The 1987 crash brought some prominent firms close to collapse as
credit nearly dried up, and those memories came flooding back on
the anniversary.
   ``We went through hell. People were perspiring, wide-eyed. ...
We had to show signs of confidence when we weren't sure what was
going to happen ... We were concerned that guys wouldn't have
strokes or heart attacks,'' recalled Peter DaPuzzo, O'Toole's boss
at Shearson Lehman Hutton.
   People still could not agree what to call what happened on Oct.
19, 1987: ``crash,'' ``market break,'' or _ as David Ruder, the
chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, prefers _ ``a
compressed large downward move in stock prices.''
   Scholars compared the 1987 crash to the Dutch tulip mania of
1634-37 and the South Sea Bubble of 1720, not to mention U.S. stock
market crashes of 1873, 1884, 1893, 1907 and 1929.
   ``These aren't singular phenomena. They do recur and they share
common characteristics,'' said Eugene White of Rutgers University,
who was attending the symposium at New York University's Salomon
Brothers Center.
   ``After the New Deal reforms everyone thought the markets could
be crash-proof. Obviously that's not the case.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Crash-AMEX     10-20 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-AMEX,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Individuals Should Invest For Long Term, Market Head Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Crash-Anniversary, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One year after the October crash, the stock market
remains a dangerous place for small investors seeking quick
profits, says the president of the American Stock Exchange.
   For an individual to ``dart in and out of the market'' in
competition with institutional investors ``is like me trying to
take on Ivan Lendl in tennis,'' said AMEX President Kenneth R.
Leibling.
   Still, Leibling noted Wednesday, stocks historically have been a
better long-term investment than bank accounts, bonds or money
market funds.''
   While individual investors shouldn't ``play'' the market,
Leibling said the stock market remains ``a superior means of
investment if an individual is prepared to invest based on the
fundamentals and particularly on a long-term basis.''
   Leibling, 39, in Boston for an executive symposium sponsored by
General Electric Co., said during a news conference that he thought
the chances of another crash were slight, mainly because the U.S.
economy is strong and ``the market appears to be quite reasonably
valued by historic standards and in relation to corporate profits.''
   But Leibling stressed there is no guarantee it won't happen
again, despite newly approved circuit breakers that will halt
trading temporarily if stock prices take a sudden plunge.
   ``There is a school of thought that says that as the market
moves toward (the circuit breaker), investors may rush to get out
knowing that the market's going to close, and it may even
exacerbate the trend,'' he said.
   ``There is no experience with this in the markets, and I don't
think there is any guarantee that this will be productive,'' he
added.
   The circuit breaker plan was approved Tuesday as a one-year
experiment by the Securities and Exchange Commission and the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission.
   If the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks drops 250
points in a single day, trading on all major U.S. exchanges will
automatically be halted for one hour.
   If there is an additional 150 point plunge, for a total of 400
points in a single day, a second circuit breaker will impose a
two-hour halt.
   Leibling said he does not foresee any major rise or fall in
stock prices in the near future.
   He predicted that if Republican Vice President George Bush wins
the presidential election, ``there will be a continuity that could
have a positive effect'' on the markets.
   If Democrat Michael Dukakis wins, on the other hand, ``there
will be concern about changes,'' but the market's response is
uncertain.
   ``Traditionally it's perceived on Wall Street that Republican
adminsitrations will be better for the market. Whether they really
are or not is another matter. But many times perceptions dictate
reality when it comes to the market,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 0304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MontanaMining     10-20 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Montana Mining,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mining Industry Bright Spot in Slumping Mountain State Economy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOZEMAN, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlook in many areas of Montana's
economy may be bleak, but for the metals mining industry, the
horizon sparkles in gold, platinum and copper hues, experts say.
   ``The future looks real good,'' said Joe Dewey, general manager
of Stillwater Mining Co., the nation's only platinum mine. ``We've
been in a continual expansion mode ... The demand (for platinum)
outstrips the supply.''
   The Stillwater mine, which employs 356 people in south-central
Montana, has asked the state for permission to operate a second
mine. Propelling the need for platinum is the use of the metal in
catalytic converters, which cut fumes emitted from cars. Platinum
also is being used more frequently by the jewelry industry,
financial experts say.
   Metals mining is the only area in the Montana economy with a
bright future, according to a report released recently by the
Federal Home Loan Bank in Seattle.
   Examples are easy to find. The Jardine Joint Venture gold mine
just north of Yellowstone National Park is expected to begin
full-scale operation next spring, and its new mill will be enclosed
by this winter.
   Higher copper prices mean that 322 workers at Montana Resources
Inc. in Butte will get an additional $800 each in profit-sharing
for the quarter ended Sept. 30, said company vice president Ray
Tilman.
   The Golden Sunlight gold mine in Whitehall, which has about 200
employees, may hire 40 more if expansion plans get the green light
from the state Hardrock Mining Bureau, said mine manager Quayle
Lusty.
   And so far four new gold mines have received state permits to
operate this year, compared to five permits issued in 1987 and six
in 1986.
   The Jardine mine plans to move up to 450 tons of rock a day to
get at gold ore. Gold bullion currently is selling at about $415 a
troy ounce.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
