<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Hunts-Minpeco     10-20 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hunts-Minpeco,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Lamar Hunt To Settle Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lamar Hunt has agreed to pay $17 million to Peru's
state-owned mineral company to settle his part of a jury award
against him and two of his brothers, a published report said.
   An attorney representing Minpeco SA told the Dallas Morning News
a hearing has been set today in New York so the proposed agreement
can be reviewed by a federal judge. Thomas Gorman, representing
Minpeco, said Wednesday court approval is required before the
agreement can become final.
   A $134.6 million verdict was rendered in August against Hunt,
his brothers Nelson Bunker Hunt and William Herbert Hunt, and three
other defendants for conspiring to corner the world silver market
nine years ago.
   Tom Whitaker, a spokesman for the Hunt brothers, could not be
reached by telephone by The Associated Press today.
   ``Negotiations have been ongoing for quite some time, and it
would be premature to comment further at this time,'' Whitaker told
the News.
   Minpeco alleged the Hunts, sons of the late oil billionaire H.L.
Hunt, conspired to corner the silver market in late 1979 and early
1980. A federal jury in New York agreed with the company and
awarded it the $134.6 million.
   Gorman said the agreement with Lamar Hunt was reached after
several weeks of negotiations in Washington and New York. He said
plans called for Hunt to pay the settlement by check today.
   Bunker and Herbert Hunt filed for personal bankruptcy in Dallas
late last month. The Chapter 11 filings, which will protect the
Hunts' assets from creditors while they reorganize their finances,
so far have protected them from paying the Minpeco judgment.
   A motion will be filed in bankruptcy court Friday asking the
court to unfreeze the Hunts' assets so Minpeco can pursue
collection efforts against them, Gorman said.
   Bunker Hunt, at the time of the bankruptcy filing, said ``the
thought of even a dime going to the government of Peru is
repugnant.''
</TEXT>
