<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Interco     10-20 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interco,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manufacturer Spurns Heightened Takeover Try</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc., citing the opinion of its
financial advisers, today rejected as inadequate a hostile takeover
offer sweetened earlier this week to $74 a share by Cardinal
Acquisition Corp.
   Cardinal, which is controlled by brothers Steven M. and Mitchell
P. Rales of Washington, D.C., increased its offer from $70 a share
on Monday. The latest bid, valued at $2.7 billion, was in the form
of a tender offer that was extended until 11 p.m. Oct. 31.
   The Raleses have been blocked at least temporarily by a federal
appeals court from completing their tender offer pending further
review in Delaware of an Interco legal challenge.
   Interco has alleged that Cardinal failed to divulge that Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc., investment bankers, is a co-bidder in the
takeover. Interco also contends the tender offer is leveraged so
high it violates federal securities laws.
   Also today, as part of a restructuring plan that was announced
last month, Interco declared an additional special dividend of
$30.80 per share. The special dividend consists of $24 per share in
cash, including 12 percent interest from Oct. 13 to the date of
payment, and $6.80 per share, the net of the original issue's
discount, of subordinated discount debentures due in 2003.
   ``With today's declaration, we have now declared $55.80 in
special dividends as part of our restructuring program,'' said
Harvey Saligman, board chairman and chief executive officer. ``We
are committed to the timely realization of value to all
shareholders and are hard at work to meet or improve upon the value
goals we have set for our ongoing restructuring program.''
   Cardinal launched its Interco takeover try in July with a
$64-a-share offer that was raised to $70 a share in August.
   Cardinal said on Monday that its new offer is subject to the
same conditions that were imposed with the original tender offer.
Those include attracting 75 percent of Interco's 36.2 million
shares outstanding and the withdrawal of a ``poison pill''
shareholders rights plan.
   The Rales brothers own 8.7 percent of Interco's stock, which
closed Monday on the New York Stock Exchange at $71.50, up $1.62{.
   Interco, a broadly based manufacturer and retailer of consumer
products, reported sales of $3.3 billion its last fiscal year. The
company's apparel is merchandised under brand names that included
London Fog, John Alexander and LeTigre. Its footware brands include
Florscheim and Converse and its furniture lines include Ethan Allen
and Broyhill.
</TEXT>
