<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Japan-DesignAwards     10-20 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Design Awards,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nissan Sports Car Wins Top Design Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Co.'s newest sports car, a sleek
two-door with an aerodynamically designed exterior, won top honors
in the Japanese Trade Ministry's prestigious ``Good Design'' awards
program Thursday.
   The Nissan Silvia, whose latest model was introduced this
summer, took the Good Design Grand Prize for the most oustanding
design in the annual competition sponsored by the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry.
   MITI cited the smooth exterior proportions and curved interior
surfaces of the Silvia, which sells for about 2 million yen, the
equivalent of $15,600, and has a 1.8-liter engine, as setting a
trend in automobile styling for the coming years.
   In the separate categories division, winners included among
others a keyboard synthesizer by Yamaha, a five-door refrigerator
by Matsushita Electric, a microscope by Nikon and a heart pulse
meter by Nihon Koden.
   Winners in the foreign products division included the U.S.
company Polaroid's mini-portrait camera, mountain climbing boots by
Koflach of Austria, a dishwasher by West Germany's Bosch and a
flexible conveyor belt by Flex-Link of Sweden.
   The welfare division included an electric letter opener and sink
faucet filter, and the small and medium-sized enterprise division
included a lampshade, waste paper baskets and an unusual bicycle
with a curved horizontal bar.
   Awards in the ``long life'' division, to commend long-selling
products in the Japanese market, went to among others a line of
dinnerware, a can opener, hanging files, notebooks, a lace curtain
and a mechanical pencil.
   Of the 3,718 products entered, 1,006 were chosen by the ministry
for recognition. There is no monetary prize with the awards, but
manufacturers are allowed to use the ministry's ``G'' mark in
advertisements.
   The Good Design awards were established by the ministry in 1957
to recognize improvements in design standards and the quality of
life. Last year's Grand Prize winner was a fold-up, portable,
overhead projector designed by Ricoh.
</TEXT>
