<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting disappointment in
the slow pace of export sales despite a spurt of business on
Wednesday.
   The Agriculture Department's rejection this morning of China's
bid for 400,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat disappointed
traders and set the negative tone for early trading, analysts said.
   A number of smaller grain sales to foreign buyers were rumored
this morning but analysts said traders were getting fed up with
rumors.
   Most disappointing has been unsubstantiated talk of Soviet
purchases of U.S. grains and soybeans, said Steve Freed, a grain
analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   ``We're being jacked around by rumors of Russians buying soybean
meal, Russians buying corn, and I think everybody's getting rumored
out,'' he said.
   Analysts said the grain markets probably will remain in the
doldrums until some really significant export business develops _
something like a new long-term grain agreement with the Soviet
Union.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 2{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.25{ a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to { cent higher with December at $2.90\ a bushel; oats
were { cent lower to 1 cent higher with December at $2.58\ a
bushel; soybeans were 3} cents lower to 1 cent higher with November
at $8.05 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .13 cent higher with October at
72.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with October at 81.85 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent
lower to .13 cent higher with October at 39.70 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .02 cent lower to .15 cent higher with
February at 48.35 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Wednesday while pork futures
were mostly lower.
</TEXT>
