<2ND_LINE>PM-Boeing Orders,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Orders Total $520 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three foreign airlines have ordered a total of
five Boeing jets worth about $520 million.
   Qantas, the international airline of Australia, ordered two
747-400s costing an estimated $320 million, Boeing confirmed
Wednesday. Qantas now has eight of the latest 747 model on order,
with options on 17 more.
   Icelandair announced it has ordered two Boeing 757-200 jets
worth $100 million and taken an option on a third.
   Malaysia Airlines announced it ordered one 747-400, valued at
more than $120 million and scheduled for delivery in June 1990.
   Qantas currently has a fleet of 25 747s and eight 767s in
service.
   The two 747s, to be delivered in April and May 1990, will form
part of the airline's re-equipment program, which will nearly
double the airline's fleet over the next four years, Qantas
Chairman J.B. Leslie said.
   The 370-seat aircraft will fly routes to London and Frankfurt,
the airline said.
   The two planes ordered by Icelandair include spare parts and
crew training, and are to be delivered in February and March 1990,
Boeing Commercial Airplanes said. If Icelandair decides to take the
third jet, it would be delivered in 1991.
   Iceland's flag carrier said it plans to use the twinjets on its
routes from Reykjavik to New York City, Orlando, Fla., and various
European cities.
   Boeing has received orders for 370 757s, with 194 delivered so
far.
   Malaysia Airlines earlier ordered two 747-400 Combis, which can
carry a half-load of cargo on the main deck behind the passengers.
The new airplanes are to be used on routes between Malaysia and
Europe, Australia and the United States.
   Boeing has had orders for more than 500 commercial jets worth
$23.9 billion this year, a record for the industry.
</TEXT>
