<2ND_LINE>PM-Haft-Perpetual,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Haft Acquires Minority Interest In Financial Corporation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert H. Haft, who with his father has
attempted takeovers of several major retail companies, has acquired
a minority interest in the Washington, D.C.-based Perpetual
Financial Corp.
   Haft, who purchased 5 percent of Perpetual's stock, said
Thursday, ``I believe the enterprise has a bright future. There's
nothing to the rumor that we've made an offer.''
   But the Washington Post reported that the Hafts, who own the
Landover, Md.-based Dart Corp., might make an offer of $16 a share
bid for Perpetual Financial. The concern is the holding company for
the Perpetual Savings Bank, the largest thrift in the Washington
area.
   Perpetual officials denied there had been a takeover attempt
from the Hafts, and senior vice president Robert A. Barton Jr. said
``I think someone just sits in an office and conjures up all types
of rumors. They're just absurd.''
   But speculation on the takeover rumors helped spark an advance
in Perpetual Financial stock prices on Wednesday. The stock closed
at $11 a share, up $1.25, on volume of nearly 877,000 shares.
   In the past the Hafts have submitted unsuccessful acquisition
bids for retailers such as Kroeger, Safeway Stores, Inc. and
Supermarkets General. They are currently negotiating to purchase
$15 million in stock in Walgreen Co., the nation's largest drug
store chain.
</TEXT>
