<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Amex     10-20 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Amex,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Express Reports Decline In Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. on Thursday reported a 13
percent drop in its third-quarter earnings despite record results
in the divisions that run its credit card and financial services
businesses.
   The company attributed the decline to continued pinched profits
at its bank and brokerage firm, Shearson-Lehman Hutton Holdings
Inc., and to the fact that it restated year-ago earnings to reflect
deferred tax benefits.
   American Express said it netted $282.1 million, or 66 cents a
share, in the three months ended Sept. 30, vs. revised earnings of
$324.1 million, or 74 cents a share in the comparable period last
year.
   Revenue during the period jumped 36 percent, to $5.71 billion
from $4.19 billion.
   For the first nine months of the year, American Express' profit
totaled $828.6 million, or $1.94 a share, on revenue of $16.67
billion. That was 30 percent higher than restated earnings of
$637.4 million, or $1.44 a share, and $12.94 billion in revenue, in
1987.
   American Express said it revised the 1987 results to include $76
million of tax-deferred benefits due to accounting changes in the
quarter and $198 million in the nine-month period.
   ``The dominant story for American Express is the consistent,
outstanding performance of Travel Related Services and IDS
Financial Services, which again posted record quarterly earnings,''
Chairman James D. Robinson III said in a statement.
   ``At the same time we remain confident that Shearson Lehman
Hutton and American Express Bank are well-positioned to rebound as
conditions in their markets improve.''
   At the Travel Related Services division, which runs the credit
card and travelers checks business, quarterly earnings climbed 18
percent to a record $221 million from $188 million. Revenue totaled
$1.9 billion, up 24 percent from last year.
   The company said its credit-card charge volume reached a
third-quarter record $22 billion, up 16 percent from 1987.
Travelers checks sales also rose.
   IDS Financial Services had a 17 percent jump in quarterly
earnings to a record $40 million from $34 million, American Express
said. The company said sales of securities, annuity and investment
certificates led the increase, but sales of mutual funds and life
insurance continued to fall.
   American Express Bank's earnings fell to $43 million in the
third quarter, compared with a $71 million profit last year, mainly
reflecting the fact that last year's profit was restated due to the
accounting changes. The company said earnings also suffered from
its ongoing program to reduce its exposure to troubled Third World
loans.
   American Express had reported Wednesday that Shearson Lehman's
third-quarter profit dropped 85 percent to $8.2 million from $54
million last year. It cited sluggish business following last year's
stock market crash, higher short-term interest rates and lagging
expenses from the purchase of E.F. Hutton Group Inc. a year ago.
</TEXT>
