<DOCNO> AP881020-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Whittle 1stLd-Writethru   10-20 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Whittle, 1st Ld-Writethru,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whittle Taking on Time as Partner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 6 new grafs of announcement. Picks up 9th graf pvs,
Special Reports ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. has tentatively agreed to buy a 50
percent interest in the privately held media concern Whittle
Communications LP, the companies announced today.
   The agreement in principle calls for Time, the magazine giant,
to make an initial payment of $185 million and potential additional
payments that depend on Whittle's growth through 1993, the
companies said in a statement.
   They said New York-based Time also would have options to
increase its ownership.
   Completion of the deal is subject to negotiation of definitive
agreements and any required approvals, the statement said.
   Whittle, based in Knoxville, Tenn., has grown rapidly in recent
years by concentrating on developing media vehicles such as
magazines and sponsored posters that are aimed at reaching targeted
audiences, such as people at school and or in doctor's offices.
   A matchup between Whittle and Time would be somewhat ironic
since Whittle took great delight in recent months in tweaking the
nose of the magazine publishing establishment as it launched a new
magazine, Special Reports.
   Special Reports is a package of six magazines that are designed
specifically for doctor's waiting rooms. The magazines appear
quarterly and each is focused on areas such as Family, Health,
Sports and Personalities.
   But Whittle angered many in the magazine business when it went
after advertisers by telling them that the doctors who took the
magazines into their waiting rooms would stock no more than two
other magazines.
   That provision, along with the right to be the only advertiser
in the magazines in specific product categories, was designed to
help the sponsors cut through the commercial clutter and have their
messages stand out.
   Whittle Chairman Chris Whittle announced last month as the first
editions were being distributed to more than 16,500 doctors'
offices that advertising space was sold out for two years. He said
advertisers had committed to spend $80 million and claimed it was
one of the most successful magazine launches ever.
   Time is involved in publishing 23 magazines either by itself or
through partnerships or joint ventures.
   It is in a joint venture with Dale Lang, for instance, that
publishes the magazines McCall's, Working Woman, Working Mother and
Baby.
   In addition to Special Reports, Whittle offers about 40 other
media properties that advertisers can use to reach consumers.
   It puts up sponsored wallboards that it calls information
centers in places such as high schools or hospitals, publishes
newsletters and offers sampling programs. Whittle has said he is
interested in getting into book publishing and television.
   The privately-held company employs 900 people, recorded revenues
of $105 million in the year that ended in June and expects revenues
of $150 million for the year that ends in June 1989.
   Time, which also has interests in book publishing and cable
television, earned $231 million, or $4 a share, on revenue of $3.3
billion in the nine months ended Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-RJRNabisco 7thLd-Writethru   10-20 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco, 7th Ld-Writethru,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nabisco Management Considering $17 Billion Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE stock price, ADD Shearson
statement, CORRECT analyst's estimate; make editing changes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. announced today that top
managers are considering offering to buy the consumer-products
giant for almost $17 billion, a deal that would be the largest
corporate acquisition ever.
   The announcement of a possible $75-a-share offer for the firm
that manufactures Oreo cookies and Winston cigarettes underscored
the soaring interest in food companies and well-known brand names.
It came just three days after Philip Morris Cos. Inc. offered to
buy processed foods manufacturer Kraft Inc. for $11 billion and two
days after Pillsbury Co. rejected a $5.23 billion bid from the
British firm Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   Wall Street apparently expected a higher offer for RJR Nabisco.
The company's stock surged higher after the news broke, climbing
$19.75 a share to $75.62{ in New York Stock Exchange trading. More
than 5.6 million shares had been traded by early afternoon, making
it the most active stock on the Big Board.
   RJR Nabisco said President F. Ross Johnson and Edward A.
Horrigan Jr., chief executive of the company's tobacco business,
had notified Nabisco that they ``intend to seek to develop, with a
financial partner, a proposal to acquire RJR Nabisco in a leveraged
buyout merger transaction.''
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. later confirmed it was the financial
partner and was providing equity financing and advice to the
management group.
   ``Any proposal, if made, would be reviewed by a special
committee composed of outside directors which has been established
by the board,'' RJR Nabisco said in a statement.
   The group said they estimated they would offer $75 in cash for
each of the company's approximately 225 million common shares
outstanding.
   In a leveraged buyout, the buyer borrows the money to buy the
company, then pay off the debt either through company revenue or
selling off parts of the operation.
   If such a deal were completed, it would be the biggest leveraged
buyout of an American corporation by far. The biggest LBO was the
$6.1 billion buyout of Beatrice Cos. by an investment group led by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. in 1986.
   It also would surpass the biggest corporate acquisition, the
$13.4 billion purchase of Gulf Corp. by Chevron Corp. in 1984.
   One Wall Street analyst, Pavlos Alexandrakis of Argus Research
Corp., said a $75-a-share bid would be low.
   ``Valuing Nabisco, as a food company and discounting the tobacco
operation, I arrive at a value somewhere between $85 and $90,'' he
said.
   RJR Nabisco was formed when the tobacco company R.J. Reynolds
Industries Inc. bought Nabisco Brands Inc., the food and consumer
products giant, for $4.9 billion in 1985.
   The company's products are some of the best-known in the
country, and also include Ritz crackers, Camel and Salem
cigarettes, Del Monte vegetables and Milk-Bone dog biscuits.
   It is currently test-marketing a smokeless cigarette, Premier.
   RJR Nabisco had 1987 profits of $1.18 billion on sales of $15.77
billion. Food products accounted for 59.7 percent of the company's
revenue, while tobacco products brought in 40.3 percent of its
sales.
   Earlier this year, the company announced a reorganization of its
food business, separating its biscuit and grocery foods divisions
into two free-standing operating companies. RJR Nabisco said the
move would make it more responsive to changes in the marketplace.
   In the past few years, the company has sold off divisions that
did not fit with its long-range plans, including Kentucky Fried
Chicken.
   Philip Morris, which like RJR Nabisco has tobacco and food
businesses, offered to buy Kraft for $90 a share or a total of $11
billion. Kraft said it was studying the offer and expected to make
a recommendation to its shareholders by Oct. 31.
   Wall Street analysts said it would be difficult for Kraft to
turn down the Philip Morris bid.
   Pillsbury said Grand Metropolitan's $60-a-share offer was
inadequate, and that it was exploring options in response to the
bid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
