<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1421EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Getty-Texaco 1stLd-Writethru   10-20 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Getty-Texaco, 1st Ld-Writethru,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Merger Stand</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 11 new grafs, ``In an ...'' after final graf pvs with
more information</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court today rebuffed
Attorney General John Van de Kamp's challenge to the $10.1 billion
buyout of Getty Oil Co. by Texaco in 1984, ruling that California
antitrust law cannot be used against mergers.
   Van de Kamp had argued that the merger, then the second largest
in U.S. history, would drive up gasoline prices in California by
tying up Getty's abundant oil supplies and San Joaquin Valley
pipeline, a major source for low-priced independent oil firms.
   Rejected by state courts in attempts to block the merger in
1984, Van de Kamp sought at least to require court orders making
the former Getty supplies available to independents after 1989,
when a Federal Trade Commission order expires.
   It was the first time a California attorney general had ever
tried to use state antitrust law against mergers.
   But the court ruled 4-3 that California's 1907 antitrust law,
the Cartwright Act, which prohibits any ``combination of capital''
that might affect prices, did not apply to mergers.
   The opinion by Chief Justice Malcolm Lucas said the term
``combination of capital'' was intended to apply only to business
dealings between two companies that maintained separate identities,
and not to a purchase of one company by another.
   The California law was modeled after antitrust statutes in
Michigan and Texas that had been interpreted by courts in 1899 and
1904 not to apply to mergers, Lucas said. He said the California
Legislature, presumably aware of those rulings, had amended the law
26 times since 1907 and had never added anti-merger language.
   The ruling does not appear to affect Van de Kamp's separate
challenge to the merger of Lucky and Alpha Beta supermarkets, a
suit that relies on federal law. Van de Kamp is one of several
state attorneys general who have tried to activate state antitrust
enforcement in light of the Reagan administration's reluctance to
challenge mergers.
   In an 89-page dissent, Justice Stanley Mosk said California
antitrust law could be used against mergers, even those allowed by
the federal government.
   The Reagan administration ``has all but ceased enforcing the
federal antitrust laws as they apply to mergers,'' Mosk said,
citing a study that said the Justice Department had contested only
26 out of over 10,000 merger applications between 1981 and 1986.
   ``...Vigorous enforcement of state antitrust laws is plainly
necessary.''
   As state attorney general from 1959 to 1964, Mosk established an
antitrust division in his office and was the first to enforce state
antitrust laws extensively.
   The Texaco-Getty merger was approved by the FTC with conditions
requiring Texaco to make oil available to independent firms through
1989. The federal agency assumed that the independents would be
well-supplied after that with offshore oil.
   But Van de Kamp said in his suit that the protections were
inadequate, arguing that offshore oil supplies were uncertain and
were generally controlled by major refiners that would not supply
independent companies.
   He contended that neither federal antitrust law nor the FTC
order was intended to prohibit states from using their own
antitrust laws to attack anticompetitive effects of a merger in a
state such as California, where half to two-thirds of Getty's
assets were located.
   The majority in today's ruling, consisting of Lucas and Justices
David Eagleson, Edward Panelli and John Arguelles, concluded that
California law does not authorize a state challenge to a merger and
did not discuss whether federal approval of the merger would
prohibit any state intervention.
   Mosk, joined in dissent by Justices Allen Broussard and Marcus
Kaufman, said ``combination of capital'' was a broad term that
applied to mergers as well as anticompetitive agreements between
independent companies.
   That interpretation is consistent with the main goal of
antitrust law, consumer protection, and was accepted by a state
appeals court as early as 1915, leaving the Legislature with no
need to amend the law, Mosk said.
   Mosk also said the FTC order approving the merger did not
prohibit a state from taking additional steps that are consistent
with the goals of promoting competition and protecting consumers.
He said the remedies sought by Van de Kamp, such as separate
management by Texaco of the former Getty property and post-1989
orders guaranteeing oil supplies to independents, did not conflict
with the FTC decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
