<TEXT>
   The stock market turned upward today, rebounding
from Wednesday's drop.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 22.58 points on
Wednesday, rose 14.05 to 2,151.32 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 5 to 3 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 878 up, 488
down and 572 unchanged.
   The market was unsettled Wednesday by rising interest rates and
a rumor that a major newspaper was about to publish a story
potentially hurting the presidential campaign of Vice President
Bush. The rumor was quickly denied, however.
   Analysts said buying was encouraged today by abundant takeover
news and rumors, which create opportunities for quick trading
profits.
   In the newest development on that front, RJR Nabisco soared 20[
to 76 on word that a management group may propose to buy out the
company for about $75 a share.
   That prompted buying of such other tobacco stocks as American
Brands, up 4\ at 58{, and Philip Morris, up 3] at 97]. Philip
Morris is itself in the process of going after Kraft, which traded
today at 90[, down \.
   At the same time, market participants were looking ahead to
Friday's scheduled report from the government on the consumer price
index for September.
   Brokers say any sign of new upward pressure on inflation would
increase expectations of further credit-tightening by the Federal
Reserve.
   American Telephone & Telegraph rose ] to 27\ in active trading.
The company reported third-quarter earnings of 55 cents a share, up
from 47 cents in the comparable period last year.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
1.32 to 157.50. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .99 at 305.47.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 122.38 million shares with two
hours to go.
