<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RefinerySale     10-20 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Refinery Sale,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mobil Agrees To Sell Refinery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobil Oil Corp. announced today that it has
agreed to sell its refinery in Ferndale, Wash., and its interest in
Olympic Pipeline Co. to Sohio Oil Co. for $152.5 million, plus
crude and product inventories.
   Mobil also said is has agreed to exchange about 240 Mobil
stations and four product terminals in Washington, Oregon and
northern California for about 330 Sohio-owned and leased service
stations in Florida, Michigan, and six mid-Atlantic and Northeast
states, plus one product terminal in Tampa, Florida.
   Sohio, a subsidiary of BP America, is a major producer of
Alaskan North Slope crude and owns 50 percent of Trans Alaska
Pipeline. The Ferndale refinery, north of Bellingham, Wash., is a
major processor of North Slope crude.
   Mobil said it is withdrawing from marketing gasoline and diesel
fuel in Washington, Oregon, Nevada and in 48 counties in northern
California. The company will continue to market lubricants and to
honor its aviation-fuel contracts in the region.
   The refinery sale is expected to be completed by year end, and
the exchange in the second quarter of 1989, Mobil said.
</TEXT>
