<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Close Down Sharply; Grains Also Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices collapsed Thursday on the
Chicago Board of Trade and closed at their lowest levels since late
July on a combination of bearish fundamental and technical factors.
   Most grain futures also closed lower.
   Soybeans opened mostly lower in sympathy with the wheat market,
which was pressured by disappointment over the Agriculture
Department's rejection of China's bid for 400,000 metric tons of
U.S. wheat.
   But soybean selling accelerated steadily, fueled first by news
of heavy beneficial rains in a major soybean-growing area of Brazil
and later by bearish technical signals as the price for November
delivery of soybeans broke key support levels at $8 and $7.88 a
bushel.
   ``From there it was Katie bar the door,'' said Joel Karlin,
research analyst with Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   The November contract closed at $7.84 a bushel, the lowest
soybean price on the Board of Trade since July 26.
   Rumors late in the session that the Soviet Union had purchased
200,000 metric tons of soybean meal from Argentina added to the
selling pressure, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 4 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.23{ a bushel; corn was 4}
cents lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.86 a bushel; oats
were 1 cent to 3{ cents lower with December at $2.54} a bushel;
soybeans were 10 cents to 22{ cents lower with November at $7.84 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
