<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1701EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Banks     10-20 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Banks,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank America's Profit Soars, Bank of Bost Has Moderate Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp., the nation's third-largest banking company,
reported Thursday that its third-quarter profit more than tripled
from a year ago, while 13th ranked Bank of Boston Corp. had a 7
percent earnings increase.
   A.W. Clausen, chairman of BankAmerica, credited the San
Francisco company's quarterly profit to growth in net interest
income, reduced operating expenses and low net credit losses.
   Bank of Boston Chief Executive Officer Ira Stephanian said his
company also had higher net interest income as well as venture
capital profits but they largely were offset by higher non-interest
expenses.
   BankAmerica reported third-quarter net income of $190 million,
or 97 cents per share, in the three months ended Sept. 30, compared
to $54 million, or 25 cents per share, last year. For the nine
months net income totaled $461 million, or $2.40 per share, vs. a
$1 billion loss last year, when the company increased its loan-loss
reserves to cover shaky Third World debt.
   Bank of Boston Corp. said it netted $79 million, or $1.14 a
share, in the quarter, compared with earnings of $74 million, or
$1.09 a share, last year. Its nine-month profit was $240 million,
or $3.47 a share, up from $61 million, or 80 cents.
   BankAmerica's $190 million profit represents the once-troubled
banking giant's fifth straight quarterly gain. From the end of 1984
through the end of 1987, BankAmerica lost a total $1.85 billion.
During that span, BankAmerica dropped from being the top bank in
the nation to the No. 3 spot behind Citicorp and Chase Manhattan
Corp.
   BankAmerica said quarterly profit would have been $14 million
higher had it not placed $394 million of its $492 million Argentina
loan portfolio on a non-accrual basis, meaning it would record
interest payments only when received instead of when due.
   Bank of Boston said its nine-month profit from a year ago
reflected a $300 million increase in its Third World loan-loss
reserves. During that period this year the provision totaled $108
million, compared to $395 million last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1903EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Zenith     10-20 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Zenith,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zenith Posts 3rd Quarter Profit; Profitable Year Predicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. said Thursday it
returned to profitability in the third quarter and the company's
chairman predicted the beleaguered firm would show a year-end
pre-tax profit for the first time since 1984.
   For the three-month period ended Oct. 1, Zenith's after-tax
profit totaled $3 million, or 11 cents a share, compared with a net
loss of $25.1 million, or 99 cents a share, in the year-ago period.
   It marked the company's first quarterly profit since the fourth
quarter of 1987 and came as a relief to Zenith officials, who are
battling a takeover bid by dissident shareholders.
   Third-quarter sales climbed 15 percent to $682 million from $592
million.
   ``We are delighted that we have returned to the black, albeit a
small black,'' Jerry K. Pearlman, Zenith's chairman and president
told a news conference following the release of the third-quarter
results.
   The results included a gain of $2.6 million from the sale of
property, including unused factory space, warehouses and vacant
land, Pearlman said.
   For the first nine months, Zenith reported a loss of $8.7
million, or 34 cents a share, compared with a loss of $23.8
million, or 99 cents a share, in the same 1987 period. Revenue for
the nine-month period were $1.85 billion, compared with $1.68
billion in 1987.
   Pearlman said cost-cutting measures had enabled Zenith _ the
only company still manufacturing televisions in the United States _
to lower prices on its televisions, video-cassette recorders and
other consumer electronics to levels competitive with imports.
   He said certain Zenith televisions and less expensive VCRs were
in such high demand that the company had fallen behind in filling
orders.
   While others in the industry have announced their intentions to
raise TV prices, ``we've already implemented selective TV and VCR
price increases that, if they hold, should help fourth-quarter
profitability,'' Pearlman said.
   Zenith is battling its largest shareholder, New York-based
Brookhurst Partners L.P., for control of the company. Last week,
Brookhurst launched a consent solicitation, which is similar to a
proxy vote, seeking shareholder approval for its plan to gain
control of Zenith's board of directors and sell the company.
   Pearlman said the cost of fighting Brookhurst had disrupted
Zenith's own efforts to improve the performance of its consumer
electronics division through some kind of arrangement with other
companies.
   Because of the consent solicitation, Pearlman also tempered his
rosy forecasts for fourth quarter and year-end results with a
warning, required by the Securities and Exchange Commission, that
the predictions were based on his best understanding of the
situation and might not come true in case of an unexpected setback.
   Brookhurst's consent solicitation ends on Dec. 4.
   Zenith's third-quarter sales of computer systems and components
increased 17 percent to $392 million while sales of consumer
electronics, the division that is the source of Zenith's financial
problems, advanced 13 percent to $290 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
