<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1913EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Southeast-Japan     10-20 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Southeast-Japan,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Verity: Trade Deficit ``Cancer'' On Society</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity
said Thursday the U.S. trade deficit is a ``cancer on this
society'' and urged the United States to attack its $57 billion
deficit with Japan by exporting more.
   But he told business leaders from Japan and the governors of
seven Southeastern states that changes in the Japanese distribution
system are also needed to help in the effort.
   Verity spoke to the joint meetings of the Southeast United
States-Japan Association and its Japanese counterpart, the
Japan-Southeast United States Association. The groups work to
foster better business ties between Japan and the Southeast.
   Speaking with reporters later, Verity said ``if we're going to
reduce the trade imbalance, we have to increase exports to Japan.
I'm convinced we can ease that trade imbalance in the next three to
four years.''
   Verity called the deficit ``a cancer on this society'' and
warned ``American producers will not be able to survive as long as
they only depend on the U.S. market.''
   Asked about Democrat Michael Dukakis' prediction that he will
eliminate the trade deficit in four years, Verity said the only way
that could be done is by putting up trade barriers or by a
recession.
   Verity said the American people don't want either and are
willing to see a gradual cut in the trade deficit as exports grow.
   During his speech, Verity noted progress has been made in easing
the trade imbalance with recent agreements that allow American
companies more access to Japanese construction projects and the new
Omnibus Trade Bill.
   He said the measure should not cause any problem for trade
between the two nations.
   ``It will be administered in a very enlightened way and Japan
has nothing to fear from that trade bill,'' he said.
   To ease the trade deficit, he said, steps need to be taken to
change the old Japanese product distribution system _ a system
which, for imports ``often double or triples the price of the
product before it gets to the consumer.''
   Verity, a resident of Beaufort, S.C., said a recent trade
mission to Japan showed that there are markets there for top
quality American goods.
   He said while the United States welcomes Japanese investment
which creates jobs, the United States must export more.
   Meanwhile, the Southeast continues to be a fertile ground for
Japanese investment in this nation.
   As of August, Japanese investment in the seven-state region of
Alabama, Florida, Georgia, North Carolina, South Carolina,
Tennessee and Virginia totaled $5.2 billion.
   There are 478 Japanese-owned countries in the region which have
created a total of 8,085 jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
