<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DowJones-Shaw     10-20 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dow Jones-Shaw,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dow Jones President Retiring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones & Co. said Thursday that its president
and chief operating officer of nine years, Ray Shaw, has decided to
take early retirement next spring for personal reasons.
   The company, which publishes the Wall Street Journal and
operates the Dow Jones News Service, said Chairman Warren H.
Phillips will serve as president after Shaw's retirement March 31.
   Phillips had held both titles prior to Shaw's appointment as
president in 1979.
   Shaw, 54, joined the Journal in 1960, serving as a reporter and
editor before becoming the founding managing editor of AP-Dow
Jones, an international news service operated jointly with The
Associated Press.
   Shaw oversaw the launch of Dow Jones' electronic publishing unit
in the early 1970s and later was responsible for the business
operations of the Journal, Barron's magazine and the news services.
He was named executive vice president of Dow Jones in 1977 and
president and chief operating officer two years later.
   Shaw said his decision to retire was ``totally for personal and
family reasons.''
   ``There were no corporate considerations involved in my
decision,'' he said in a statement.
   Dow Jones said that Shaw's wife and three children have been
living and working in North Carolina for several years and he has
been commuting there on weekends.
   Phillips said Shaw ``has played a major role in setting the
company's course, and has been responsible for many of Dow Jones'
most successful ventures. He would have been in line for even
greater responsibilities and recognition in the future.''
</TEXT>
