<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Townsend's first name in lede.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert M. Haft, who has attempted takeovers of
several major retail companies, and Ronald Townsend, president of a
Gannett-owned television station, were elected to the Board of
Directors of the Washington, D.C.-based Perpetual Financial Corp.
on Thursday.
   The Haft family has acquired nearly 5 percent of stock in
Perpetual, said family spokesman Stanley Rubenstein.
   But Rubenstein denied a report that Haft planned to make a $16 a
share bid to acquire the holding company for the area's largest
thrift.
   ``There was a rumor that somebody was circulating in the
Washington area that the Hafts had made an offer, and that is
absolutely not true,'' Rubenstein said. The rumor sparked a rally
of the company's stock Wednesday.
   Haft, who is president of Crown Books, Trak Auto and Dart Group,
was not available to comment.
   In the past, the Hafts have submitted unsuccessful acquisition
bids for retailers such as Kroeger, Safeway Stores, Inc., and
Supermarkets General. They are currently negotiating to purchase
$15 million in stock in Walgreen Co., the nation's largest drug
store chain.
   Townsend is the president and general manager of WUSA Channel 9,
the Gannett-owned CBS affiliate in Washington.
   Perpetual senior vice president Robert A. Barton Jr. said Haft
and Townsend were elected to the 12-member board Thursday morning
``because of their visibility in the community.'' The new members
will serve for terms of up to three years.
   Perpetual Financial Corp., with assets of $5.6 billion, is the
holding company for Perpetual Savings Bank, F.S.B., the largest
thrift in Virginia, Maryland and the District of Columbia.
