<2ND_LINE>BC-Kodak-Mitsubishi,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak In Snowmaking Product Deal With Mitsubishi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastman Kodak Co. subsidiary that
sells an innovative snowmaking aid announced an agreement Thursday
with Mitsubishi Corp. that gives the Japanese company all rights to
sell the product in Japan.
   The snowmaking aid, called Snomax, is a protein that, when
dissolved in water, allows snowflakes to form in water that's eight
to 10 degrees Fahrenheit warmer than freezing.
   It's in use by more than 150 ski resorts around the country and
in Canada, and was used at the winter Olympic Games in Calgary
earlier this year.
   Snowmax technologies, the Kodak subsidiary, has also started
marketing it in various European countries as well as in Australia.
   Financial terms of the agreement were not disclosed.
   Mitsubishi, through its subsidiary Kashiyama Kyogo Ltd., a
leading manufacturer of snowmaking equipment, will be trying to
sell Snowmax to more than 600 ski resorts in Japan.
   ``Although only slightly more than a hundred ski resorts in that
country currently have artificial snowmaking capability, the
capability, and thus the market, is expanding rapidly,'' said
Edward Robinson, president of Snowmax Technologies.
</TEXT>
