<2ND_LINE>AM-Burlington Northern,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burlington's Board Approves Spin-off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burlington Northern Inc.'s board of directors has
approved the spin-off of its energy and natural resources holdings,
Burlington Resources Inc., to company shareholders, the railroad
holding company announced Thursday.
   New executive officers also were named for both companies.
   Burlington Northern said it would distribute 130 million shares,
or 87 percent of Burlington Resources on Dec. 31 to shareholders of
record on Dec. 16. Each shareholder will receive 1.74 shares of
Burlington Resources for each share they hold of Burlington
Northern.
   About 13 percent, or 20 million shares, of Burlington Resources
common stock was sold in a public offering July 7 at $25.50 a share.
   Burlington Northern announced in June the creation of the new
company, made up of Meridian Oil Co., El Paso Natural Gas Co., Plum
Creek Timber Co., Meridian Minerals Co. and Glacier Park Co., a
real estate concern.
   Burlington Northern's principle company remains Burlington
Northern Railroad, which operates a 23,500-mile rail system in 19
Western states and two Canadian provinces.
   Burlington Northern announced earlier this month that it was
moving its headquarters from Seattle to Fort Worth, Texas.
Burlington Resources will remain based here.
   The company announced that Thomas H. O'Leary, currently a vice
president of both companies, will become president and chief
executive officer of Burlington Resources. Gerald Grinstein,
currently vice chairman of both companies, will become president
and chief executive officer of Burlington Northern. Both
appointments will take effect Jan. 1.
   Richard M. Bressler will continue as chairman of the board of
both companies. He currently is chairman, chief executive officer
and president of both.
</TEXT>
