<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Textron     10-20 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Textron,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textron Earnings Flat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textron Inc. said Thursday a strike at
its Lycoming turbine engine division kept third-quarter operating
income nearly flat, but lower taxes enabled it to post a 14 percent
increase in profit, compared with 1987.
   The company reported net income from continuing operations for
the quarter ended Sept. 30 of $62.8 million, or 72 cents per share,
compared with $55.1 million, or 63 cents per share, in the year-ago
quarter. Revenue was $1.73 billion, up from $1.72 billion in the
same quarter in 1987.
   ``The seven-week strike at our Lycoming turbine engine division,
settled in July, adversely affected results in both the second and
third quarters,'' B.F. Dolan, Textron chairman, president and chief
executive, said in a prepared statement. ``However, we anticipate
that we will achieve our financial targets for the full year.''
   Lycoming headquarters and its main plant are in Stratford, Conn.
   For the first nine months, Textron reported a 17 percent decline
in after-tax profit to $170.4 million from $206.3 million in the
same 1987 period. Revenue was $5.36 billion vs. $5.38 billion in
the year-ago period.
   Textron has subsidiaries in aerospace technology, commercial
products and finance.
</TEXT>
