<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-20 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips In Lackluster Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precede LONDON BC</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped toward the lower end of its
recent trading range in light foreign exchange dealings Thursday.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Analysts said many traders here and overseas were bearish on the
dollar, but few appeared willing to press the currency below its
recent support levels of 1.80 West German marks and 125 Japanese
yen.
   The market has been stuck in a narrow range near those levels in
anticipation of the November elections.
   ``It's as though people want to sell (dollars), but they're not
totally convinced,'' said Stephen Leach, currency analyst for
Chemical Bank.
   Traders said there was a brief attempt to take the dollar higher
near the close of European trading, but the effort dissipated as
activity shifted to New York.
   Among the factors dragging the dollar down in domestic trading
were softer oil prices, which fell amid renewed pessimism about
OPEC's ability to agree on production limits.
   Rumors that Iran would refuse to join other cartel members in
cutting production surfaced at committee meetings of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries under way in Madrid,
Spain.
   In Tokyo, where the trading day begins, the dollar closed at
127.15 yen, up 0.30 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 126.90
yen. In New York, the dollar dipped to 127.10 yen, from 127.385
late Wednesday.
   The dollar rose against the British pound in London, where it
cost $1.7335 to buy one pound, compared with $1.7515 late
Wednesday. But in New York, the pound was quoted at $1.7636 in late
trading, more expensive than $1.75175 Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday, were: 1.80075 West German marks, down from 1.81195;
1.52325 Swiss francs, down from 1.5312; 1.20095 Canadian dollars,
up from 1.19945; 6.15275 French francs, down from 6.1905; and
1,342.00 Italian lire, down from 1,348.00.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8005 West German marks, down from
1.8115; 1.5210 Swiss francs, down from 1.5275; 6.1630 French
francs, down from 6.1710; 2.0320 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0380;
1,341.50 Italian lire, down from 1,347.625; 1.1982 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.19955.
   In gold trading, Republic National Bank quoted bullion at
$410.90 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EDT, down from $411.80 late
Wednesday.
   At the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery fetched $412.20 a troy ounce, up from $411.40 late
Wednesday.
   Elsewhere, gold rose in London to a late bid price of $412 a
troy ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $411.05. In Zurich, gold
was higher, closing at a bid $411.50 compared with $410.00 late
Wednesday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.56 to close at a bid
$414.49.
   Silver bullion for current delivery was quoted at $6.342 a troy
ounce at the Comex, up from $6.337 late Wednesday. Silver bullion
prices were unchanged in London, where the metal was trading at a
late bid price of $6.35 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
