<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Media 1stLd-Writethru   10-20 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Media, 1st Ld-Writethru,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Times' Profit Down 18 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 1-2 to ADD Times Mirror earnings and edit to
conform; picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, Third-quarter revenue ...;
ADDS new grafs 9-13 with Times Mirror earnings; No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Times Co. reported Thursday an 18 percent decline in
third-quarter profit from a year earlier, due largely to lower
advertising volume at its flagship newspaper The New York Times,
while Times Mirror Co.'s profit rose 14 percent.
   The New York-based publishing company said its net income for
the third quarter fell to $26.7 million, or 33 cents a share, from
$32.6 million, or 40 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue declined to $404.1 million from $406.4
million.
   Advertising linage at The Times was down 8 percent from the
third quarter of 1987, the company said. It also blamed the profit
decline on costs stemming from The Times's expanded national
editions introduced in San Francisco and Los Angeles.
   In addition, higher newsprint prices and costs related to a new
weekly television magazine at The Times also trimmed profit, the
company said.
   Despite the downward trend, Chairman Arthur Ochs Sulzberger
said, the company still expects the year as a whole to show
improvement over 1987.
   In the first nine months of the year, net income slipped to
$117.2 million, or $1.44 a share, from $117.8 million, or $1.44 a
share.
   The decline occurred despite a rise in nine-month revenue, to
$1.3 billion from $1.2 billion.
   Times Mirror, based in Los Angeles, said the 14 percent rise in
its third-quarter profit was due mainly to the sale of timber lands
and the Times Mirror Press.
   The company which publishes the Los Angeles Times, Newsday and
the Baltimore Sun, said it netted $80.9 million, or 62 cents a
share, up from $70.6 million, or 55 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 4.8 percent, to $814.8 million from
$777.5 million.
   The sale of the timber lands and Times Mirror Press boosted
revenues that were declining because of lost advertising dollars,
the company said.
   Strong revenues from the company's professional publishing
businesses and cable television operations also helped offset
declines in newspaper publishing and broadcast TV, Times Mirror
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
