<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-20 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0861</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Matches Record High, Further Gains Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper for spot delivery on New York's Commodity Exchange
matched the exchange's record high price of $1.46 a pound Thursday
and analysts predicted further gains due to tight supplies, strong
demand and a miners strike in Peru.
   On other markets, precious metals retreated; soybean prices
collapsed; grain futures moved lower; energy futures were mixed;
livestock and meat were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   ``Copper is just galloping along,'' said Bette Raptopoulos,
metals analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   The contract for October delivery of copper on the Comex hit
$1.46 a pound, the record high posted last Dec. 31, fairly late in
Thursday's session following a bout of profit-taking from
Wednesday's sharp gains. Another round of late selling brought the
October price down to a close of $1.4575, up 4.05 cents from
Wednesday.
   Copper for delivery in December rose 2.65 cents to $1.36.
   The general strike in Peru, the world's sixth-largest copper
producer, stretched into a third day Thursday but that has been
only one factor in copper's rise from around $1 a pound on Sept. 1.
   In addition to persistent labor problems in Peru and Chile,
which ranks along with the United States as a leading copper
producer, rail transportation of copper has been a major problem in
Zambia, the No. 4 copper producer. Canada ranks third in copper
production worldwide.
   Thus, supplies of copper have been extremely tight for more than
a year despite increased output by North American producers.
   The lastest figures from the American Bureau of Metal Statistics
show domestic inventories of refined copper at 52,500 short tons on
Aug. 31, more than 35 percent below the Dec. 31 level and nearly 63
percent below the year-ago figure.
   On the demand side, consumption typically rises in the fourth
quarter and this year has been no exception. In fact, experts say
demand was unusually strong last year and remains so this year
because of the strong economies of the major industrialized
countries.
   Speculators have recently joined commercial players in the
copper futures market, and the additional buying has helped to pump
up prices, analysts said.
   ``All in all, it's become a bullish scenario,'' Ms. Raptopoulos
said. ``As long as the Peru strike goes on and the tightness
remains, this market will have to trend higher.''
   Precious metals advanced slightly on the Comex in light trading
as the inflation-sensitive gold market awaited news from an OPEC
committee meeting in Madrid, Spain, to discuss efforts to stabilize
oil prices.
   Gold settled 70 cents to 80 cents higher with December at
$415.40 a troy ounce; silver was 0.5 cent higher across the board
with December at $6.41 a troy ounce.
   Soybean futures prices collapsed to 12-week lows on the Chicago
Board of Trade on a combination of bearish fundamental and
technical factors.
   Most grain futures also closed lower.
   Soybeans opened mostly lower and selling accelerated steadily,
fueled first by news of heavy beneficial rains in a major
soybean-growing area of Brazil and later by bearish technical
signals as the price for November delivery of soybeans broke key
support levels at $8 and $7.88 a bushel, analysts said.
   The November contract closed at $7.84{ a bushel, the lowest
soybean price on the Board of Trade since July 26.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 4 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in December at $4.23{ a bushel; corn was 4{ cents lower to
} cent higher with December at $2.86\ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
3{ cents lower with December at $2.54} a bushel; soybeans were 10{
cents to 22 cents lower with November at $7.84{ a bushel.
   Crude and heating oil futures fell amid profit-taking on the New
York Mercantile Exchange but gasoline futures advanced on
indications of tight supplies.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 80 cents
lower with November at $14.60 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent to
.79 cent lower with November at 43.06 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .04 cent to .36 cent higher with November at 49.35
cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures finished mostly higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange on position-evening ahead of Friday's quarterly USDA
cattle-on-feed report. Pork futures were mixed in cautious trading
ahead of the USDA's monthly cold-storage report, which is also due
out after Friday's close.
   Live cattle settled .10 cent lower to .38 cent higher with
October, which expired Thursday, at 72.70 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .05 cent lower to .17 cent higher with October at 81.85
cents a pound; live hogs were .78 cent lower to .10 cent higher
with October, which expired Thursday, at 39.27 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .28 cent to .77 cent higher with February
at 48.92 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures posted sharp gains on the Chicago Merc. The
contract for December delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500 settled
5.95 points higher at 284.75.
</TEXT>
