<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USXPlant     10-20 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USX Plant,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USX Chairman Says No Good Offers Made For Baytown Plant So Far</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. has not received any realistic offers
for its idled Baytown plant since the steel and oil giant agreed to
wait six months before negotiating a sale to Iraq, the company's
chairman said Wednesday.
   ``We'd love to sell the mill _ at a full price,'' said David M.
Roderick, USX chairman of the board and chief executive officer.
``But I don't know what will happen.''
   USX stirred up controversy this summer after confirming it was
negotiating a deal to dismantle the plant and sell its equipment to
Iraq, which wanted it to build pipes for irrigation and oil
production.
   Opposition to the proposed Iraq sale has been led by U.S. Rep.
Jack Fields, R-Texas, whose district includes Baytown. Fields
claims the sale would cause a loss of U.S. jobs and steelmaking
capacity.
   Roderick told members of the Houston Club Wednesday a letter of
intent had been worked out to sell the equipment, but Iraq never
followed through with the money.
   A couple of weeks ago _ at the request of U.S. Rep. Jack Brooks,
D-Texas _ Roderick said he agreed to wait six months before
entering any agreement with Iraq and to consider offers from
domestic buyers.
   Roderick said Brooks told him that also would give Congress time
to consider whether to pass sanctions against Iraq for its alleged
poison gas attacks on Kurdish villages in the northern part of the
country during its war with Iran.
   That bill, which includes an amendment that could require USX to
obtain presidential approval before it sells any equipment to Iraq,
is pending in the Senate.
   Since that time, prospective buyers have looked at the plant but
no realistic offers have been made, Roderick said.
   ``We're not giving it away,'' he added.
   Roderick would not confirm reports the proposed sale of the
plant's equipment to Iraq was for $100 million, but he did say any
sale to a domestic buyer required more money because it also would
involve land.
   ``We've had some people who have looked at it, and I'm sure will
look at it again. We've had an offer on it before, which we have
said has been unacceptable to us, and whether somebody will make us
another offer, we can't tell,'' he said.
   A realistic offer, he said, is ``one that meets my price, all
cash.''
   Roderick denied claims that USX does not want to sell the plant
to a U.S. company because it fears further competition.
</TEXT>
