<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-Phones     10-20 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Phones,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Reports 16 Percent Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. reported
Thursday its third-quarter earnings rose 16.2 percent on the
strength of cost cutting and strong sales growth.
   Bell Atlantic Corp., one of the regional operating companies
spun off in the breakup of the Bell System nearly five years ago,
said its profit rose 6 percent.
   AT&T said its net income for the quarter ended Sept. 30 was $587
million, or 55 cents per share, up from $505 million, or 47 cents
per share, in the same period a year ago. Revenue rose 3.2 percent
to $8.75 billion from $8.47 billion.
   AT&T Chairman Robert E. Allen attributed the results to
``double-digit growth in product sales and an increase in
long-distance revenues.''
   Product sales for the quarter rose 12.4 percent and sales of
services increased by 2.2 percent. Rental revenues, which account
for less than 10 percent of total revenues, declined.
   Staff redeployment to sales positions and a hiring halt also
helped bolster the latest results, AT&T said. The hiring halt,
announced in July, reduced the work force by 4,000 to 311,000 as of
Sept. 30.
   For the first nine months of the year, earnings were up 8.2
percent to $1.67 billion, or $1.56 per share, compared with $1.55
billion, or $1.42 per share, in 1987. Revenue increased 3.4 percent
to $25.85 billion from $24.99 billion.
   AT&T noted its plan, announced earlier, to lower interstate
long-distance prices by $697 million on Dec. 1. It also said it was
stepping up its shift to a digital telephone network, which could
result in faster depreciation of old analog equipment and related
facilities.
   That process could affect future earnings since the equipment
and plant have book value of $4 billion to $5 billion, but AT&T
said it could not estimate the impact until further study was
completed later this year.
   Bell Atlantic said its net profit totaled $341 million, or $1.72
a share, in the quarter, compared with earnings of $321.8 million,
or $1.62 a share, a year earlier. Revenue increased to $2.61
billion from $2.59 billion.
   For the nine months, earnings increased 6 percent to $1.01
billion, or $5.12 a share, compared with $955.4 million, or $4.80 a
share, in 1987. Revenue was unchanged at $7.7 billion.
   Bell Atlantic, which is based in Philadelphia, attributed its
results to increased sales, efficiency and growth in the regional
economy. The company serves six Eastern states and the District of
Columbia.
   The company said its increased business was attributed to lower
rates for local and toll services and reduced charges for access to
long-distance companies.
</TEXT>
