<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Proxmire-PartingShot     10-20 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Proxmire-Parting Shot,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proxmire Urges Fed To Allow Banks Into Securities Despite Congress</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: St Germain, no period, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. William Proxmire, frustrated by his
unsuccessful fight to pass legislation restructuring the nation's
banking system, on Thursday called for regulators to act without
waiting for Congress.
   ``Congress has failed to do the job,'' the Wisconsin Democrat
said. ``There is not a scrap of real evidence that Congress will
act in the future. The time has come for the Federal Reserve Board
to act.''
   The statement by Proxmire, who is chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee, brought him in direct conflict with House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, and House Banking Committee Chairman Fernand J. St
Germain, D-R.I. Wright last week warned Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Alan Greenspan that changes in the banking system are
``rightfully a legislative concern.'' And, St Germain threatened to
use the next bank bill to reverse any regulatory changes between
now and then.
   In March, the Senate overwhelmingly passed legislation
permitting banks to underwrite securities, forbidden turf since
1933 when Congress enacted the Glass-Steagall Act, separating
banking from the securities business, as part of the wave of
Depression-era reforms.
   Proxmire has argued that technological developments since then
have allowed securities firms to poach on banks' traditional
business and have put banks at a competitive disadvantage.
   As a tribute to the banking chairman, the Senate named its bill
after Proxmire, who is retiring after 31 years in Congress.
   However, the legislation ran aground in the House last week
after St Germain and Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the
House Energy and Commerce Committee, failed to settle a
jurisdictional feud over which committee would have the greater say
over the bill.
   Proxmire had hoped to circumvent the House tangle by having the
Senate pass the bill again, in pieces, and send it back to the
House. But when his package came to the Senate floor on Wednesday,
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, D-N.Y., a supporter of the securities
industry and one of only two senators opposing the original bill,
blocked it.
   St Germain promised action on the bank bill ``before the snow
melts'' next year, but Proxmire said, ``That is not going to happen
this year, and it almost certainly won't happen next year, or for
many years to come.''
   Citing a Supreme Court decision in June that upheld the Fed's
power to permit bank underwriting of securities, Proxmire said,
``The Fed should move and move promptly in the future.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
