<2ND_LINE>AM-A&P-Delchamps,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A&P Increases Offer For Delchamps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Co. Inc.
sweetened its offer Thursday for Delchamps Inc. a Mobile-based
grocery chain, to $32 a share from $30 just days after both
companies took the takeover battle to federal court.
   ``The only comment we have is that our directors will meet in
the near future to review and evaluate their offer and we will
release our findings at that time,'' said Delchamps spokesman Joel
Swanson.
   Swanson said he did not know if the tender offer, worth $224
million, had an expiration date.
   The previous $30 a share offer, worth $210 million, was to
expire Nov. 4. A&P tried to buy Delchamps for $27 a share last
October, and for $24 a share in 1986.
   Each grocery store chain is suing the other in U.S. District
Court in Mobile as A&P seeks to re-establish itself on the Gulf
Coast and Delchamps tries to retain its regional domain.
   Delchamps filed a lawsuit Monday accusing A&P of failing to
disclose potential violations of antitrust laws in its takeover
proposal and devising a plan to financially cripple Delchamps even
if it fails to buy the company.
   A&P filed a counter lawsuit Wednesday against Delchamps seeking
a court order that would prevent the Mobile-based grocery chain
from blocking any threat to its control.
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Mobile, accuses
Delchamps of taking repeated steps to ``thwart serious
consideration'' of its proposed acquisition by A&P, a Maryland
corporation headquartered in New Jersey.
   A&P already owns 4.5 percent of Delchamps' 7 million shares of
stock, Swanson said.
   A&P accuses Delchamps in its lawsuit of misleading its
shareholders and the investment community.
   Unless Delchamps is prevented from taking further actions to
block any threat to its control, the suit claims, the Mobile
company may take other actions to block shareholders from fairly
considering A&P's offer.
   In a letter mailed to shareholders Monday, Delchamps Chairman
and President A.F. Delchamps Jr. said the Delchamps board
determined that A&P's offer is inadequate and it was in the
stockholders' best interest for the company to remain independent.
   Delchamps accused A&P of starting a fight to ``pick off the
company at a cheap price and proceed with its plan to achieve
dominance in the Gulf Coast retail stores market'' or at least to
``cause internal dissension and uncertainty,'' thereby weakening
Delchamps as a competitor.
   Delchamps stock has been trading at slightly more than $27 a
share since A&P began making the latest takeover attempt.
Delchamps, which operates 102 stores, had sales of about $700
million last year.
   A&P, which has 1,170 stores in the United States and Canada, had
sales of $9.6 billion in 1987.
