<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1853EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Getty-Texaco Bjt   10-20 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Getty-Texaco, Bjt,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Texaco-Getty Merger Stand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court ruled Thursday that
Attorney General John Van de Kamp could not use California
antitrust law to challenge the federally approved $10.1 billion
buyout of Getty Oil Co. by Texaco, the second largest merger in
U.S. history.
   The court ruled 4-3 that California's 1907 antitrust law does
not apply to mergers.
   Van de Kamp, who had contended the 1984 merger would eventually
lead to higher gasoline prices in the state by drying up oil
supplies to cut-rate independent refiners, said the setback would
not end his efforts to strengthen state antitrust enforcement.
   ``I believe that ... the Reagan administration's abdication of
antitrust enforcement made it important to use California law to
rein in mergers that threaten our state's economy,'' Van de Kamp
told reporters after the ruling.
   He said he would ask the Legislature to broaden state law to
expressly cover mergers, and would challenge other mergers under
federal antitrust law, such as his suit against the merger of the
Lucky and Alpha Beta supermarket chains. A federal judge in Los
Angeles has ordered the two markets to continue operating
separately, a ruling that is being appealed.
   Federal law allows challenges to mergers but has some drawbacks,
including a lack of authority, under current interpretations, to
require a merged company to sell off some of its holdings, Van de
Kamp said. At issue in the Lucky-Alpha Beta appeal is whether
federal law allows the attorney general to challenge a merger on
behalf of the people of the state.
   Texaco lawyer Laurence Popofsky praised Thursday's decision and
said suits like Van de Kamp's raise the question of ``whether it is
appropriate to have 50 state attorney generals second-guessing
federal authorities'' on mergers in interstate commerce.
   The Texaco-Getty case was the first attempt by a California
attorney general to use state antitrust law against a merger, and
is an example of efforts by Van de Kamp and his counterparts in
other states to fill the gap left by the Reagan administration's
relaxation of federal antitrust enforcement.
   Van de Kamp is also leading an eight-state lawsuit in federal
court claiming a conspiracy by insurance companies to cut back on
coverage to public agencies and drive up rates.
   In a dissent to Thursday's ruling, Justice Stanley Mosk _ who as
state attorney general from 1959 to 1964 was the first to enforce
California's antitrust laws extensively _ said that in light of
federal policy, ``vigorous enforcement of state antitrust laws is
plainly necessary.''
   The Reagan administration ``has all but ceased enforcing the
federal antitrust laws as they apply to mergers,'' Mosk said,
citing a study that said the Justice Department had contested only
26 out of over 10,000 merger applications between 1981 and 1986.
   The majority opinion by Chief Justice Malcolm Lucas did not
discuss whether a state could or should have its own policy on
mergers, ruling only that California's 81-year-old Cartwright Act
did not apply.
   The Texaco-Getty merger was second in size only to Chevron's
$13.2 billion acquisition of Gulf. More than half of Getty's
property consisted of California crude oil. It also owned a
632-mile San Joaquin Valley pipeline, the only one in the state
available to independent refiners.
   The Federal Trade Commission allowed the Texaco buyout in June
1984, requiring only that Texaco continue sales of former Getty oil
to independent refiners in California through April 1989. After
that, the FTC assumed, new supplies of offshore oil would be
available to the independents.
   After state courts refused to block the merger, Van de Kamp
maintained his suit, asking at least for additional protections for
the independents, such as extensions of their oil purchase
contracts beyond 1989 and guaranteed access to the pipeline. He
said the offshore supplies were uncertain and would be controlled
by major refiners who would not sell to independents.
   Sacramento Superior Court Judge Benjamin Diaz and a state
appeals court dismissed the suit, saying FTC approval of the
merger, after consideration of the issues raised by Van de Kamp,
precluded a state lawsuit. The Supreme Court majority reached the
same result by different reasoning.
   Lucas said mergers are not covered by the language of the
Cartwright Act, which prohibits any ``combination of capital'' that
might affect prices.
   The chief justice said the California law was modeled after
antitrust statutes in Michigan and Texas that had been interpreted
by courts in 1899 and 1904 to apply only to business dealings
between two companies that maintained separate identities, and not
to a purchase of one company by another.
   Mosk, in a dissent joined by Justices Marcu Kaufman and Allen
Broussard, said the language of the California law on
``combinations of capital'' clearly was broad enough to cover
mergers.
</TEXT>
