<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EasternShuttle     10-20 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Shuttle,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Flight Attendants Won't Join Effort To Block Shuttle Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines flight attendants won't join
other unions at Eastern in trying to block the $365 million sale of
the Northeast shuttle to developer Donald Trump, an attorney said
in court Thursday.
   Union attorney Arthur Luby said the Transport Workers union was
attempting to negotiate a contract with Trump for the 300 flight
attendants who work on the three-city shuttle, the only profitable
operation at Miami-based Eastern.
   Because of ``the very, very difficult working conditions,'' the
union ``couldn't in good conscience go and do something that forces
them to continue to work for Eastern when they might have a chance
to do something to improve their lot,'' Luby told U.S. District
Judge Barrington D. Parker at a hearing on the proposed deal.
   Two other unions at Eastern, the International Association of
Machinists and the Air Line Pilots Association, have announced
plans to seek a preliminary injunction to block the cash sale.
   The Machinists and pilots contend that the deal is part of an
attempt by Eastern's parent, Texas Air Corp., to undermine the
strength of organized labor. Texas Air says it needs to sell the
shuttle to get needed cash in order to save Eastern from financial
failure.
   The unions have sought to use the mandatory bargaining
provisions of the Railway Labor Act to stop Eastern from laying off
employees and cutting operations of the ailing carrier.
   Parker, whose order barring Eastern from laying off more than
3,000 employees was overturned last month by a federal appeals
court, gave the two unions until Nov. 21 to request a preliminary
injunction.
   Although he suggested that the unions might be ``baying at the
moon'' in light of the appeals court ruling on the layoffs, Parker
said he considered the shuttle deal a separate issue and that he is
prepared to hear arguments on it.
   The shuttle sale is scheduled to be completed by Dec. 15. Parker
indicated he would hold a hearing in the first two weeks of
December, a schedule that sets the stage for another eleventh-hour
court battle between Eastern and the unions.
</TEXT>
