<TEXT>
   The stock market climbed to new heights since
last year's crash with a rally Thursday that gathered momentum as
the session progressed.
   Analysts said a rash of takeover bids and buyout announcements
involving big-name companies in recent days played a large part in
reviving enthusiasm for stocks.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had fallen 22.58
points on Wednesday, jumped 43.92 to 2,181.19. That surpassed the
previous 1988 closing high of 2,159.85 reached on Tuesday.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
1,058 up, 416 down and 504 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 189.58 million
shares, against 186.35 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 221.43 million shares.
   The market was unsettled Wednesday by rising interest rates and
a rumor that a major newspaper was about to publish a story
potentially harmful to the presidential campaign of Vice President
Bush. The rumor was quickly denied, however.
   Analysts said buying was encouraged Thursday by abundant
takeover news and rumors, which create opportunities for quick
trading profits.
   In the newest development on that front, RJR Nabisco soared 21]
to 77\ on word that a management group may propose to buy out the
company for about $75 a share.
   That prompted buying of such other tobacco stocks as American
Brands, up 4} at 59, and Philip Morris, up 5 at 99. Philip Morris
is itself in the process of going after Kraft, which traded
Thursday at 90\, down [.
   At the same time, market participants were looking ahead to
Friday's scheduled report from the government on the consumer price
index for September.
   Any sign of new upward pressure on inflation would increase
expectations of further credit-tightening by the Federal Reserve,
but concern on that score seemed to ebb Thursday.
   American Telephone & Telegraph rose | to 27{ in active trading.
The company reported third-quarter earnings of 55 cents a share, up
from 47 cents in the comparable period last year.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up ~ at 45{;
International Business Machines, up 2{ at 124~; General Electric,
up ~ at 45, and Union Carbide, up 1} at 27\.
   Pittston picked up 1\ to 15} on higher quarterly profits.
   Quantum, which said it planned to buy back 2 million of its
shares through a tender offer, gained 1] to 13| in the
over-the-counter market.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $45.27 billion, or
1.65 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
2.83 to 159.01.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 7.26 to 326.07, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 5.91 to 282.88.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
gained 2.86 to 388.62. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 306.37, up 1.89.
