<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Amoco,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amoco Reports 34 Percent Rise in Third-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amoco Corp. said Thursday its third-quarter
profit jumped 34 percent due mainly to strong performance in
refining, marketing and transportation operations.
   For the third quarter, Amoco had after-tax profits of $552
million, or $2.15 per share, up from $412 million, or $1.60 a
share, in the year-ago period. Revenue totaled $5.9 billion in
1988, compared with $5.8 billion reported in 1987, the company said.
   ``Increased customer demand has had a twofold effect on
refining, marketing and transportation operations,'' said Richard
M. Morrow, chairman and chief executive officer.
   ``First, it has resulted in higher sales volumes, which has
enabled us to run our refineries at higher utilization rates,'' he
said in a statement. ``The increased demand has also caused
industry refining tightness which resulted in strong product
margins.
   ``Many of these same factors also favorably impacted chemical
operations, allowing us to maintain near-record earnings from these
activities.''
   Earnings for the first nine months of 1988 totaled $1.69
million, or $6.56 a share, up 72 percent from $983 million, or
$3.84 a share, in the first nine months of 1987, Amoco said.
   Year-to-date revenue increased 7 percent, to $17.9 billion,
compared with $16.7 billion for the first nine months of 1987, the
company said.
</TEXT>
