<HEAD>Sweetened Takeover Try Rejected by Manufacturer</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 1st graf to RESTORE dropped word `from,' adds new 5th
graf to UPDATE with court lifting injunction; uppicks 5th graf pvs:
Interco ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL LeBAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of furniture and apparel maker
Interco Inc. on Thursday rejected a sweetened, $2.7 billion tender
offer from an investment group and boosted the value of the
company's own restructuring plan.
   Cardinal Acquisition Corp., headed by brothers Steven M. and
Mitchell P. Rales of Washington, D.C., had increased its hostile
offer from $70 a share to $74 on Monday. The tender offer was
extended until 11 p.m. Oct. 31.
   ``There's probably more to come,'' Laurence C. Day, a Newhard
Cook analyst, said of the bid by the Raleses. ``They've indicated
that. They've always indicated that all along.''
   Interco's financial advisers, Wasserstein, Perella & Co.,
recommended rejection of Cardinal's latest offer, labeling it
inadequate.
   Separately, Cardinal said in a release that a federal appeals
court lifted an injunction against the tender offer. The ruling, by
the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit in Philadelphia,
allows Cardinal to purchase Interco shares.
   Interco, for which Cardinal originally bid $64 in July, rose 62{
cents to $71.12{ a share in trading on the New York Stock Exchange
Thursday.
   ``The stock wouldn't be where it is if it weren't for the
takeover offer,'' First Boston industry analyst Margaret Gilliam
said in New York City. ``If the offer is increased, I think it will
be by only small increments from here on out.''
   Interco also announced that as a part of a restructuring and
recapitalization plan outlined last month it has declared an
additional special dividend totaling $30.80 per share in cash and
securities.
   ``With today's declaration, we have now declared $55.80 in
special dividends as part of our restructuring program,'' said
Harvey Saligman, board chairman and chief executive officer.
   Saligman said Interco also is considering an increase in the
amount of preferred securities to be issued in the restructuring.
   ``From Interco's point, they're buying time _ perhaps to sell
some assets. They're also creating confusion,'' analyst Day said of
the special dividend. ``There's a limit somewhere. It's hard at
this point to really see what the total value of the (Interco)
package would be.''
   Cardinal has been blocked at least temporarily by a federal
appeals court from completing its tender offer pending further
review in Delaware of an Interco court challenge.
   Interco has alleged that Cardinal failed to divulge that Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc., the investment firm, is a co-bidder in the
takeover attempt. Interco also contends the tender offer is
leveraged so high it violates federal securities laws.
   Saligman said Interco's board considers its restructuring,
combining continued shareholder participation in the company with
the enhancement of the special dividends, superior to Cardinal's
tender offer.
   The Raleses own 8.7 percent of Interco's stock. The latest
Cardinal offer is subject to 75 percent participation among
Interco's 36.2 million shares outstanding and the withdrawal of a
``poison pill'' shareholders rights plan.
   Interco manufactures men's and women's apparel, footwear,
furniture ahd home furnishings. Company sales for the first half of
the current fiscal year were $1.27 billion, up 3 percent from 1987.
</TEXT>
