<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OPEC 2ndLd-Writethru   10-20 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Refuses Production Parity for Iraq as OPEC Ministers Meet</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to correct name of Iraqi oil minister; picks up
4th graf pvs, ``Indonesia's Oil ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh
said Thursday Iran would not accept production parity with Iraq, a
goal sought by the majority of OPEC oil ministers who met in the
Spanish capital to discuss how to stem excess output by cartel
members.
   Following the 90-minute session at the Algerian Embassy of the
price and long-term strategy committees of the Organization of
Petroleum-Exporting Countries, spokesman James Audu said the
organization's secretary general Subroto would hold a news
conference Friday morning prior to beginning a second meeting.
   After the meeting broke up, Iraq's Oil Minister Issam
Abdul-Raheem Al-Chalabi said it was too early for him to comment on
his country's position on a production sharing agreement.
   Indonesia's Oil Minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita told reporters
there were ``some miles to go'' before a production agreement could
be reached but added that all 13 OPEC members were committeed to
finding a solution to ``current discord.''
   Current OPEC production is estimated at around 20 million to 21
million barrels a day, far above the cartel's official ceiling of
15.06 million barrels a day.
   Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates have proposed
17.4 million barrels a day, including Iraq's share, as a more
realistic ceiling.
   Iraq, now outside the quota system, has demanded a quota equal
to that of Iran, at 2.369 million barrels a day.
   Analysts report that Iraq has been pumping at least 2.6 million
barrels of crude a day, an amount that could rise to 3.7 million
barrels in mid-1989 with the completion of a a new pipeline through
Saudi Arabia to the Red Sea.
   Iran has been pumping 2.5 million barrels a day, the analysts
say.
   Oil ministers from Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Nigeria all said
Thursday they would only accept a new production pact if it
included Iraq.
   But Aqazadeh, who is meeting with his Iraqi counterpart
Al-Chalabi for the first time in an OPEC setting since an August
cease-fire ended the eight-year Gulf War, said Iran would not
accept an agreement that gave Iraq production parity. He added he
had no alternative proposals to solve the long-standing problem.
   Both Iran and Iraq want to pump and sell as much oil as possible
to increase revenue to rebuild their war-battered nations.
   Venezuelan Oil Minister Julio Cesar Gil said Thursday if OPEC
nations don't comply with their production quotas under any new
agreement, the cartel would simply find itself facing the same oil
glut that has been forcing prices down in the past months.
   An excess of oil on international markets has sent prices
tumbling to below $12 a barrel in recent weeks, far below the OPEC
target of $18 a barrel.
   The OPEC price committee includes oil ministers from Algeria,
Saudi Arabia, Nigeria, Indonesia and Venezuela.
   Ministers from Iraq, Iran, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela
sit on the long-term strategy committee.
   The remaining OPEC members are Ecuador, Gabon, Libya, Qatar and
the United Arab Emirates.
   The price committee met Sept. 25-26 in Madrid without resolving
the production problem. All 13 OPEC members are to meet in Vienna
in November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881020-0324 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CaterpillarTalks     10-20 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Caterpillar Talks,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW and Caterpillar Reach Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers union and
Caterpillar Inc. have reached a contract accord on all issues
except those to be addressed by the union at the local level, chief
UAW negotiator Bill Casstevens said late Thursday.
   Casstevens said the union will strike, however, unless
Caterpillar meets with UAW locals and settles their issues by 11
p.m. Friday.
   ``The issues that remain that separate us are issues that we say
are local in nature,'' said Casstevens, secretary-treasurer of the
UAW International. ``The company disagrees with us.''
   Casstevens said the locals would be authorized to ``take
whatever action they deemed necessary,'' including a strike, if the
deadline was not met.
   A spokesman for Caterpillar was not immediately available for
comment.
   Casstevens confirmed that one of the main issues still
separating the two sides was contract provisions concerning special
job classifications, which restrict workers from transferring
between jobs within the company.
   ``We are saying we have an understanding on the central items
that we could recommend to the membership. The items that separate
us are items that we say are local in nature and have to be
resolved on the local table,'' Casstevens said.
   He said he hoped the company would resume talks on the local
level.
   ``We're sending them back to the local table,'' Casstevens said.
``We hope they'll talk. You can't resolve it without doing that.''
   The local unions that reportedly have not reached local
agreements with the company include East Peoria, Aurora and
Decatur, Ill.
   Jerry Brown, bargaining chairman of Local 974 of Peoria, said
the local was prepared to strike. He said it had given the company
a proposal Tuesday and was waiting for a response.
   Brown said the union would not to grant an extension on its
local talks. He said the union had considered the economic
consequences of staging a walkout, but added that the union might
not have a choice.
   ``We don't take a strike lightly and we didn't come down here to
bargain for a strike, but we're not going to roll over and play
dead either,'' he said.
   Local members consider the job classification issue to be
important because it went against the basic idea of a senority
system and would allow some workers to be laid off before workers
with less senority, Brown said.
   He didnt rule out the possibility of a settlement before the
deadline and again urged the membership to continue reporting for
work until instructed otherwise.
</TEXT>
