<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MajorFraud     10-20 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Major Fraud,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Major Fraud Penalties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved and sent to the president's
desk Thursday legislation calling for 10-year prison sentences and
$10 million fines for major government procurement fraud.
   ``Procurement fraud costs our country hundreds of millions of
dollars a year,'' Rep. William J. Hughes, D-N.J., said as the bill
passed on a voice vote.
   The measure, which establishes a new crime of major fraud,
applies throughout the government but is designed to respond to
recent disclosures of widespread cheating among defense contractors
in military procurement.
   ``It's an insult to the taxpayers and to the many honest people
who do business with the government that the crooked contractors
often avoid prosecution and their punishment is rarely commensurate
with the crime,'' Hughes said.
   The House already had passed the measure and merely agreed to
amendments added by the Senate before sending it on to the
president for his signature. Approval came with no controversy.
   Under the bill, the maximum sentence for major fraud would be
set at 10 years in prison.
   Fines under the measure would be similar to current ones for
fraud against the government. They vary depending on the amount of
the loss. In especially flagrant cases, however, courts would have
the option of imposing penalties of up to $10 million under the
bill.
   A statute of limitations of seven years would be established
under the measure in contrast to the normal one of five years.
So-called whistle-blower protections would be provided to those who
draw attention to procurement fraud.
   Among other things, the Senate amendments would authorize $8
million over four years for the hiring of additional prosecutors to
work on procurement fraud. They also deleted a House feature that
would have provided $250,000 rewards for information leading to
conviction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
