<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FAA-Warning 2ndLd-Writethru   10-20 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FAA-Warning, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airlines Ordered to Check Takeoff Alarms on 1,800 Planes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 pvs, bgng: ``The FAA ...'' to clarify problem
statistics and identify Northwest as airline in Detroit crash.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration, after
finding ``a significant number'' of takeoff alarm systems not
working properly, on Thursday ordered the warning devices tested on
nearly 1,800 Boeing 727 and Boeing 737 jetliners.
   The action, prompted in part by two fatal airline crashes,
requires the tests to be conducted within 200 flight hours and
repeated every 200 hours to make certain that pilots are warned if
their planes are not properly configured to take off.
   FAA spokesman John Leyden said the inspections, which are likely
to take about three hours, are not expected to disrupt the
airlines' normal operating schedules since they likely will be
conducted during routine maintenance.
   The takeoff alarms on the two model Boeing planes _ two of the
most widely used jet aircraft in commercial operation _ sound a
horn if the crew has forgotten to set, or set improperly, a variety
of control and operational devices in the cockpit.
   The FAA said a one-time check last month of alarms on nearly
1,186 Boeing 727s revealed that the alarms either were improperly
working or failed altogether on 35 aircraft. Twer and Southwest Airlines
are among the major users of
Boeing 737s.
</TEXT>
