<DOCNO> AP881020-0330 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 2226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     10-20 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony Continues in Polaroid Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. contacted a major
investment bank to discuss a possible takeover of Polaroid Corp.
before a planned meeting between the two companies, a Shamrock
adviser testified Thursday.
   The acquisitions manager for Wertheim Schroder & Co. said he was
aware that Shamrock President Stanley P. Gold had approached Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. before a scheduled mid-July meeting that was
abruptly canceled by Polaroid.
   Ilan Kaufthal, a Wertheim Schroder managing director,
contradicted testimony Monday by Gold, who said he had contacted
several smaller banks but not Drexel, a major player in financing
corporate takeovers.
   ``I knew that Gold and Drexel were discussing financing if Gold
proceeded on the buyout'' of Polaroid, Kaufthal said, adding the
talks were held sometime between January and June.
   Burbank, Calif.-based Shamrock, controlled by the Roy E. Disney
family, is suing Polaroid in Delaware Chancery Court in an effort
to invalidate Polaroid's employee stock ownership plan that would
all but block a takeover.
   On the first day of the trial Wednesday, Gold said he had not
talked with Drexel before July 12, when Polaroid unveiled the
10-million-share, $300-million stock plan and one day before the
meeting between the two companies.
   One week later, Shamrock made its first $40-a-share bid for
Polaroid. Shamrock contends Polaroid created the stock plan to
thwart an acquisition.
   Gold did say he had talked with Wells Fargo Bank and Bank of
Nova Scotia on whether they would be interested in financing the
venture if Shamrock proceeded with the takeover.
   Shamrock rested its case Wednesday in Chancery Court before Vice
Chancellor Carolyn Berger. Polaroid was expected to begin calling
witnesses Friday. I. MacAllister Booth, Polaroid's chief executive
officer, is among those expected to testify.
   The stock ownership plan puts 14 percent of Polaroid stock in
the hands of employees. Under Delaware's takeover law, a hostile
bidder must acquire more than 85 percent of a target's outstanding
shares for control.
   Cambridge, Mass.-based Polaroid is incorporated in Delaware.
   Shamrock was rejected in its unsolicited bid before making a
hostile offer of $42 a share last month that values Polaroid at
about $2.6 billion. Polaroid has said the offr was too low and
advised stockholders to reject it.
   Kaufthal said Shamrock had agreed to conditions set by Polaroid
for the July 13 meeting, including that they not reach the 5
percent stock ownership threshold required for federal disclosure
or take any action requiring disclosure.
   After the meeting was canceled, Kaufthal testified that he
called a Polaroid executive and said he was ``very disappointed on
a personal and an ethical basis'' and told him ``he had lied to me
and my client.''
   On Monday, Gold testified that Wertheim Schroder proposed trying
to selling all of Polaroid's manufacturing facilities to Eastman
Kodak Co. and negotiate a settlement of Polaroid's $5.7 billion
patent infringement judgment against Kodak.
   The investment banker also proposed to slash Polaroid's research
and development expenditures by more than 50 percent and reduce its
marketing and administration staff from 3,000 to under 2,000.
   Wertheim suggested that Shamrock could realize as much as a 49
percent return on a $350 million equity investment if the entire
company was sold in 1992, according to the testimony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
